<1ST_LINE>u w AM-US-Egypt 1stLd-Writethru a0694 06-27 0280</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Egypt, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0694,240</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Officials Discuss Smuggling Charges</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: INSERTS 3 grafs after 4th graf bgng, `Federal authorities,'
to UPDATE with report that Egypt recalled two officers, including
Mohammed, to Cairo</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The State Department on Monday called for full
cooperation from Egypt in an investigation into an alleged scheme
to illegally export U.S. technology to the Middle Eastern country.
   An Egyptian army colonel stationed in Washington was one of five
people charged in the case last Friday.
   ``We take violations of our laws very seriously,'' Charles E.
Redman, the State Department spokesman, said.
   Federal authorities alleged a conspiracy to export the chemical
carbon-carbon, which is used to make missile nose cones and stealth
aircraft less visible to radar. Lt. Col. Mohammed Abdella Mohammed,
who was assigned to the Egyptian embassy in Washington, was
arrested in Baltimore and then released after claiming diplomatic
immunity.
   The Washington Post reported in Tuesday's editions that Mohammed
and another Egyptian military procurement official, Adm. Abdel
Rahim Elgohary, had been called home by Egypt in the wake of the
charges and that the two returned to Cairo last weekend.
   Citing an Egyptian source it did not identify, the Post said the
two would help authorities in Cairo ``carry out the necessary
investigation.'' Although Elgohary was not charged in the case, the
Customs Service mentioned him in an affidavit as having played a
role.
   It was not immediately known if the two would return to the
United States, the newspaper said.
   Redman said U.S. diplomats had discussed the case with Egyptian
officials since last Friday. ``We expect full cooperation,'' he
said.
   Otherwise, the spokesman declined comment on the substance of
the case.
</TEXT>
