<FILEID>AP-NR-06-27-88 0006EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Times-Mirror-Poll Bjt   06-27 0763</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Times-Mirror-Poll, Bjt,720</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hold For Release At 10 a.m. EDT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Dukakis ``A Blank Page'' With Voters</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EVANS WITT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   To an uncertain and divided electorate,
Michael Dukakis is ``a blank page'' whose lead over George Bush is
grounded in negative feelings about the Republican vice president,
rather than positive attitudes toward the Democratic nominee-to-be,
according to a survey released today.
   The national poll did find Democrats remarkably united behind
Dukakis at this point, although there are weaknesses in the
coalition that Bush could exploit to build his chances for a fall
victory.
   Much of Dukakis' strength comes from voters worried about the
course of the nation.
   ``Democrats are seen as the party of change. Bush is not,'' said
Andrew Kohut, president of the Gallup Organization, which conducted
the poll for the Times-Mirror Corp.
   The survey, the latest in a series for the media company, is
based on interviews with 3,021 adults in person from May 13-22. The
margin of error was two percentage points.
   The horse-race numbers for the poll gave Dukakis 53 percent of
the registered voters and Bush 40 percent. Seven percent were
undecided.
   Overall, Dukakis drew a favorable response from 66 percent of
the sample, while 22 percent rated him unfavorably. Bush got 51
percent positive marks and 42 percent negative.
   But the Dukakis numbers are the result of a ``vague, mildly
positive image,'' the poll analysis said, pointing out that
relatively few voters could rate Dukakis on a range of specific
characteristics. Only 29 percent said he ``can get things done''
while 33 percent said he is well-informed.
   Bush's image is a bit clearer, since he has been on the national
scene longer, but he is stuck with ``some strong negatives and
relatively few positives,'' the analysis said.
   ``Dukakis is still a blank page to most people,'' Kohut said,
adding that ``neither man has a clearly drawn image.''
   Asked in the poll if they were voting more for their candidate
or against his opponent, Bush backers were mostly positive. Of his
40 percent support, 26 percentage points were based on pro-Bush
sentiments and 11 percent anti-Dukakis. Three percent were not sure.
   But half of Dukakis' supporters took a negative stance. Of
Dukakis' 53 percent, only 22 percentage points were pro-Dukakis; 26
percent were anti-Bush; and the rest were not sure.
   The Times-Mirror surveys over the past year have divided the
public into 11 groups based on their values and partisan
affiliation.
   Dukakis is doing well in part because he is drawing strong
support in three of the four usually Democratic groups _ 80 percent
or better. In fact, the poll said that Democrats are slightly more
loyal to Dukakis at this point than Republicans are to Bush _ a
dramatic change from the high rates of Democratic defection in
recent decades at the presidential level.
   Bush has solid backing in the two key GOP groups.
   But the vice president has not won the strong support Ronald
Reagan had in a group the poll calls the ``Disaffecteds,'' those
who are pessimistic and deeply suspicious of both big government
and big business.
   There are, however, weaknesses in the Democratic coalition.
   One conservative segment _ called ``God and Country Democrats''
_ and a swing group called ``Seculars'' are giving about a quarter
of their support to Bush, despite the groups' natural Democratic
leanings.
   Bush's poor showing, in the face of the relative economic
prosperity of the country under a Reagan-Bush administration, seems
to spring from long-term trends worrying the public.
   For example, 54 percent think they will be personally better off
next year, while only 10 percent say their financial situation will
deteriorate.
   And 24 percent think the national economy will improve in the
next year, while 46 percent believe there will be little change.
Twenty percent are pessimistic.
   In sharp contrast to such optimism, only 41 percent of the
public was satisfied with ``the way things are going'' in the
country, while 54 percent were dissatisfied.
   And 37 percent said is likely or certain that the U.S. economy
could collapse in the next 10 years because of foreign competition.
   With such pessimism after seven years of GOP control of the
White House, it should not be surprising that the Democrats are
perceived as the party most likely to bring about changes.
   Forty-three percent of those questioned said the Democratic
Party ``can bring about the kinds of changes the country needs,''
with only 27 percent labeling the GOP that way. Nine percent said
both parties, 11 percent said neither and 10 percent were not sure.
</TEXT>
