<1ST_LINE>r p PM-PlatformHighlights     06-27 0413</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Platform Highlights,390</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Highlights Of Democrats' Proposed Platform</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Democrats-Platform</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here are highlights from the proposed platform
approved Saturday night by the Democratic Platform Committee.
   ECONOMY _ Says ``all Americans have a fundamental right to
economic security in a stronger, surer national economy,''
including an indexed minimum wage, ``an adequate Social Security
System safeguarded against emasculation and privatization'' and
advance notice of plant closings.
   DEFENSE _ Calls for ``more stable defense budgets'' and a
commitment by U.S. allies ``to assume a greater share of the
costs'' of defending liberty. Criticizes ``wasting money on
duplicative and dubious new weapons instead of investing more in
readiness and mobility.''
   ARMS TALKS _ Calls for following up the Intermediate-range
Nuclear Forces Treaty ``with mutual, verifiable and enforceable
agreements that will make significant reductions in strategic
weapons.''
   WOMEN _ Seeks an Equal Rights Amendment to the Constitution;
endorses ``freedom of reproductive choice'' without mentioning
abortion, and pledges the party to ``full and equal access of women
and minorities to elective office.''
   CHILD CARE _ Pledges significant increases in aid for low- and
middle-income families.
   EDUCATION _ Says ``the education of our citizens, from Head
Start to institutions of higher learning, deserves our highest
priority.'' Promises to invest in a National Teacher Corps to
recruit teachers through scholarships and to reverse Reagan
administration aid cuts. Also promises more support for bilingual
education and black colleges.
   DRUGS _ Calls for appointment of a national drug czar, denounces
suggestions to legalize illicit drugs.
   CRIME _ Would impose a federal ban on ``cop-killer'' bullets.
   SOUTH AFRICA _ Denounces that nation's apartheid regime as ``a
terrorist state'' and pledges tougher sanctions.
   MIDDLE EAST _ Calls for maintaining the special relationship
with Israel while seeking negotiations under the Camp David Accords
to bring peace to Israel and its neighbors.
   VOTING RIGHTS _ Supports same-day and mail-in voter registration
and opposes ``any dilution of the one-person, one-vote principle.''
Backs statehood for the District of Columbia.
   VOLUNTEERS _ Encourages voluntary national service.
   HOUSING _ Calls homelessness ``a national shame'' and calls for
expanding the supply of affordable housing and help for first-time
home buyers.
   CIVIL RIGHTS _ Supports equal access to government services,
jobs, housing, business and education for all ``regardless of race,
sex, national origin, religion, age, handicapping conditions or
sexual orientation.''
   AIDS _ Promises increased research, education and prevention
efforts as well as ``respect for the civil rights of those
suffering from AIDS or testing positive for the HIV antibody.''
</TEXT>
