<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Bush     06-27 0592</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bush,580</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Faults Congress in Drug War</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLUMBUS, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vice President George Bush says the
nation's prison capacity should be dramatically expanded as part of
a get-tough attitude toward drug dealers.
   Bush, who is slated to get the Republican presidential
nomination this summer, also claimed that Congress has failed to
support law enforcement against drugs.
   A representative of Democrat Michael Dukakis, meanwhile, laid
the blame at the door of Bush and the Reagan administration.
   The opposing assertions by Bush and Sen. Dennis DeConcini,
D-Ariz., were made Sunday at a national conference of the Fraternal
Order of Police.
   Focusing on what has become a major issue in this year's
presidential campaign, Bush and DeConcini each pointed the finger
for letting the drug situation escalate out of control.
   On the prison issue, ``The single most important thing Congress
could do in the war on drugs is alleviate the shortage of state
prison space, responsible for the premature release of countless
criminals,'' Bush told the audience of about 200.
   He said the country is spending ``anywhere from $2 billion to $5
billion a year on domestic military bases we don't need any more''
and that those could be converted to minimum-security prisons.
   He said at a subsequent news conference that he did not have a
list of bases in mind but that a review of such facilities should
be conducted and that no state should be exempt.
   ``Congress is full of rhetorical heroes on the issue of drugs,
but when it comes to law enforcement, some of them go AWOL,'' Bush
claimed, using the military jargon for absent without leave.
   He said Congress reduced the administration's Coast Guard budget
request last year by $72 million, and by $864 million over four
years.
   But DeConcini said that was ``just a bogus argument.''
   He said it was the administration that did the cutting and
Congress that restored drug-fighting dollars. He said President
Reagan's 1988 budget sought a $900 million cut in anti-drug funds,
including money for the Coast Guard and Border Patrol, and a 60
percent cut in drug prevention and education programs.
   DeConcini said Congress restored 70 percent of the money.
   DeConcini also attacked Bush's performance as head of the
National Narcotics Border Interdiction System, which he said was
``an organization of half-empty offices lacking organization'' that
failed in its drug-fighting goals.
   DeConcini said he was addressing the group as a surrogate for
Dukakis, who has sewn up the Democratic presidential nomination and
is spending a few days vacationing in Nantucket, Mass.
   In his speech, Bush called for mandatory testing of ``anyone
responsible for the public safety,'' recriminalization of drug
possession in states where it has been decriminalized, and the
death penalty for drug kingpins and those who commit drug-related
murders.
   He also urged continuation of the ``zero tolerance'' policy
aimed at users of drugs in even small amounts, and drug education
programs for youth and in the work place.
   At his news conference, Bush was asked about a New York Times
report that his aides are focusing on Sen. Bob Dole of Kansas as
the leading candidate to become Bush's running mate.
   ``Nobody is authorized to speak in my behalf,'' Bush said,
adding he does not yet have ``a long list or a short list.''
   Dole, while campaigning for Bush on Saturday in Oregon,
indicated the two have not had a discussion about his joining the
ticket.
   In choosing a running mate, Bush said he would look for ``a
philosophical compatibility and a temperamental compatibility.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
