<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Jazz     06-27 0450</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Jazz,0469</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Orchestra Plays 4 Ellington Tone Poems</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY10</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Duke Ellington liked to compose tone poems, as
well as short jazz tunes, and the American Composers Orchestra
performed four of those longer work at Carnegie Hall in what was
billed as the first all-Ellington symphonic concert.
   The evening was conducted by Maurice Peress. She worked with
Ellington on several projects including in 1969 making a symphonic
suite from Duke's 1943 ``Black, Brown and Beige.''
   The symphonic suite includes ``Work Song,'' with its crashing
sounds and optimism; ``Come Sunday,'' with the melody played by the
orchestra's first cellist, then with delicate shading by alto
saxophonist Frank Wess, and ``Light,'' which has a big finish _ Jon
Faddis' trumpet was heard _ as light really streams in.
   The Sunday night concert began with ``Les Trois Rois Noirs''
(``The Three Black Kings''), which Ellington was working on, for
the Dance Theater of Harlem, when he died in 1974. His son, Mercer
Ellington, composed it with him and finished it and Luther
Henderson orchestrated it for jazz band and orchestra.
   ``King Solomon'' is roiling and majestic. The theme for the
black King of the Magi was played in mellow fashion by saxophonist
Jimmy Heath. The final section eulogized Martin Luther King and
included a swinging march.
   All four of the evening's tone poems concern black history and
life. All the music combines seriousness, dignity, the lightening
of jazz and a very American-sounding optimism.
   We might have preferred performance by an ensemble with less
``sweetening'' by a huge string section and more muscle from the
brass. Guest musicians who did add fiber were bassist Ron Carter,
one-time Basie Band drummer Butch Miles, pianist Roy Glover and
saxophonists Joe Temperley, Bill Easley and Walt Weiskopf.
   Sir Roland Hanna had the pianistic style right for the piano
concerto, ``New World A-Comin','' which Ellington composed in 1943
and revised for his First Sacred Concert.
   ``Harlem,'' commissioned by the NBC Symphony in 1950, ended the
concert. Ellington undoubtedly had a detailed program in his head
when he composed ``Harlem,'' and it's fun to hear the melodies and
decide when Duke had the populace partying or somebody feeling blue.
   After intermission, the composer's sister, Ruth Ellington
Boatwright, presented an original manuscript page of ``New World
A-Comin''' to Betty Allen, a Carnegie Hall board member. The page
will hang in the composers gallery of the Carnegie Hall archives,
Miss Allen said.
   The American Composers Orchestra, which has an annual concert
series in New York, specializes in American symphonic music.
   The evening was an event of the JVC Jazz Festival and the First
New York International Festival of the Arts.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
