<FILEID>AP-NR-06-27-88 0213EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-PollMethod     06-27 0556</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Poll Method,0581</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>With PM-Poll-Protests, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   This Media General-Associated Press poll is
based on telephone interviews April 29-May 8 with 1,204 adults in
the continental United States. The phone numbers were selected
randomly by computer and interviews were conducted with the adult
who had the most recent birthday.
   The results were weighted to adjust for variations in the
sample. The poll has a 3-point margin of error, meaning the results
theoretically would be within 3 points of the same 19 times out of
20 if every adult American were asked the same questions. The error
margin is larger for subgroups _ 5 points for conservatives, for
example.
   There are other sources of potential error in polls, including
the wording and order of questions. These are the questions and
responses in this poll:
   1. The anti-war protests of the 1960s reached a peak in the
summer of 1968. Do you think the anti-war protests of the 1960s
influenced U.S. policy in Vietnam?
   Yes: 54 percent. No: 26 percent. Don't know or no answer: 20
percent.
   1a. (if yes on question 1) Do you think the anti-war protests
prolonged U.S. involvement in the Vietnam War, or shortened U.S.
involvement in the war?
   Prolonged: 23 percent. Shortened: 59 percent. Neither: 9
percent. Don't know or no answer: 9 percent.
   1b. (If yes on question 1) Do you think the anti-war protests
prevented the U.S. from winning the war?
   Yes: 30 percent. No: 58 percent. DK-NA: 12 percent.
   2. Do you think the anti-war protests of the 1960s have had a
lasting effect on U.S. foreign policy?
   Yes: 57 percent. No: 27 percent. DK-NA: 16 percent.
   2a. (If yes on question 2) Overall, do you think that effect has
been positive or negative?
   Positive: 47 percent. Negative: 45 percent. DK-NA: 8 percent.
   3. Do you think the anti-war protests of the 1960s have had a
lasting effect on American society?
   Yes: 74 percent. No: 16 percent. DK-NA: 11 percent.
   3a. (If yes to question 3) Overall, do you think that effect has
been positive or negative?
   Positive: 51 percent. Negative: 41 percent. DK-NA: 8 percent.
   4. Compared to 20 years ago, are you generally more liberal now,
more conservative, or about the same?
   Liberal: 17 percent. Conservative: 29 percent. Same: 37 percent.
Does not apply: 16 percent. DK-NA: 2 percent.
   5. What about American society in general _ do you think it is
more liberal now than it was 20 years ago, more conservative, or
about the same?
   Liberal: 52 percent. Conservative: 28 percent. Same: 15 percent.
DK-NA: 6 percent.
   6. Please tell me if you agree or disagree with these statements:
   a. Young people were more interested in changing society 20
years ago than they are now. Agree: 62 percent. Disagree: 32
percent. DK-NA: 6 percent.
   b. Young people were more idealistic 20 years ago than they are
now. Agree: 65 percent. Disagree: 29 percent. DK-NA: 7 percent.
   c. Young people are more selfish now than they were 20 years
ago. Agree: 71 percent. Disagree: 23 percent. DK-NA: 6 percent.
   d. Young people are more apathetic now than they were 20 years
ago. Agree: 57 percent. Disagree: 30 percent. DK-NA: 14 percent.
   e. Young people are more realistic now than they were 20 years
ago. Agree: 54 percent. Disagree: 36 percent. DK-NA: 11 percent.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
