<HEAD>Mexican, U.S. Firefighters Battle Shopping Center Blaze</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TIJUANA, Mexico (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fire crews from both sides of the border
Sunday night battled a major blaze that heavily damaged a shopping
center injured seven Mexican firefighters before being brought
under control.
   The blaze was under control by 10 p.m., officials said.
   The blaze, visible from San Diego, began in a commercial
district about 6:30 p.m., destroying 15 to 16 buildings, including
clothing stores and other businesses, said Tijuana firefighter
Ruben Garcia.
   Seven firefighters suffered smoke inhalation while battling the
blaze and were sent to hospitals, Garcia said. Their conditions
were not immediately available.
   San Diego fire Capt. Ralph Haynes said the blaze had spread over
a two-block area and damaged a bank and an apartment complex.
   About 120 Mexican firefighters were sent to the scene, and 1{
hours later, six San Diego firefighters were dispatched, Haynes
said.
   Fire investigators had not determined the cause of the fire.
There were no damage estimates.
