<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Freddie'sPal Bjt   06-27 0662</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Freddie's Pal, Bjt,0684</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Suburban Woman Reaches Out To Death-Row Inmate</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto CD1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By M.R. KROPKO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNIVERSITY HEIGHTS, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   For a few days that tried her
soul, Kate Uhlir left her suburban Cleveland routine to witness
life in a Georgia prison and to share what was supposed to be a
death-row inmate's final hours.
   On June 16, Freddie Davis, Ms. Uhlir's longtime pen pal, was
spared from the electric chair, at least for 90 days. The Georgia
Board of Pardons and Paroles suspended his execution six hours
before it was to be carried out.
   ``I sort of felt like a soldier on an island with a bow and
arrow to defend the island and there were tanks coming at me,'' Ms.
Uhlir recalled.
   She was in a waiting area outside the prison with some of Davis'
family and friends when the small group of his supporters learned
his execution had been delayed.
   ``We jumped up and down and screamed,'' Ms. Uhlir said.
``Finally, we burst into tears. ... I put my arms around his
mother. Her whole body just shook ... It was something really
extraordinary.''
   The 49-year-old office manager and mother of six first wrote
Davis in 1980 after a friend involved in a Cincinnati-based program
called Prison Pen Pals gave her his name and address. She said she
knew nothing about him or his crime.
   Except for a period in 1986, when Ms. Uhlir was struggling with
a personal problem, she and Davis have written each other at least
once a month.
   She learned that Davis, now 31, was sentenced to die for the
Jan. 30, 1977, rape and stabbing death of Frances Rice Coe, a
Meriwether County, Ga., neighbor of co-defendant Eddie Spraggins.
   Spraggins also was convicted of murder and sentenced to death,
but won a new trial. He was the prime witness against Davis during
his 1977 trial.
   However, Spraggins said in an affidavit recently filed with the
Georgia Supreme Court that his testimony that Davis was in the room
with Mrs. Coe when she was killed was false.
   The affidavit supported Ms. Uhlir's belief that Davis is
innocent, developed over her years of correspondence with him.
   His letters to Ms. Uhlir gradually became more personal, and she
regularly wrote him about her children. In his letters, he called
her ``Sis.''
   Davis had been sentenced to die on Christmas Eve 1982, but was
granted a stay of execution.
   In his letters, he insisted that he killed no one but was
preparing to die.
   After learning that Davis had told his attorneys he wanted to
meet his pen pal, Ms. Uhlir traveled to the Georgia Diagnostic and
Classification Center, in Jackson, Ga. She met Davis for the first
time in the prison June 14.
   ``We held each other right in the hallway,'' she recalled. ``In
the room, there were two plastic molded chairs. He said, `Take your
pick.' One of the things I remember well is that he was covered
with sweat. But he was well-groomed and clean. He was warm and
gentlemanly.
   ``He said, `I'm not afraid to die, but I would like to die the
way God wants me to die.' ...
   ``He said, `I didn't kill her, Katey. I've never killed
anybody,' I said to him, `Couldn't you have stopped it?' He just
said, `I don't know.'''
   A federal appeals court refused to grant a stay of execution
before the parole board suspended the sentence.
   In its decision, the board said it had questions about Davis'
culpability, Spraggins' recantation and the new trial granted
Spraggins.
   ``The state Board of Pardons and Paroles will not have an
opportunity for a full and fair investigation ... unless the
execution ... is suspended,'' said board Chairman Wayne Snow.
   ``I believe that he didn't kill anybody,'' said Ms. Uhlir. ``He
knew there was still hope. Even in his letters, he never had any
false fantasies. But what's next for him? I'm afraid to say.''
</TEXT>
