<1ST_LINE>r a PM-NeighborsRescued     06-27 0277</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Neighbors Rescued,0287</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>New Neighbor Rescues 12 From Fire Next Door</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI SPRINGS, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man who moved into a house three
weeks ago met his next-door neighbors by rescuing 12 of them from a
burning home.
   Richard Castro, a 26-year-old truck driver, said he awoke at
5:30 a.m. Sunday to the sound of an explosion and breaking glass
coming from his neighbor's house.
   ``He just grabbed a fire extinguisher from the kitchen and ran
next door,'' said his wife, Laureen, 27.
   As Ms. Castro dialed 911, her husband used the extinguisher to
pound the door of Irma Uriarte's house.
   Unable to get a response, Castro smashed a window, unlatched the
door and entered.
   ``It was so smoky in there, I was dying for air,'' he said. ``I
kept having to step outside.''
   Castro then rousted the family out of their beds.
   ``I thought someone was going to rob the house,'' said John
Pereira, one of the Uriarte relatives who was in the house for a
family gathering. ``We got up when we heard the noise and then we
saw the smoke.''
   Castro found the origin of the fire _ a living-room lamp and
couch _ and put it out before helping the family outside.
   The neighbors formally met on the Uriarte lawn and Metro-Dade
firetrucks pulled up about 10 minutes later, Castro said.
   ``Mr. Castro is a hero,'' said Pereira, who came for the reunion
from his home in New York. ``If it wasn't for him, we wouldn't be
here now.''
   Said Castro, ``I really don't feel like a hero. I was just doing
what felt natural. I'm just glad everyone is OK.''
</TEXT>
