<2ND_LINE>AM-Japan-Markets,0254</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Soars, Stocks Slide</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar closed at its highest level this year
against the Japanese yen at the end of trading Monday, while stock
prices continued a downward swing.
   The dollar closed at 131.70 yen, up 2.00 yen from Friday's
close, to reach its highest closing since December. It opened at
131.00 yen and traded in a range between 130.75 and 131.70 yen.
   On the Tokyo Stock Exchange, the 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average,
which fell 194.18 points during Saturday's half-day session,
declined another 121.20 points, or 0.44 percent, to close the day's
session at 27,435.01.
   Dealers said a stronger dollar in New York on Friday was
boosting the currency in Tokyo at the start of the trading week.
   ``There may be profit-taking selling pressure, but the dollar
will remain in an upward direction,'' said an exchange dealer with
a major commercial bank, who requested anonymity.
   The Bank of Japan has refrained from intervening in the market,
according to analysts, who said the central bank had been expected
to step in to slow the dollar's rise at a level around 130 yen.
   Although share prices were mixed on opening, they plunged in
morning dealings, depressed by the rising U.S. currency.
   ``Movements on the foreign exchange market are affecting share
prices,'' said a trader with a Japanese security house in Tokyo.
``It's a strong trend, and we have to wait as the market corrects
itself,'' he said, speaking on condition of anonymity.
</TEXT>
