<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Airbus-Glance     06-27 0216</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Airbus-Glance,0226</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Airbus At A Glance</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-France-Crash, Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>By The Associated Press</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Here are some facts on the Airbus A320, the twin-engine jetliner
that crashed in eastern France on Sunday:
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   MANUFACTURER: Airbus Industrie, a Toulouse, France-based
European consortium. First test-flown on Feb. 22, 1987, the plane
was certified on Feb. 26.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   CAPACITY: Normally seats 150 passengers but can carry up to 179.
Carries a crew of two on the flight deck, with one (optionally two)
additional crew members. Four flight attendants.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   DIMENSIONS: A 111-foot wingspan, overall length of 123 feet and
height of 38 feet. The wheelbase is 41 feet. Passenger doors are
front and aft on the port side, with two emergency exits over wings
on both sides.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   SPECIAL FACTS: Has a range of about 3,700 miles and consumes 40
percent less fuel than similar two or three engine jets.
   It is the first civilian airliner equipped with a fully
computerized flight-control system the manufacturer says permits
safer, electronically controlled flight. Instead of the old control
column in front of the pilot, there is a ``pistol-grip'' side stick
linked to five computers that modify and relay the pilot's
directions to wing and tail flaps.
   Airbus Industrie has 500 orders to purchase the craft, which
cost about $60 million each.
</TEXT>
