<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Bangladesh-Floods     06-27 0282</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bangladesh-Floods,0293</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Flood Death Toll Rises To 17</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DHAKA, Bangladesh (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eight more people have died in
flood-related accidents in Bangladesh, raising the death toll in
the past week to at least 17, officials and press reports said
today.
   Seven fishermen drowned after being swept into the Bay of Bengal
early Sunday when an embankment crumbled under the pressure of
flood waters, officials in the port city of Chittagong said.
   Another person was killed Sunday when a mudslide buried his
house in the Chittagong Hill Tracts, the officials said, speaking
on condition of anonymity.
   Nine people died in floods earlier last week.
   Officials in Dhaka said rail and road links between the capital
and the northern Sylhet and Sunamganj districts _ hardest hit by
the floods _ have been disrupted by the swirling waters.
   All trains running between Sylhet and Dhaka have been canceled,
they added.
   Ittefaq, a Bengali-language newspaper, said floods have stranded
more than 500,000 people in the remote areas of northern Netrokona
district.
   Rescue teams have been evacuating the people to government
shelters, mostly by boat, the newspaper said.
   Thousands of homes have been destroyed in the region, Ittefaq
reported.
   Most of the victims are poor people who live and farm in
low-lying areas that are flooded when Bangladesh's many rivers
overflow during the annual monsoon rains.
   Earlier this month, at least 25 people died in the first spate
of monsoon-related flooding, according to official count.
Unofficial reports put the figure at 50.
   More than 1,200 people were killed last year in devastating
floods that destroyed crops the government said could have yield
3.4 million tons of rice for this impoverished, food-importing
nation of 105 million people.
</TEXT>
