<FILEID>AP-NR-06-27-88 0352EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Drought-Rivertown     06-27 0588</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Drought-Rivertown,0606</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Barge Traffic Delays Cause Grain Pileups</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Drought-Insurance, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL DE LA GARZA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOUND CITY, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   This community on the banks of the Ohio
River is living up to its name in an unexpected way: Piles of grain
valued at almost $1 million are heaped on its streets because of
drought-stranded barge traffic.
   The off-and-on closure of the river from Cairo to about 10 miles
north of Mound City, whose top industry is grain storage and
shipment, has made it tough to find empty barges to haul the grain.
   And the ones that are available cannot be stocked to capacity
because the Coast Guard has placed tonnage limitations on tow sizes
in hopes of avoiding vessel groundings.
   Dozens of towboats, which need a minimum depth of 9 feet, have
run aground in recent weeks because of fast-sinking water levels
and shoaling, a buildup of silt deposits caused by slow-flowing
water.
   ``How do you get the barges in if the river's close and they
can't move?'' asked Robert Hudson of ADM Growmark in Mound City.
``You have to bring them in by helicopter.''
   ADM Growmark, along with two other grain operators here, began
dumping grain on city streets near the river about two weeks ago.
Hudson said ADM will hold the grain rather than move it by rail to
save money.
   He estimated rail costs at 50 percent more than the highest
barge freight rates.
   Since the drought began taking its toll, barge operators have
doubled the average bulk commodity rates, to about $14 a ton, said
Robert Gardner of Conti Carriers and Terminals, a unit of
Chicago-based Continental Grain Co., the nation's fifth largest
barge company.
   ``I think a lot of people underestimate this industry,'' Gardner
said. ``It's resilient and it's able to cope with problems of this
nature. We're pretty resourceful.''
   By the middle of last week, about 200,000 bushels of grain
created huge mounds in Mound City and trucks continued to dump
more. Hudson estimated its worth at $700,000.
   The Coast Guard said barge traffic along the river, where depths
were only 6 feet in spots, remained limited during the weekend.
Sand bars, some larger than a football field, have forced closure
of the river to allow dredging.
   The pileup, Hudson estimated, will cost local grain operators
about $6,000 a month. But Hudson and other industry officials say
they've weathered tough times before.
   ``We take economic chances from time to time,'' said Gardner.
``We do it with the weather as well. All in all,'' he said, ``what
it does is slow things down a little bit.''
   Hudson noted, for example, that barges are still loading,
however slowly.
   Officials call the southern edge of the Ohio one of the nation's
most treacherous inland waterways because of its shallow waters.
   If a boat runs aground or rams the banks of the narrowing
channel, its barges can break up and float down river, possibly
damaging other vessels.
   At midweek, hundreds of barges were stranded on the Ohio. On
Sunday, 54 barges were waiting to go downriver, the Coast Guard
said.
   The delay meant up to $10,000 a day for each idled towboat
because of the costs of labor, gasoline and lost business.
   And Chuck Shumann, a U.S. Army Corps of Engineers spokesman in
Louisville, Ky., warned last week: ``If the drought continues and
we do not get additional water in the river, there will be
additional dredging. In the worst we could have more severe
problems of boats getting through.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880627-0042 </DOCNO>
