<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Japan-Markets     06-27 0216</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Japan-Markets,0223</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Soars, Stocks Slip</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar jumped to its highest closing level this
year against the Japanese yen today, while stocks slumped in
moderate trading on the Tokyo Stock Exchange.
   The dollar surged to end the day's session at 131.70 yen, up
2.00 yen from Friday's close. It opened at 131.00 yen and was
traded between 130.75 and 131.70 yen.
   ``The market is taking its cue from gains in overseas currency
dealings,'' said a dealer with the Bank of Tokyo. ``In particular,
the dollar rose sharply against the (West German) mark, and that's
moving the market here,'' he said, speaking on condition of
anonymity.
   Today's closing was the highest since Dec. 10, when the currency
ended trading at 132.18 yen.
   On the Tokyo Stock Exchange, the 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average,
a 194.18-point loser during Saturday's half-day session, fell
another 121.20 points, or 0.44 percent, to close the day at
27,435.01.
   Volume traded on the first section reached about 850 million
shares, compared to the 600 million traded over the half-day
session on Saturday.
   Some traders said the market was reflecting concern over the
influence of the stronger dollar on Japanese prices and interest
rates. Others said the losses more likely stemmed from a correction
after sharp market gains this year.
</TEXT>
