<1ST_LINE>r a PM-AMAConvention     06-27 0471</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-AMA Convention,0482</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Retransmitting a0484 to DELETE INCORRECT time in editor's note.</HEAD>
<HEAD>Doctors Debate Proposals On AIDS, Medicaid Reform At AMA
Convention</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Lead prospects uncertain.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM C. HIDLAY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   American Medical Association delegates today
gathered to debate proposals for battling AIDS by testing all
immigrants and inmates, overhauling Medicaid and creating a type of
hospital worker to replace nurses.
   The annual policymaking meeting runs through Thursday and was
expected to attract up to 2,000 doctors from across the country.
The 420 doctors who are official delegates represent the
association's estimated 295,000 members and act as a legislature,
debating and setting policy for the nation's largest organization
of physicians.
   Today, the delegates were scheduled to debate 101 reports on
problems including child pornography and the health hazards of
clove cigarettes, and to consider more than 200 resolutions on such
issues as the health risks of tanning parlors and the need to
revamp the nation's Medicare health insurance system for the
elderly.
   Other proposals to be considered by the organization's House of
Delegates included banning plastic handguns, putting warning labels
on alcoholic beverages and clarifying the AMA's stand on mercy
killing.
   ``We take an open, liberal policy on resolutions and will
consider anything that we feel affects the public's health,'' said
Dr. William Hotchkiss, whose term as AMA president is ending.
   Hotchkiss said before the convention began that he expected the
AIDS epidemic, and how to combat it, would prompt detailed
discussion.
   ``AIDS, of course, is the biggest threatening health problem in
the United States. There is still considerable debate that I think
will take place over the issue of testing,'' said Hotchkiss, a
thoracic surgeon from Chesapeake, Va.
   One resolution up for debate today recommends requiring state
and local health departments to notify the sexual partners of
anyone who tests positive for exposure to the AIDS virus. The
proposal also calls on the AMA to recommend that all immigrants and
prison inmates be tested for exposure to the virus that causes
acquired immune deficiency syndrome.
   The AMA Board of Trustees' also is proposing a massive overhaul
of Medicaid, the nation's program for helping the poor pay for
medical care.
   A report for the convention says the Medicaid program is marred
by ``severe inequities'' nationwide and is ``in desperate need of
reform.''
   It proposes extending benefits to an additional 27 million
people and raising the annual cost of Medicaid by about $24 billion.
   A battle may erupt over the AMA's proposal to help offset the
nationwide shortage of nurses by creating a new class of hospital
workers to provide some bedside care to patients.
   The American Nurses' Association opposes the plan to create
licensed ``registered care technologists.'' Under the plan, high
school graduates could begin caring for patients as assistant
technologists with two months' training.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
