<FILEID>AP-NR-06-27-88 0507EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Israel     06-27 0582</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Israel,0603</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Israeli Soldiers Wreck Home of Arab Stabbing Suspect</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALLYN FISHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soldiers today demolished the home of an Arab
suspected of stabbing a Jewish settler and police strengthened
their ranks in Jerusalem, where underground leaders urged an
escalation of the Palestinian uprising.
   Also, Israeli troops closed more than 40 Palestinian schools in
the West Bank city of Nablus, citing repeated stone-throwing
incidents in the area in recent days. The army said the schools
would be closed at least several days.
   The bulldozed house belonged to Abdel Majid Sharawne, 22.
American-born settler Yohan Chaiken said he chased and shot
Sharawne Friday after the Palestinian stabbed him in the West Bank
city of Hebron.
   Sharawne's home was the second building wrecked by Israeli
authorities in two days. On Sunday, the army blew up the second
story of a building in the occupied Gaza Strip, where it said
assailants threw a firebomb that badly burned two of its soldiers
last week.
   Five hundred extra police officers were put on alert in the
mixed Jewish-Arab city of Jerusalem today to confront expected
protests called in the latest leaflet distributed by underground
leaders allied with the Palestine Liberation Organization, said
city police spokesman Rafi Levy.
   Israeli news reports said 1,500 police in all were stationed in
the city.
   The leaflet said Palestinians should mark today and Tuesday as
``days for the escalation of the struggle.'' It said they should
march in Jerusalem, which it called ``the capital of the
Palestinian state.''
   The call was meant to protest Israel's annexation of the Arab
sector of Jerusalem a few days after it was captured from Jordan in
the 1967 Middle East War, when Israel also seized the Gaza Strip
and West Bank.
   According to U.N. figures, 211 Palestinians and four Israelis
have died in the anti-occupation uprising that began Dec. 8.
   Underground leaders also urged merchants to take part in a
general strike on Tuesday ``in affirmation of the Arab identity of
the city (of Jerusalem).''
   Police have recently rounded up Palestinian guerrilla suspects
from Jerusalem's walled Old City, most of whom are aged 17 to 23
and believed responsible for a rash of recent firebomb attacks in
the city, the mass-circulation daily Maariv said.
   In another development, the army said it was investigating
allegations that soldiers used hypodermic needles to inject two
Palestinian men in the Al Amari refugee camp near Ramallah on the
West Bank to pry information about stone-throwers from them.
   Nader Mahli, 24, said soldiers seized him Friday and gave him an
injection while they asked him for the names of stone-throwers and
members of the Shabiba, a PLO youth movement.
   Masaad Jaber, a driver for the United Nations, said soldiers
also forced his son, Midhad, to receive an injection during an
interrogation.
   One Palestinian showed reporters needle marks in his arm that he
said was caused by the hypodermics.
   In the Gaza Strip, meanwhile, Israeli troops clamped curfews on
the Beach camp and a portion of the Jabaliya camp after an Israeli
car was stoned and set ablaze in the nearby Beit Lahiya
neighborhood on Sunday, Israel radio reported.
   On Sunday, a fire damaged the Hassan Bek mosque in the seaside
port of Jaffa near Tel Aviv.
   Moslem leaders said the attack appeared to be the work of Jews
seeking revenge for fires that have razed more than 35,000 acres of
trees and farmland in Israel since May. Palestinian arsonists are
suspected in those fires.
</TEXT>
