<1ST_LINE>r a PM-People-Sullivan     06-27 0326</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-People-Sullivan,0334</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rev. Sullivan Steps down at Zion Baptist Church</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER SHINKLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Rev. Leon Sullivan, who wrote the
guidelines for U.S. companies doing business with South Africa,
exhorted his congregation to advance through work and faith as he
bid farewell to the church he led 38 years.
   ``Use what you have, and with self-help you can do anything you
want to do. You can climb any mountain, you can cross any stream,
you can follow the rainbow and you can find your dream. Self
Help,'' he shouted to the more than 2,500 people who jammed into
the Zion Baptist Church. ``Self help. Self Help.'' Sullivan, who
will remain pastor emeritus at the predominantly black
congregation, also spoke of his ambitious plans to work in
education and development in Africa.
   The 65-year-old minister is perhaps best known for the
``Sullivan Principles,'' a code of conduct he wrote in 1977 for
companies doing business with white-ruled South Africa. Sullivan
had been speaking out against apartheid since the early 1960s, when
his success as an innovative community leader led to his receiving
a post on the board of directors of General Motors.
   Sullivan gained attention for his Opportunities
Industrialization Center, which he founded in 1964. The
Philadelphia-based center, emphasizing the self-help philosophy,
now has 12 branches in Africa.
   Sullivan said those branches would be used for his program to
help Africans.
   Sullivan said he would build schools that would ``train tens of
millions of people in Africa.'' He said those who might be
skeptical about that figure should remember, ``Nothing is too big
with God.''
   Much of the work will be implemented through the International
Foundation for Education and Self-Help, a foundation Sullivan has
established. Sullivan said he plans to move to Phoenix, Ariz.,
where the foundation will be headquartered.
   Sullivan will be replaced as pastor at Zion by Rev. Gus Roman of
Berean Missionary Baptist Church in New York.
</TEXT>
