<HEAD>Mexican, U.S. Firefighters Battle Tijuana Shopping Center Blaze</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TIJUANA, Mexico (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Firefighters from both sides of the
U.S.-Mexican border battled a raging blaze that heavily damaged a
shopping center in this popular tourist city, authorities said.
   The blaze broke out in the one-story Centro Commercial Blanco
Libertad shortly before 6:30 p.m. Sunday and destroyed up to 16
businesses, said Tijuana Fire Department dispatcher Ruben Garcia.
   Firefighters from San Diego and the Mexican cities of Tecate and
Rosarito Beach helped bring the blaze under control within 2{
hours, Garcia said.
   Assistant Tijuana fire Chief Jose Carreno said fire hydrants in
the area did not work and water had to be hauled in.
   Some of the water used to fight the blaze was brought in from
San Diego, about 15 miles away, said San Diego fire Capt. Ralph
Haynes.
   Seven Tijuana firefighters were treated for smoke inhalation at
the scene, Garcia said.
   The cause of the blaze was under investigation and there were no
damage estimates.
