<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--Daytime Emmys,0178</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>CBS Big Winner In Preliminary</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   CBS won 13 awards during the non-televised
portion of the 15th Annual Daytime Emmy Awards. NBC and PBS won
seven each and ABC won four.
   Doug Duitsman, president of the Academy of Television Arts &
Sciences, served as host Sunday. The televised portions are
scheduled for Wednesday, with Phil Donahue as host.
   Four shows won three awards each Sunday: ``The Bold and the
Beautiful,'' CBS; ``Days of Our Lives,'' NBC; ``Pee-Wee's
Playhouse,'' CBS; and ``Un Ballo In Maschera,'' PBS.
   Winning two awards each were: ``The Young and the Restless,''
CBS; ``ALF,'' NBC; ``Sesame Street,'' PBS; ``What If I'm Gay?,'' a
CBS ``Schoolbreak Special''; and ``Just a Regular Kid: An AIDS
Story,'' an ABC ``Afterschool Special.''
   Actor Philip Bosco, who played Gramps in the ABC ``Afterschool
Special'' titled ``Read Between the Lines,'' was honored as
outstanding performer in children's programming. Musicians Bruce
Hornsby and Peter Harris won for outstanding music direction and
composition for their work on ``Soldier Boys,'' a CBS ``Schoolbreak
Special.''
