<DOCNO> AP880627-0055 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-27-88 0608EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-UN-Disarmament     06-27 0628</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-UN-Disarmament,0647</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.N. Disarmament Session Fails To Adopt Final Resolution On Arms
Control</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   After a month of speeches and debate on
disarmament, U.N. delegates were unable to agree on the future
direction of arms control and adjourned their special General
Assembly session in failure.
   Many of the 135 speakers at the session hailed the recent
U.S.-Soviet treaty to scrap all intermediate-range nuclear
missiles. Yet they were unable to emulate the superpowers and
overcome national policy differences.
   Different nations and regional groups held a variety of
conflicting views. But the crucial rift developed between sweeping
proposals advanced by the Soviet Union and developing nations and a
more cautious approach backed by the United States and some of its
Western allies.
   Delegates clashed in debate over issues such as the U.S.
space-based missile defense system known as ``Star Wars,'' U.N.
monitoring of land-based weapons and disarmament, and a Soviet call
for a joint U.S.-Soviet nuclear test ban.
   By Sunday morning, they gave up the attempt to write a mutually
acceptable document. No vote was attempted on the final resolution.
   The 159-member General Assembly has no enforcement power over
its decisions. But delegates believed a final resolution adopted by
consensus, would carry moral authority by expressing the will of
the world community.
   Chinese delegate Yu Mengyia seemed to blame the United States
when he said: ``A certain country which should have important
disarmament responsibilities had insisted on its position. That was
a major reason that consensus was not achieved.''
   Speaking for the Soviet Union, Vladimir F. Petrovsky said only
that no consensus was possible ``because of the actions of some
states.''
   U.S. delegate Max Friedersdorf said his country ``regretted very
much that it had not been possible to achieve consensus on the
chairman's draft document, which had been acceptable in large part
to most delegations.''
   The delegates attempted to rewrite the final document
unanimously approved at the first special General Assembly session
on disarmament 10 years ago, a utopian resolution that many nations
consider an important outline of the goal of a weapons-free world.
   An attempt to revise the document at the second special session
on disarmament in 1982 ended in disagreement.
   American and some other Western allies indicated during the
latest session that they would reject any document that did not
address basic concerns of the West, including:
   _ spiraling military spending by developing nations. Western
delegates said those funds would be better spent on economic
development, education and health care;
   _ the emergence of regional powers as major factors in
militarization and instability, such as Iran and Iraq, and India
and Pakistan. Virtually all wars since World War II have been
fought among developing nations;
   _ recognizing that the United States and the Soviet Union have
made progress on disarmament and stating that such treaties are a
strictly bilateral matter, as U.S. Secretary of Shultz George
Shultz told the special session.
   In addition, the United States favored emphasis on conventional
disarmament, especially in Europe where the Warsaw Pact is regarded
as stronger than NATO in such forces.
   In his speech to the session, Soviet Foreign Minister Eduard
Shevardnadze called for elimination of all nuclear weapons by the
end of the century, troop reductions of 500,000 soldiers each by
the Warsaw Pact and NATO, and a joint U.S.-Soviet nuclear test ban.
   The Soviets and the developing nations also favored an expanded
role for the United Nations in arms control monitoring and an
international naval force under U.N. control, which the United
States opposes.
   Non-aligned nations further wanted to identify Israel and South
Africa as regional offenders in the final document, another bone of
contention with the West.
   The special session cost the financially ailing world body $7.4
million.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880627-0056 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-27-88 0629EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-WeatherpageWeather     06-27 0507</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Weatherpage Weather,0522</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Thunderstorms Linger Over South, Midwest</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Violent thunderstorms whipped through the Midwest and the
Southeast today after battering several spots with destructive
winds, large hail and lightning.
   Thunderstorms were scattered from northeast Florida and eastern
Georgia across South Carolina into southern North Carolina. Winds
gusted to 90 mph at Tall Timbers, Md., on Sunday afternoon and up
to 75 mph in northeastern North Carolina.
   Tree and power lines were ripped down from southeast Virginia
into central and southeastern Alabama. The fierce winds also
toppled small buildings in South Carolina, east of Anderson; blew
down a radio tower in Aiken, Ga.; overturned a small airplane at
the Birmingham, Ala., airport and destroyed two mobile homes at
Andalusia, Ala.
   Evening thunderstorms produced hail the size of golfballs at
Monticello, Ga., and Mooresville N.C.
   Scattered showers and thunderstorms lingered from Colorado and
New Mexico across western Texas, northwest Oklahoma and southwest
Kansas. Golfball-size hail and a tornado were reported Sunday
evening near Partridge, Kan., while a tornado touched down farther
west, near Plevna, Kan.
   In Oklahoma, winds up to 81 mph blew the roof off an apartment
complex while downing numerous power lines at Stillwater. A roof
was ripped off a trailer house and trees were uprooted in Cherokee
County.
   In Texas, more than 2 inches of rain drenched portions of Spring
Creek near San Angelo.
   A few thunderstorms lingered from northeast Oregon into Montana
and northwest Wyoming.
   Today's forecast called for scattered showers and thunderstorms
across the southern and central Rockies and from the southern
Plains through the central Gulf Coast region to the southern
Atlantic coast; numerous showers and thunderstorms across northern
and central Florida and from northwest Texas to Colorado and
eastern Utah; and continuing dry weather across the Midwest and the
Tennessee Valley.
   High temperatures were forecast in the 80s or 90s throughout
much of the nation; in the 70s from the Great Lakes and the Ohio
Valley to the northern two-thirds of the Atlantic coast; in the 60s
and 70s along the Pacific Coast; reaching 100 to 110 across the
desert Southwest.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 a.m. EDT ranged from 44
degrees at Sault Ste. Marie, Mich., to 93 degrees at Phoenix, Ariz.
   Other reports:
   _East: Atlanta 75 partly cloudy; Boston 59 partly cloudy;
