<FILEID>AP-NR-06-27-88 0632EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Pope     06-27 0672</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Pope,0696</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pope Condemns Inter-Catholic Clashes in Face of Schism</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VICTOR L. SIMPSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>INNSBRUCK, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pope John Paul II today denounced
``bitter confrontations'' among Roman Catholics as a historic
schism loomed between the Church and its traditionalists.
   The Church's first break in more than a century could open if
traditionalist French archbishop Marcel Lefebvre goes ahead with
the consecration of four bishops in Switzerland over the Vatican's
objections.
   The action, threatened for Thursday, would mean automatic
excommunication for Lefebvre under Roman Catholic law.
   Also today, the pope, who was finishing his five-day tour of
Austria, issued special greetings to controversial President Kurt
Waldheim.
   The president has been accused of complicity in Nazi atrocities
during World War II, but denies any wrongdoing. The pope has met
with Waldheim during the visit, which has focused heavily on the
horror of the Nazi era.
   Speaking today to a crowd of 38,000, many clad in traditional
mountain peasant outfits, John Paul cited ``growing lack of
communications among generations, numerous divorces, suicides
including those among young people, all-out fights among
politicians and parties, bitter confrontation among Christians
themselves, cynical criticism of the church even in the church's
own publications.''
   ``These are all warning signs that God's command and the joyful
message of Christ for many are no longer the basis of their
behavior,'' the pontiff added.
   After his return to Rome today, the pontiff is expected to make
another attempt to head off what would be the church's first schism
since 1870.
   Lefebvre has announced his intention to consecrate four bishops
in Econe, Switzerland, on Thursday in defiance of the Vatican.
   ``A lot of people believe in tradition but not in rupture,''
Vatican spokesman Joaquin Navarro told reporters in Salzburg on
Sunday.
   Navarro said the Vatican has received indications that only
about 20 percent of Lefebvre's followers would remain loyal to the
82-year-old prelate should he defy the pope.
   The Vatican spokesman estimated that Lefebvre has between 80,000
and 100,000 followers. But other Vatican officials say as many as
half a million Catholics around the world turn to tradionalist
priests for various church functions.
   Earlier, the Vatican's No. 2 official, Secretary of State
Cardinal Agostino Casaroli, called the impending schism a ``painful
wound'' and ``a break that could not be immediately repairable.''
   ``I am certain he will not have a large following and that
people will understand the pope has done all he could to avoid
it,'' the Italian prelate told reporters.
   Also Sunday, conservative Austrian Bishop Kurt Krenn said an
official of Lefebvre's Pius X Fraternity had given him a message
saying, in essence, ``we don't want a schism and hope that a
peaceful solution can be found.''
   Krenn said he relayed the message to the pope through a Vatican
intermediary.
   A compromise solution reached by the two sides last month fell
apart, and Lefebvre said he intended to go ahead and consecrate the
four bishops: a Swiss, a Frenchman, an Argentine and an American.
   The Pius X Fraternity, headquartered in Econe, claims to have
250 priests and 280 seminarians.
   The traditionalists reject many of the reforms approved by the
Second Vatican Council of 1962-65 and celebrate the Tridentine
Latin Mass, for which special Vatican approval is required.
   The last schism in the church involved the so-called ``Old
Catholics'' who broke with the Vatican in 1870 after the First
Vatican Council proclaimed the infallibility of the pope.
   Waldheim was in the audience at Innsbruck's Bergisel stadium for
this morning's Mass, during which the pope said: ``I greet the
esteemed representatives from the civil and governmental area,
especially among them the federal president and the two state
governors from the western part of Austria.''
   As the pope cited Waldheim, the crowd broke into applause while
Austrian television focused on the president and his wife,
Elisabeth.
   Waldheim was scheduled to wish the pontiff farewell at the end
of the trip tonight at Innsbruck airport.
   John Paul angered some Jewish leaders by meeting with Waldheim
at the start of his trip Thursday.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880627-0058 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-27-88 0642EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Dollar-Gold     06-27 0370</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dollar-Gold,0388</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Higher But Off Best Levels On Profit-Taking, Gold Lower</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar rose in early European trading today
but dealers said it was off its best levels because of
profit-taking.
   Gold prices were slightly lower in quiet trading.
   Despite the dollar's slight retreat at midmorning, dealers
predicted it would continue to rise.
   ``There's been a complete reversal in trend against the
dollar,'' said one trader with a major Italian commercial bank.
   Traders said the absence of central bank intervention in the
market and heavy demand for dollars by Japanese financial
institutions had sparked the dollar's sudden advance.
   A trader at a U.S. bank in Frankfurt said leaders of the seven
major industrialized nations attending last week's economic summit
in Toronto ``probably agreed to do nothing, or let the dollar drift
up.''
   ``The only thing that will stop the dollar from going up at the
moment is a central bank intervention,'' said another trader. ``And
even then, only intervention by the U.S. Federal Reserve would be
taken as a serious signal'' that the dollar shouldn't climb higher.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day
begins, the dollar rose 2.00 yen to a closing 131.70. Later, in
London, it was quoted lower at 130.99 yen.
   Other dollar rates at midmorning, compared with late Friday's
rates:
   _ 1.8245 West German marks, up from 1.8010
   _ 1.5078 Swiss francs, up from 1.4945
   _ 6.1380 French francs, up from 6.0635
   _ 2.0581 Dutch guilders, up from 2.0305
   _ 1,351.25 Italian lire, up from 1,330.37
   _ 1.20995 Canadian dollars, up from 1.2050
   In London, the dollar rose strongly against the British pound.
It cost $1.7158 to buy one pound, cheaper than $1.7430 late Friday.
   Gold opened in London at a bid price of $442.60 a troy ounce and
at midmorning, the city's five major bullion dealers fixed a
recommended price of $442.00. Both were down from Friday's late bid
of $442.90.
   In Zurich, the bid price was $442.00, down from $442.90 late
Friday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold fell $1.55 to close at a bid $444.14.
   Silver was quoted in London today at a bid price of $6.85 a troy
ounce, up from Friday's late bid of $6.84.
</TEXT>
