<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Soviet-Defense     06-27 0176</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Soviet-Defense,0180</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviet Marshal To Visit United States</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet Union's second highest military leader
will visit the United States during the first two weeks of July,
Tass said today.
   The official news agency said Marshal Sergei F. Akhromeyev,
chief of staff and first deputy defense minister, will make the
trip at the invitation of Adm. William Crowe, chairman of the U.S.
Joint Chiefs of Staffs.
   Akhromeyev was Washington in early December for the summit
between Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev and President Reagan.
   The invitation is the result of an agreement announced by the
countries' two defense chiefs in March to expand military contacts
and exchanges of information between U.S. and Soviet officials on
force strengths.
   The agreement was part of a joint statement by Defense Secretary
Frank Carlucci and Soviet Defense Minister Gen. Dmitri Yazov after
a meeting in Bern, Switzerland believed to be the first such
session between the countries' defense ministers since World War II.
   Tass did not give Akhromeyev's exact departure date or details
of his schedule.
</TEXT>
