<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Taliesin-Wright     06-27 0198</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Taliesin-Wright,0204</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Frank Lloyd Wright's `Taliesen' Needs Repairs</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SPRING GREEN, Wis. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Famed architect Frank Lloyd Wright's
Taliesin complex near here is deteriorating and could need as much
as $15 million in preservation work, a spokeswoman says.
   Elaine Freed, vice president for external affairs with the Frank
Lloyd Wright Foundation, said the home ``needs a great deal of
work'' and that a study will be required to determine just how much.
   James Klauser, secretary of the state Department of
Administration, said Gov. Tommy G. Thompson was interested in
helping the foundation improve Taliesin and planned to make an
announcement this afternoon.
   Taliesin, including a home and a school for architects, was
declared a National Historic Landmark in 1976.
   ``Clearly Mr. Wright made a substantial contribution to
architecture in Wisconsin and throughout the country,'' said
Klauser, who also traveled to Scottsdale, Ariz., to look at
Wright's Taliesin West.
   Wright, known for designs that influenced the development of
modern architecture, died in Scottsdale in 1959 at the age of 89.
   He and his students worked both at Taliesin and at Taliesin
West. Buildings he designed include the Guggenheim Museum in New
York City and Robie House in Chicago.
</TEXT>
