<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Jackson 1stLd-Writethru a0453 06-27 0529</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Jackson, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0453,500</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 7 grafs Jackson today commenting on veep choice;
picks up 8th graf pvs, Earlier Sunday.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By F.N. D'ALLESSIO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jesse Jackson today urged sure Democratic
presidential nominee Michael Dukakis to pick a ``forward-looking''
running mate as he still refused to say whether he wants the job.
   ``The fact that we're now discussing it ... even that's about
expansion and development,'' Jackson said today on ABC-TV's ``Good
Morning America'' program.
   Jackson, who has said he feels he has earned the right to be
considered for the national ticket based on his second-place
showing in the primaries, would discuss only his vision for the job
and not whether he should be the man to fulfill that vision.
   ``Right now we're in the process ... I feel very good about
it,'' he said from his Chicago home.
   ``I do know now we must define that job to be a meaningful
one,'' said Jackson. ``I see that job as being the possibility that
we will structure into our party hope for our youth, commitment for
our farmers and workers and someone who has rapport in the Third
World. In other words, it must be a forward-looking constitutional
position and not a retirement plan or backup plan.''
   Speaking to a convention Sunday night of Operation PUSH, the
Chicago-based civil rights group he founded, Jackson also took
apparent swipes at Republican George Bush's role as vice president
in the Reagan administration.
   ``It's not a wimp job, although there have been some wimps in
it,'' he told the hometown crowd.
   Earlier Sunday, as he campaigned in the Caribbean, Jackson
referred repeatedly to the initials that stand for vice president.
   ``V.P. doesn't mean visions of the past. It must mean vitality
for the present and vitality for the future,'' he said.
   Jackson, wrapping up a trip to Puerto Rico and the U.S. Virgin
Islands on Sunday, suggested the Democratic platform agreed to over
the weekend does not go far enough.
   ``I do not think that bland is beautiful,'' Jackson said.
``People ought to be specific, ought to make promises, ought to
keep promises, ought to make commitments. People have given us a
mandate.''
   Jackson's calls for a defense budget freeze, increasing taxes on
the rich and Palestinian self-determination were not incorporated
into the document.
   But Jackson indicated he will press his views at the convention
next month in Atlanta.
   ``There will no doubt be some minority positions taken to the
(convention) floor,'' Jackson said, but added it was too early to
say which issues might be contested.
   Jackson also told a rally in St. Croix that he was pleased with
his ``profound victories'' in the party rules committee meeting
over the weekend in Washington.
   The committee on Saturday agreed that the number of ``super
delegates'' should be cut in half in 1992 and to mandate
proportional representation from primary and caucus votes. Super
delegates attend the convention by virtue of their status as party
or elective officials, and are not obligated to vote as their state
or district did.
   Jackson had complained that the super delegates and delegates
were unfairly distributed this year.
</TEXT>
