<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Afghanistan     06-27 0326</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Afghanistan,0340</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Guerrillas Claim Fall Of Second Provincial Capital</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN WILDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Afghan guerrillas today claimed they
have captured a second Afghan provincial capital in two weeks and
opened a strategic position from which they can attack the capital
of Kabul.
   The rebels' Afghan News Agency said in an unconfirmed report
that Soviet and Afghan government troops Sunday retreated from
Maidan Shahr, provincial capital of Wardak province, about 25 miles
southwest of Kabul.
   The reported victory of the rebels, following heavy fighting,
would allow them to move toward the Paghman Heights overlooking
western Kabul.
   The report came one day after Western diplomatic sources
reported that a guerrilla rocket attack on Kabul airport destroyed
eight Soviet jet fighters, the worst Soviet loss of military air
equipment in a single day since Soviet forces intervened in
December 1979.
   Pravda, Moscow's Communist Party daily, said Sunday that
guerrillas seized Maidan Shahr for one day last week before Afghan
troops recaptured it in heavy fighting.
   But a reporter for the rebel agency, which is run by the Moslem
fundamentalist Hezb-i-Islami Party, said today that Soviet-Afghan
forces withdrew from the city Sunday after more heavy fighting.
   The guerrillas seized the first provincial capital, Kalat in
southeastern Zabul province, on June 18.
   The Afghan Press Agency, a pro-rebel Pakistani news service,
reported Sunday that guerrillas repulsed a Soviet attack Wednesday
near the besieged southeastern provincial capital of Kandahar.
   It said the Soviets suffered 21 dead and several injured, and
left behind the wreckage of a tank and three armored vehicles. It
said the insurgents suffered five dead and 22 wounded.
   The guerrillas have taken several Afghan and Soviet posts since
the Geneva accords April 14. Under the agreement, the Soviet Union
began withdrawing troops from Afghanistan on May 15 and would have
until Feb. 15, 1989 to complete the pullout.
   The Soviet-backed Kabul government said only Soviet troops, not
Soviet military advisers, will leave.
</TEXT>
