<FILEID>AP-NR-06-27-88 0925EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Soviet-Reform     06-27 0542</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Soviet-Reform,0562</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Party Conference Focus On Politics, Not Economy, Delegate Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALISON SMALE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A leading economic reformer said today that this
week's Communist Party conference will focus on the party's role in
society and should not be expected to produce economic miracles.
   Otto Latsis, deputy chief editor of the monthly Kommunist and a
conference delegate, told reporters that the conference's central
aim is to unite the party behind political reform.
   Another delegate, Kommunist editor Nail B. Bikkenin, said the
goal is to develop a political system that would not allow a repeat
of the tyranny of Josef Stalin or the stagnation prevalent during
Leonid I. Brezhnev's rule.
   ``We will reconstruct our political system, which is obsolete,
obsolete,'' Bikkenin said. ``What we must have is reliable
political guarantees against a recurrence of what happened in the
past.''
   A third delegate, Pravda editor Viktor G. Afanasyev, said
Mikhail S. Gorbachev would deliver a ``big and interesting report''
when the conference opens Tuesday. Afanasyev, appearing at one of a
series of news conferences about the meeting, gave no details.
   Weeks of discussion have produced thousands of suggestions for
change, some of them as radical as having the Communist Party
general secretary elected directly by nationwide ballot.
   Proposals have been floated in the press recently, and
unfettered political discussion has occurred.
   The economy, however, has made few visible advances, and
consumer shortages of items such as sugar and cheese have worsened
in recent weeks.
   Latsis noted that in an article published today in the Communist
daily Pravda in which he called the country's retail sales system
disgraceful.
   At his news conference, Latsis said the supply system could be
improved only by providing economic stimuli and incorporating a
much greater role for demand and supply in the Soviet Union's
centraly planned economy.
   But he made clear that such matters won't be decided at the
party conference, which is expected to last at least until July 1.
   ``The central question is the question of how the party should
change its role in our society,'' Latsis said. ``In this area,
there will be decisions.''
   ``These are decisions which will change our future, but not the
next day,'' Latsis said. ``There is a lot of waiting for a
miracle.''
   Banners and propaganda posters adorning the capital as the 5,000
delegates arrived over the weekend for the first such gathering
since 1941 struck a slightly different tone.
   New lettering on many banners invoked a revolutionary style of
writing not seen since the early 1920s, when Vladimir I. Lenin had
just propelled the Bolsheviks to power.
   Latsis' remarks reflected an attempt by reformers and officials
in recent weeks to lower pubic expectations about what the
conference will produce.
   It had once been billed as a forum that would institute radical
reforms.
   Latsis said he did not yet know exactly how the conference would
be run.
   A set of proposals, known as theses, was approved by the party's
policy-making Central Committee on May 23 and has since been
debated intensely in the media and society.
   Among them is a suggestion to limit all party and state
officials to a maximum two terms in office, with a possible third
term if the electing party forum agrees.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
