<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Korea-Olympics     06-27 0301</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Korea-Olympics,0309</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Asian-Pacific Security Meeting to Safeguard Olympics</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By M.H. AHN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Security officials from seven nations
and 13 airlines will meet this week to plan anti-terrorist measures
for the 1988 Summer Olympics, the Foreign Ministry said today.
   Ministry officials said representatives will meet Tuesday and
Wednesday to share information on terrorist groups, airline safety
and other security measures.
   The United States, Japan, the Philippines, Thailand, Malaysia,
Singapore, and South Korea will attend the meeting, officials said.
Hong Kong, a British colony, also plans to send delegates.
   Thirteen airlines that fly to Seoul will discuss ways to ensure
security for their aircraft during the Olympics, officials said.
The airlines were not identified.
   The International Civil Aviation Organization, the International
Air Transport Association and the International Federation of
Airline Pilot Associations will attend as observers.
   South Korea, the United States and other nations have expressed
concern that Communist North Korea will attempt to disrupt the
Summer Games or that international terrorist groups may stage
attacks.
   Delegates will consider tightening airport security checks and
improving international cooperation to prevent terrorist attacks
against the Summer Games, which run from Sept. 17 to Oct. 2.
   South Korea and the United States have expressed concern in
recent weeks over improvements in North Korea's military forces,
including the deployment of advanced SAM-5 anti-aircraft missiles
close to the border.
   The two Koreas, divided since the partition of the Korean
peninsula in 1945 at the end of World War II, are bitter foes. The
two nations fought the bloody Korean War from 1950 to 1953 after
the North invaded the south.
   The United States has some 42,000 troops in South Korea under a
mutual defense pact and plans to beef up its forces in the region
to help safeguard the Olympics.
</TEXT>
