<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Seabrook-Talks     06-27 0485</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Seabrook-Talks,0500</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Utility Willing to Abandon Seabrook If Price Is Right</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL MOKRZYCKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NASHUA, N.H. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The main owner of the beleaguered Seabrook
nuclear power plant would abandon the unused plant for the right
price, the utility's president said today.
   ``We don't have any blinders on. We are willing to consider
anything,'' said Robert Harrison of Public Service Company of New
Hampshire.
   Harrison said the utility, which filed for bankruptcy
reorganization in January, already has held a preliminary meeting
with state officials about abandoning the plant. He refused to
identify the officials.
   ``I remain convinced that the best outcome from the point of
view of the customers is to have the plant operate. But if things
happen ... we, Public Service, are not bound inexorably to the
ultimate operation of Seabrook,'' Harrison said.
   Public Service is the largest of the plant's 12 owners with 36
percent ownership. A division of Public Service built the plant on
the Atlantic Coast in the southeastern corner of New Hampshire,
about 40 miles north of Boston.
   Harrison disclosed the abandonment talks to reporters during a
discussion of the utility's legal responsibility to maximize the
value of company assets. He was asked if Public Service would
consider a deal similar to one tentatively agreed to for the
Shoreham nuclear plant on Long Island in New York.
   Long Island Lighting Co. has approved an agreement with the
state of New York under which the completed but unused Shoreham
plant could be torn down. If finalized, it would be the first time
in the nation that a completed nuclear power plant was abandoned.
   In return, Long Island Lighting would continue to operate as a
privately owned company and get annual rate increases for 10 years.
   Harrison today declined to speculate about the likelihood that
Seabrook would be scrapped, and said he still believes the $5.4
billion plant will be licensed. Completed in 1986, it hasn't
received a federal operating license.
   Harrison acknowledged that it is virtually impossible for
Seabrook to be licensed before new presidential and gubernatorial
administrations take office in January.
   Likely Democratic presidential nominee Michael Dukakis, as
governor of neighboring Massachusetts, has been the key to blocking
a license for Seabrook, and would presumably continue his
opposition if he were elected president.
   Dukakis has refused to submit required emergency plans for six
Massachusetts communities near the plant, saying public safety
could not be assured in case of a major accident.
   New Hampshire Gov. John Sununu, a strong Seabrook supporter, is
not seeking re-election.
   In the past, Public Service has fought fiercely for the plant,
originally expected to cost less than $1 billion for two reactors
and scheduled to begin operating in 1979. But Harrison said the
bankruptcy filing changed things.
   ``Though we still staunchly support Seabrook and want it to
operate, we do not have the same life-or-death dependency on that
project,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
