<HEAD>Court Will Consider Ky. Prisoners' Rights Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD CARELLI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today agreed to decide
whether prison officials sometimes must explain why they bar an
inmate from having visitors.
   The justices said they will study a federal appeals court ruling
that a Kentucky prison's visitation program created a ``liberty
interest'' for inmates that cannot be infringed upon without due
process.
   The appeals court ruling did not say what kind of due process _
perhaps a written explanation of denied visitation rights or some
type of hearing _ is required. But Kentucky officials appealed
anyway.
   More than half the states supported Kentucky's appeal in a
``friend-of-the-court'' brief, urging the high court to issue a
decision setting precedent nationally.
   They said the Kentucky prison's visitation policy is similar to
those at prisons in many states.
   ``More significantly, there are a number of other policies at
the correctional institutions ... concerning the daily operation of
prisons ranging from inmate job assignments to telephone privileges
which in all likelihood are also affected,'' the states' brief
contended.
   The Kentucky controversy stems from a lawsuit inmates of the
Kentucky State Reformatory in LaGrange filed over conditions there.
   The suit resulted in a 1980 consent decree, in which the state
agreed, among other things, to continue an ``open visitation
policy.''
   State officials subsequently adopted guidelines and procedures
for handling prison visits.
   In 1985, inmate Kenneth Bolitt's mother was denied the right to
visit him temporarily because she had brought to the prison with
her a man previously barred for smuggling contraband.
   Inmate Kevin Black's mother and girlfriend were barred from the
prison temporarily because Black had been convicted of possessing
contraband immediately after one of their visits.
   A ``class action'' lawsuit filed in behalf of all the prison's
inmates contended that the suspension of visitors' privileges
without any due-process hearing was unlawful.
   A federal trial judge ruled for the inmates, and the 6th U.S.
Circuit Court of Appeals upheld that ruling last Nov. 19.
   ``Given the regulatory and mandatory language (in the visitation
policy guidelines), a liberty interest was created under the
circumstances here,'' the appeals court said.
   It sent the case back to a trial judge to determine ``the
particular procedural process due the (inmates) when visitation is
denied.''
   In seeking Supreme Court review, state officials said the
appeals court ruling _ potentially binding law in Kentucky, Ohio,
Michigan and Tennessee _ could ``inhibit substantially corrections
officials from drafting policies that may confer a benefit on an
inmate.''
   Kentucky's appeal said the 6th Circuit court's ruling could
affect such inmate benefits as honor housing, furloughs, work and
study programs, outside trips, recreation, escorted leaves and
inmate clubs.
   ``Finding that such policies create a constitutionally protected
interest is untenable,'' the appeal contended.
   The case is Kentucky vs. Thompson, 87-1815.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
