<HEAD>Nicaraguan President Visits Cuba</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYNA BRENNAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HAVANA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Cuban official said the visit of President
Daniel Ortega of Nicaragua will strengthen the close relations the
two nations have maintained for nearly a decade.
   Ortega was to arrive today for talks with President Fidel Castro.
   During the visit, Ortega will be awarded Cuba's highest medal,
the order of Jose Marti, the 19th century Cuban revolutionary.
   ``This visit is to further strengthen our relations,'' said
Cuban Foreign Ministry press director Omar Mendoza. ``We have
always shown our solidarity in the face of the aggression, the
suffering imposed by the United States and its dirty war.''
   Ortega's visit to Cuba coincides with a trip this week by
Secretary of State George P. Shultz to U.S. allies in Central
America, including El Salvador, Costa Rica, Guatemala and Honduras.
   Ortega's trip also comes as the Reagan adminisration is
considering renewing its congressional request for aid to the
right-wing rebels known as Contras, who have been fighting since
1981 to overthrow the leftist Sandinista government.
   At home, Ortega faces deep social, economic and political
problems. Two weeks ago he announced measures to steer the economy
away from socialist policies toward capitalism. The Cuban
invitation could serve as a nod of approval by Castro.
   Cuba and Nicaragua have maintained close relations since the
Sandinista government came to power in a 1979 revolutionary war
that ousted dicatator Anastasio Somoza. Diplomatic relations,
broken by Somoza in 1960, were reinstated days after the new
government was installed in Managua.
   Castro traveled to Managua in July 1980 to celebrate the first
Sandinista anniversary and visited again in January 1985 to attend
Ortega's inauguration as president.
   Castro, whose Communist government will mark its 30th
anniversary in January, has sent large numbers of Cuban teachers,
doctors and military advisers to work in Nicaragua.
   The United States broke diplomatic and trade relations with Cuba
shortly after Castro came to power in 1959.
