<HEAD>Justices Will Referee Ore., Wash. Environmental Disputes</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD CARELLI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today agreed to referee
environmental disputes over the planned development of a ski resort
in Washington's Methow Valley and an unfinished dam on Elk Creek in
southern Oregon.
   The justices said they will decide whether additional
environmental impact studies are required before federal agencies
may give final approval to both projects.
   Justice Department lawyers had appealed both lower court rulings.
   Sandy Butte, a 6,000-foot mountain in the Okanogan National
Forest overlooks the Methow Valley, a sparsely populated area on
the eastern side of the North Cascade Mountains in Washington.
   The valley is a winter home for Washington's largest migratory
deer herd.
   Methow Recreation Inc. in 1978 asked for permission to develop
and operate a ski resort, to be called Early Winters, on Sandy
Butte and a large parcel of land it had bought adjoining the
mountain.
   The project is expected to spawn extensive commercial and
residential development in the Methow Valley.
   The U.S. Forest Service in 1982 published a draft environmental
impact statement, and a final statement in 1984.
   In late 1985, the Methow Valley Citizens Council sued in federal
court. The suit contended, among other things, that the Forest
Service had violated the National Environmental Policy Act of 1969
in approving the Early Winters project.
   A federal trial judge dismissed the suit, but the 9th U.S.
Circuit Court of Appeals reinstated it.
   The appeals court ruled that the Forest Service must come up
with detailed and effective ``mitigation measures'' to protect the
valley's air quality, the deer herd and other environmental aspects.
   The appeals court said the Forest Service's impact statement
offered ``no assurance whatsoever that the vague mitigation
objectives it features ... would ever in fact be achieved or even
that effective measures would ever be designed, let alone
implemented, if the Early Winters development were to proceed.''
   The 9th Circuit court concluded that the impact statement's
``discussion of mitigation measures is inadequate as a matter of
law.''
   The Oregon controversy dates back to 1962, when Congress
authorized construction of the Rogue River Basin Project a flood
control program in the southern part of the state.
   Elk Creek Dam was one of three dams included in the project, and
is the only one not completed and operating.
   Elk Creek is a tributary of the Rogue River, one of eight rivers
in the nation designated as ``wild and scenic'' by a 1968 law. The
Rogue is known for its white-water rafting and fly-fishing.
   The Corps of Engineers filed a series of environmental impact
statements on the Elk Creek project from 1971 through 1980 before
the Oregon Natural Resources Council and other environmental groups
sued.
   The lawsuit contended that the Corps of Engineers failed to
comply with the Natural Environmental Policy Act of 1969 by
submitting an incomplete final environmental impact statement.
   The 9th Circuit court agreed, stating, ``An EIS must include a
discussion of measures to mitigate adverse environmental impacts of
the proposed action.''
   ``Because the wildlife mitigation plan here merely lists
measures to be used and includes neither an analysis nor an
explanation of effectiveness, it is inadequate to satisfy the
NEPA,'' the appeals court added.
   The cases are Robertson vs. Methow Valley Citizens Council,
87-1703, and Marsh vs. Oregon Natural Resources Council, 87-1704.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
