<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Scotus-Anti-Poverty     06-27 0448</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Scotus-Anti-Poverty,440</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court Says Federal Judges Have Authority to Award Lawyers Fees in
California Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today said federal judges
have substantial authority to award fees to lawyers who win suits
against the government.
   The justices, voting 6-2, said a California anti-poverty law
firm is entitled to recover legal fees for sucessfully challenging
the withholding of federal housing subsidies.
   But the court said $322,700 in fees awarded to the firm is
excessive and ordered further hearings to determine a lower amount.
   The Reagan administration had argued that the fee was both
excessive and not justified at all.
   The Western Center on Law and Poverty in Los Angeles represented
tenants of government-subsidized housing seeking to force the
Department of Housing and Urban Development to pay increased costs
for utilities and local taxes.
   The tenants challenged a decision by HUD Secretary Samuel Pierce
not to use money from a rental reserve fund to pay the costs.
   The case was settled when the government agreed to deposit $60
million into a special escrow fund to be distributed to needy
tenants and to owners of subsidized housing.
   While the settlement was being administered, Congress in 1980
passed the Equal Access to Justice Act to compensate attorneys who
win lawsuits against the government.
   The law generally imposes a $75-per-hour ceiling for lawyers'
fees but permits higher hourly pay in some circumstances.
   The law authorizes judges to award legal fees to the winning
side in suits against the government unless the judge finds the
government's position ``was substantially justified or that special
circumstances make an award unjust.''
   A federal judge in the California case applied an hourly rate
ranging from $80 to $120, totaling $322,700. The judge said the
litigation was complex, protracted and required attorneys with
special skills and qualifications.
   The Reagan administration said the tenants surrendered their
right to the lawyers' fees when they agreed to the settlement. It
also argued that the $75 per hour ceiling should be used if any
legal fees are awarded.
   Justice Antonin Scalia, writing for the court today, upheld the
authority of the trial judge to decide that Pierce's position was
not ``substantially justified'' as defined in the Equal Access to
Justice Act.
   But Scalia said the $75-an-hour cap must apply. Granting the
lawyers higher fees must be based on more than the factors cited by
the judge in the case, Scalia said.
   Justices Byron R. White and Sandra Day O'Connor, in a dissenting
opinion, voted to strike down the award of legal fees entirely.
Justice Anthony M. Kennedy did not take part in the ruling.
   The case is Pierce vs. Underwood, 86-1512.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
