<HEAD>Northwest, Pan Am Have Airbus A320s On Order</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with four grafs to fix dateline and city where
Northwest based to Eagan, sted Minneapolis; picks up 5th graf pvs,
Pan American xxx</NOTE>
<HEAD>With PM-France-Crash</HEAD>
<DATELINE>EAGAN, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Northwest Airlines has on order up to 100
Airbus A320 jetliners like the one that crashed during a
demonstration flight in France, a company official said.
   The twin-engine Air France aircraft crashed in a forest at the
end of an airfield in eastern France near the Swiss border. Three
passengers were killed and 50 others were injured.
   ``I doubt (the crash) would have an impact on our decision to
purchase from Airbus,'' Alan Muncaster, a spokesman for Northwest,
said Sunday. ``But obviously we would want to check into the cause
of the crash.''
   Northwest, based in this St. Paul suburb, and Airbus announced
in October 1986 that Northwest would buy up to 100 Airbus A320s
from its manufacturer, Airbus Industrie, in a deal that would be
worth $3.2 billion.
   Pan American World Airways has ordered 16 A230s, with an option
to buy 34 more. In addition, two U.S. leasing companies have
ordered the A320. GATX Air has ordered 10 and International Lease
Finance Corp. has three on order.
   A spokesman for Airbus Industrie said there were indications
that human error caused Sunday's crash, but the president of the
airline's pilot's union said its engines may have failed to restart
at the pilot's command.
   The jet went into service in April for Air France and British
Airways, and last Thursday, Air France took delivery of the plane
that crashed.
   The Airbus A320 is the first civilian airliner equipped with a
fully computerized flight-control system, which the manufacturer
says permits safer, electronically controlled flight.
   The aircraft carries 168 people and consumes 40 percent less
fuel than similar two or three engine jets.
   The Northwest agreement calls for delivery of up to 100
A320-200s between 1990 and 1995. Northwest must make a firm
commitment on 10 A320s for delivery in 1990 and 1991.
   The Toulouse, France-based Airbus Industrie consortium says it
has more than 500 orders or letters of intent to buy the A320.
France, Britain, West Germany and Spain are partners in Airbus.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880627-0094 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-27-88 1228EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Botswana     06-27 0251</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Botswana,0258</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Another South African Arrested In Connection With Raid</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GABORONE, Botswana (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A third South African has been
arrested in connection with an army incursion into Botswana,
authorities said Monday.
   Barry Viviers appeared in magistrate's court on a charge of
unlawful possession of a hand grenade found at his home Friday.
   Police said Viviers, who lives in Gaborone, had been in contact
with a suspected South African commando, Theodore Hermansen, on the
day before the June 20 cross-border mission.
   During the incursion, a five-member South African army unit
fired at a group of Botswana policemen, injuring three officers.
Those five soldiers escaped back to South Africa, but Hermansen and
a colleague, Johannes Basson, were arrested at a roadblock and have
been charged with violating Botswana's National Security Act.
   Viviers, 20, was ordered held pending a bail application later
this week. He was born in Botswana but lived for most of his life
in South Africa before returning to Gaborone a few years ago.
   South African officials have said the army unit entered Botswana
on an intelligence mission as part of the campaign to combat the
African National Congress guerrilla movement. It has neither
confirmed nor denied Botswana's allegation that Hermansen and
Basson were linked to the mission.
   Botswana said the commandos planned a raid on a target in
Gaborone and has accused South Africa of ``state terrorism.''
   South Africa claims its soldiers fired at the policemen after
being fired at first. Botswama says the police patrol was unarmed.
</TEXT>
