<1ST_LINE>r a PM-BrawleyCase     06-27 0520</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Brawley Case,0538</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Brawley Advisers Blast Giuliani and TV Station</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Advisers to Tawana Brawley, the young woman who
refuses to help police investigate her charges that she was
assaulted, are accusing a federal prosecutor and a television
reporter of conspiring to obstruct justice.
   Meanwhile, Manhattan Borough President David Dinkins questioned
the tactics of the three advisers, accusing them of doing damage to
the civil rights movement with their ``wild charges.''
   Dinkins, the city's highest-ranking elected black official, made
his comments Sunday about the Rev. Al Sharpton and Brawley
attorneys C. Vernon Mason and Alton Maddox Jr. on WABC-TV's
``Eyewitness News Conference.''
   The Brawley case began when the teen-ager was found last
November in a plastic bag smeared with dog excrement. She claimed
that she had been raped and assaulted by six white men.
   Her family and family advisers have since claimed that she
cannot get justice from authorities and her family has refused to
cooperate in the investigation.
   At a news conference Sunday, Mason and Sharpton threatened a
$100 million lawsuit against WCBS-TV in response to Saturday's
arrest of Samuel McClease.
   McClease had claimed in an interview with the station that he
had tape recordings that would cast doubt on the Brawley story, but
tapes he gave to federal authorities were blank and he was charged
Saturday with obstruction of justice and perjury.
   ``Certainly with the arrest of Mr. McClease, Channel 2 (WCBS)
has knowingly participated in slandering me, slandering the
Brawleys and slandering the advisers,'' Sharpton said.
   McClease, 26, a self-proclaimed surveillance expert, claimed
that Sharpton had hired him to bug conversations involving Mason
and Maddox.
   In the WCBS broadcast, McClease said the tapes revealed that
there was no evidence to support the black teen-ager's contentions
that she was abducted by a gang of white men, and that the advisers
knew this.
   The advisers said Sunday that they want WCBS reporter Mike
Taibbi and U.S. Attorney Rudolph Giuliani to explain why they gave
credence to McClease.
   ``Rudolph Giuliani and Mike Taibbi met, agreed, conspired,
combined to obstruct justice in the Tawana Brawley case,'' Mason
said. Maddox was not at the news conference.
   Sharpton said Giuliani helped Taibbi ``undermine black
leadership'' by subpoenaing McClease.
   Giuliani said, ``The statements are illogical and not worthy of
response.''
   Phyllis Stewart, a spokeswoman for WCBS-TV, said the station
would have no comment on the advisers' statements.
   Dinkins said on WABC-TV that he was particularly bothered by
comments Sharpton, Maddox and Mason have made about Gov. Mario
Cuomo and state Attorney General Robert Abrams.
   The advisers have compared Abrams, who is special prosecutor in
the case, to Adolf Hitler and labeled Cuomo a racist.
   ``I don't think they help their cause or ours by calling the
governor and Robert Abrams and others names,'' Dinkins said. ``I
mean, just wild charges, unsubstantiated and, I am confident,
untrue.''
   ``As they seek to focus on the inequities in the criminal
justice system ... they don't do the cause any good and they
certainly don't appear to be assisting the cause of bringing to
justice the culprit in the Tawana Brawley situation,'' Dinkins said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
