<DOCNO> AP880627-0103 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-27-88 1335EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Brites     06-27 0423</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Brites,0443</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bright and Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>THOMAS, Okla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Heard about the upscale Ben & Jerry's ice
cream from Vermont? How about some Shorty & Blondie's from Oklahoma?
   Shorty and Blondie are mules that crank out homemade ice cream
when attached to an ice cream making machine assembled by Bud
Potter.
   ``It's just like making ice cream on the back porch, but instead
of using a handle to turn the freezer, a pair of mules does the
job, walking around the freezer in a circle,'' Potter said.
   Potter, his brother, Don, and Ed Atkin, began making the
mule-powered ice cream last summer, and they attract a crowd
whereever they go.
   Atkin selected Shorty, a 600-pound white mule, to turn the
freezer.
   ``He's a good little mule and he can do it,'' Potter said. ``But
it's pretty hard to do it by himself. It's better with two (mules)
on it.''
   That's when Blondie, a matching mule, entered the picture.
   ``Ed hand-picked them to make it look just right,'' Potter said.
``The mules need to be a certain size and matched up to look good.''
   Once the mules get started, it takes about 20 minutes and 12
sacks of ice to turn out a freezer full of ice cream, Potter said.
   ``Shorty knows all about making ice cream, but he doesn't like
it. He likes oats and alfalfa hay,'' Potter said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>ST. PAUL, Kan. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   This small town's designation as a ghost
town has some of its 700 residents irked.
   ``How dare he say we're dead? We're not dead,'' said Ruth
Schoenhofer, who has lived in St. Paul for 40 years.
   The town in southeast Kansas is included in a new traveler's
guide called ``Ghost Towns of Kansas,'' by Topeka historian Daniel
Fitzgerald.
   ``We'd love to have him come down here on a Friday night,''
agreed Betty Brogan. ``He could just see how much action there is
around here.''
   St. Paul has a post office, construction company, bank, fire
department, tavern, a couple of beauty shops, three gas stations
and a high school graduated 19 students last month.
   Fitzgerald, 29, an archivist at the Kansas Center for Historical
Research in Topeka, said he has been baffled by the fuss.
   He said he never claimed in his book that the town was actually
dead. Instead, he said, he defines a ghost town as ``a shadowy
semblance of its former self.''
   He said he included St. Paul in his book because the town's
regional importance and population has declined in the last hundred
years.
</TEXT>
