<2ND_LINE>PM-Biaggi-Wedtech,0161</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Won't Let Defense Call Meese in Wedtech Trial</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge today denied requests to call
Attorney General Edwin Meese III as a defense witness in the
racketeering trial of Rep. Mario Biaggi and six others.
   The defense wanted U.S. District Judge Constance Baker Motley to
allow them to call Meese, asserting that it was he who ``acted
corruptly'' in helping the Wedtech Corp.
   Biaggi, his eldest son, and five others are charged with turning
Wedtech, a now-bankrupt defense contractor, into a racketeering
enterprise that paid bribes to obtain no-bid government contracts.
   The defense wanted to call Meese and a former top aide of his to
show that Wedtech had connections with high Reagan administration
officials and didn't need to bribe Biaggi, D-N.Y., for his
assistance.
   But the judge ruled that Meese's testimony was ``not relevant to
anything that this jury has to decide'' about Biaggi's guilt or
innocence.
