<FILEID>AP-NR-06-27-88 1324EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Drought-GypsyMoths Bjt   06-27 0695</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Drought-Gypsy Moths, Bjt,0714</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gypsy Moths Expand Territory In United States</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Drought Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto upcoming</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MALCOLM JOHNSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HARRISON, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The light green leaves of some trees in
the middle of the dark green forest of Michigan's Lower Peninsula
have the fragile look of spring's new growth, and some scattered
trees show exposed, brown branches.
   The thinner growth is evidence of a ravenous little caterpillar
_ the juvenile stage of the gypsy moth _ that is making life
miserable for uncounted people across the United States.
   And the drought is increasing the damage, as trees already
weakened by lack of water try to fight off the effects of repeated
defoliation by the hungry caterpillar.
   ``Now, the trees are fighting just to stay alive,'' said Jim
Hanson, forest entomologist for the U.S. Forest Service in St.
Paul, Minn.
   Trees will use up food reserves putting out a new growth of
leaves, he said. ``They don't have anything left, and they start
declining.''
   Two or three defoliations can kill a tree, and the drought may
hasten that process, said Frank Sapio, forest pest specialist for
the Michigan Department of Natural Resources.
   The caterpillar likes oaks best and can kill 20 percent to 30
percent of the trees in a three-year infestation, Hanson said. But
the pest eats more than 200 plant species.
   From its initial foothold in New England, the gypsy moth is
slowly expanding its territory westward and southward. It's been
detected in all of Michigan's 83 counties.
   Experts offer little hope for homeowners driven to distraction
by caterpillars covering their houses and lawn furniture, stripping
their trees, defecating everywhere and stinking when they die.
   ``They are literally dripping off the eaves of homes,'' said
Ronald Priest, manager of the gypsy moth program for the Michigan
Department of Agriculture.
   Sue Eiseler moved to the Harrison area about three years ago,
but already she and her husband are thinking about leaving.
   ``We are totally covered,'' she said. ``This is the third year
our trees are totally stripped. It's a like a nightmare.''
   ``If they're chewing, you can sit and listen to them,'' state
Rep. Sid Ouwinga said. ``When you start getting 20 calls a day from
your constituents in one county, you know you have a problem.''
   There's no real threat to human health, although some people can
be allergic to the caterpillars.
   Experts have given up any hope of eradicating the pest and
endorse spraying chemicals only in selected spots. Other than that,
they advise people to reduce the nuisance by scraping gypsy moth
egg masses off houses and outdoor furniture and trying to keep the
caterpillars out of trees by putting bands of burlap or sticky
substances on the trunks.
   ``The biggest thing is for people to understand _ teaching them
that we can't eradicate them,'' said Rob Hallet, Clare County
chairperson for gypsy moth education. ``They're miserable, they're
a nuisance, but they're here. We can't get rid of them.''
   ``People demand something be done _ that translates into using
pesticides,'' Priest said. But at least one lawsuit filed by
environmentalists has blocked spraying of one chemical in part of
Clare County.
   ``That can be dangerous _ they're spraying poisons,'' Hallet
said.
   A map shows heavy infestations along the East Coast from Maine
to Maryland, some presence in Ontario and Quebec, wide infestations
covering much of Lower Michigan, spot outbreaks in Ohio, Illinois,
Indiana, Illinois, Wisconsin and Minnesota, and some detection of
the pest in Oregon and Washington.
   ``The female lays its eggs on just about anything,'' Hanson
said. ``When people move, they're transporting these egg masses
around the country.''
   According to experts in various states, a naturally occurring
virus killed many of the pests in Massachusetts; Ohio and Illinois
are generally free of the insect now; Connecticut expects to near
1987's figure of 127,452 acres defoliated; spraying in Oregon and
Minnesota reduced their problem; and the problem is in its earliest
stages in Colorado.
   In 1985, Michigan began a joint federal-state-local program of
voluntary spraying in 37 counties, and officials are testing
insects which feed on the moths. The state paid $250,000 for
spraying this year.
</TEXT>
