<1ST_LINE>u p PM-PoliticalRdp 3rdLd-Writethru a0586 06-27 0934</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Political Rdp, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0586,930</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Texas Treasurer Ann Richards to Be Democratic Keynoter</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates with Richards announcement, subbing top 2 grafs</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By LAURA KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The Democrats' pre-convention pace accelerated today as the
party named Texas State Treasurer Ann Richards to be the
convention's keynote speaker and as apparent presidential nominee
Michael Dukakis scheduled a quick trip to Washington to talk with
senators about a running mate.
   The choice of Ms. Richards to give the nationally televised
address was announced at a news conference in Washington. Earlier,
Dukakis aides said the senators with whom he'll meet on Wednesday
will include several mentioned as possible vice presidential
candidates.
   One possible source of friction at the party convention eased,
when Dukakis rival Jesse Jackson praised a proposed platform worked
out in Denver.
   The developments came as a new poll indicated that Dukakis is
continuing to run well ahead of Vice President George Bush, the
likely Republican presidential nominee, although it suggested there
is plenty of room for voters to change their minds since Dukakis is
still ``a blank page'' to many.
   Bush was back in Washington today after a one-day trip to
Columbus, Ohio, where he singled out defense issues as a key
battleground for the summer campaign. Dukakis was wrapping up a
four-day vacation on Nantucket.
   The selection of Ms. Richards as convention keynoter was said to
have originated with party officials, although the Dukakis campaign
embraced it.
   Ms. Richards is the first woman elected to statewide office in
Texas in 50 years, and her selection is likely to be seen as a
Democratic effort to court not only women's votes but Southern
support as well.
   Dukakis press secretary Mark Gearan said the Massachusetts
governor had decided to delay by a day a scheduled campaign trip
through the Midwest in order to spend Wednesday in private meetings
with 30 or more senators on Capitol Hill. But officials also said
the Massachusetts governor would spend part of his time talking
with prospective running mates.
   Dukakis has said he hopes to make his decision before the
convention opens on July 18, although aides dismissed published
reports that an announcement could be made this weekend.
   Dukakis' aides last week sent out requests for background
information on several prospective running mates, including Jesse
Jackson, Sens. Sam Nunn of Georgia, John Glenn of Ohio and Bob
Graham of Florida, as well as House Democratic Leader Tom Foley of
Washington.
   Others mentioned as possible running mates include Sen. Lloyd
Bentsen of Texas and Rep. Lee Hamilton of Indiana. Rep. Richard
Gephardt of Missouri, who sought the presidential nomination, also
has been mentioned.
   The Gallup poll released today showed Dukakis with a 13-point
lead over Bush, 53 percent to 40 percent, with 7 percent undecided.
The survey, based on interviews with 3,021 adults from May 13-22,
had a margin of error of 2 percentage points. Its results were in
line with a string of surveys putting Dukakis' edge at 10 points or
more.
   But the poll, conducted for the Times Mirror Corp., also
indicated that Dukakis' lead came more from voters' negative
feelings about Bush than positive feelings about the Democratic
nominee-to-be.
   Dukakis tried to keep his island sojourn nearly free of campaign
business. Gearan said Sunday the governor had not even talked by
telephone with aides in Denver, where platform drafters were at
work on a campaign manifesto.
   The document that emerged conformed more closely to the wishes
of the Dukakis camp than those of the Jackson forces.
   Jackson's calls for raising taxes on the rich, freezing the
Pentagon budget, pledging no first use of nuclear weapons and
supporting a Palestinian homeland were all turned aside.
   Still, Jackson said today on ABC-TV's ``Good Morning America,''
``In some measure, our mission is to find common ground in the
committee structure.''
   ``Where that cannot take place, we'll take it to the floor and
simply let the people air it out in the public,'' he said. However,
he added, ``Lets look at the plus side. There is language in that
platform about a pension fund, a reinvestment plan, that's a step
in the right direction. A commitment to fight drugs, a commitment
to a new Soviet-U.S. approach to third world development, a
commitment to ending apartheid in Southern Africa.''
   And Democratic rule-makers, meeting Saturday in Washington,
agreed to an overhaul of party rules _ which Jackson hailed as a
``victory for the people. ... a victory for democracy.''
   Under the agreement, the number of ``super delegates'' to the
1992 convention will be cut nearly in half, and all the other
delegates would be awarded to presidential candidates in proportion
to public suppor.
   During the primary season, Jackson bitterly criticized
delegate-selection rules, complaining that his delegate total did
not reflect his proportion of the popular vote.
   Bush was in Washington today, after a one-day trip to Columbus,
Ohio, where he blamed Congress for hampering the administration's
drug war.
   ``Congress is full of rhetorical heroes on the issue of drugs,
but when it comes to law enforcement, some of them go AWOL,'' or
absent without leave, he told a police group.
   The vice president told reporters traveling with him on Air
Force Two he would be spelling out foreign policy differences with
Dukakis. On defense in particular, he said, ``a very serious debate
... has not yet been joined.''
   ``Obviously he (Dukakis) will have to join it,'' he said. ``I
think I will come out well on that.''
   Bush criticized Dukakis' calls for unilateral nuclear weapons
cuts. ``How do we defend if we eliminate these systems he's calling
for?'' he asked.
</TEXT>
