<FILEID>AP-NR-06-27-88 1351EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-France-Crash 4thLd-Writethru a0553 06-27 1110</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-France-Crash, 4th Ld - Writethru, a0553,1140</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>PRECEDE Mulhouse</HEAD>
<HEAD>Preliminary Investigation Says Plane Flying Too Low</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 8 grafs to UPDATE with results of preliminary
investigation; pickup 4th graf pvs, ``The narrow-bodied ...''
^LaserPhotos NY6,7</NOTE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A new Airbus A320 which crashed and killed three
passengers had flown too low when it made a pass during a
demonstration flight at an air show in eastern France, officials
said Monday.
   The Director-General of the Civil Aviation Authority, Daniel
Tennenbaum, told a Paris news conference that the Air France jet
flew at an altitude of 30 feet when it made a low-flying pass over
an airfield near Mulhouse Sunday. He said the determination came
from a preliminary investigation of the crash.
   Fifty passengers were injured.
   In the eastern French town of Mulhouse, state prosecutor Jean
Volff also said the preliminary investigation of the crash showed
the plane was flying too low.
   ``The A320 passed at 30 feet altitude, which is completely
outside the technical norms when it is carrying passengers,'' Volff
said.
   Tennenbaum said the fully computerized aircraft needed eight
seconds to respond to the command of the pilot who, because of the
low altitude, had only five seconds to maneuver the plane upward.
   A spokesman for Airbus Industrie, the aircraft's manufacturer,
said earlier there were indications that human error caused the
crash Sunday of the Air France jet, which was carrying 133 people,
but the president of the airline's pilot's union said its engines
may have failed to restart at the pilot's command.
   Transport Minister Louis Mermaz said ``nothing for the moment
calls into question either the functioning of the aircraft or the
big Airbus project.''
   
   The narrow-bodied Airbus A320, developed by a European
consortium over four years at a cost of $2 billion, is the new
entry in the commercial aircraft market and a jet advertised as the
fastest-selling plane in aircraft history. It went into service in
April.
   The Air France twin-engine plane clipped some trees and plunged
from about 60 feet into a forest at the end of the airfield in
front of TV cameras and a crowd of about 1,000 people attending the
show. The aircraft burned and sent a pillar of black smoke in the
air.
   Only the plane's red, white and blue tail remained unscorched.
   A control tower official, who spoke on condition of anonymity,
said the jet appeared to lose power as it passed over the field in
Habsheim, a village about 15 miles from the Swiss border.
   Christian Roger, the pilot's union president, had said there
were indications that ``the engines failed to restart'' at the
pilot's command.
   Unlike other planes, he said, connections from the controls to
the engines are made through the computer and not directly by
cables.
   The newspaper l'Humanite reported today that pilot Michel
Asseline told a rescuer, ``I wanted to increase the power, but the
aircraft did not respond.'
   Jean-Marie Schreiber, a reporter for the newspaper L'Alsace who
was aboard, told the daily newspaper France-Soir he felt a jolt
when the plane started to climb after passing over the field.
   ``Then, all of a sudden, I had the feeling we had hit a pothole,
and I saw trees from the window,'' he said.
   One passenger, Roland Schmitted, said, ``We were flying low, and
I was afraid there would be a catastrophe ... I am a pilot, and I
said to myself, he's never going to make it over those trees.''
   He said passengers were able to get out after fire broke out
because the crew put down the evacuation chutes almost immediately.
   Officials said 50 people required hospitalization and some were
badly burned. They said there was only a rudimentary passenger list
and some aboard may have left the crash site without identifying
themselves.
   Air France and British Airways, which each have two A320s,
temporarily grounded their planes as a precaution. On Monday,
however, British Airways said it will resume using the aircraft on
Tuesday, saying i was satisified the plane is safe.
   No American airline uses the A320 yet, although Egan,
Minn.-based Northwest Airlines has 100 of the planes on order and
New York-based Pan American World Airways has 16 ordered with an
option to buy 34 more.
   In addition, two U.S. leasing companies have ordered the A320 _
GATX Air of San Francisco has asked for 10 of them and
International Lease Finance Corp. of Beverly Hills, Calif., has
three on order.
   Air France took delivery just Thursday of the plane that crashed
and flew it six times on Saturday.
   Airbus, a Toulouse, France-based consortium, says it has more
than 500 orders or letters of intent to purchase the A320. France,
Britain, West Germany and Spain are partners in Airbus.
   The French news agency Agence-France Presse reported Monday that
the Airbus 320 has had two serious electrical problems since April,
the first on the inaugural flight March 26 and the second June 23
on a flight that was to have gone to Amsterdam, but did not depart.
   The aircraft carries 168 people and consumes 40 percent less
fuel than similar two or three engine jets.
   It is the first civilian airliner equipped with a fully
computerized flight-control system, which the manufacturer says
permits safer, electronically controlled flight.
   Instead of the old control column in front of the pilot, there
is a ``pistol-grip'' side stick linked to five computers that
modify and relay the pilot's directions to wing and tail flaps.
   In the event of total failure of the electrical flight control
system and all computers, the jet is equipped with a mechanical
cable link to the tail that would allow the pilot to fly manually,
although with reduced maneuverablity.
   The plane operates with a two-man flight crew. Earlier this
year, pilots and flight engineers of France's largest domestic
carrier, Air Inter, called a series of protest strikes, saying
three crewmembers were needed for safety.
   Newspapers quoted Romain Kroes, a union spokesman, as saying
Sunday's accident proved the necessity for a third person in the
cockpit. He said a flight engineer is needed to take over manual
controls in case of failure of the electronic system of supplying
the plane's engines with fuel.
   Mermaz said both black boxes with flight data had been recovered
and officials were studying them.
   The government officials, who spoke on condition of anonymity,
said pilot Asseline and co-pilot Pierre Mazieres were not injured
and should be able to help investigators.
   The plane had flown from Paris and landed in Mulhouse, about 320
miles to the east, to take on additional passengers and was to
circle Mount Blanc in the Alps, then return to Paris via Mulhouse.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
