<HEAD>Fulton County Commissioner Sentenced To Six Years</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Adds one graf with background on Fulton Co.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOHN A. BOLT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A suspended Fulton County Commissioner who was
convicted last month on three counts of extortion was sentenced
today to six years in prison and fined $25,000.
   U.S. District Judge Orinda Evans sentenced A. Reginald Eaves to
six years on each of two counts, to run concurrently, and a
six-year suspended sentence on a third count, with five years on
probation.
   The judge also said he may not seek elective or appointive
office while in jail or on probation.
   The commissioner was accused of taking payments of $20,000 and
$10,000 from an undercover FBI agent posing as a developer in
exchange for his vote on a rezoning matter. Eaves said the payments
were for consulting work.
   The government had sought a 12-year sentence and fines and
restitution totaling $300,000. The defense had suggested community
service.
   Eaves has been suspended from his seat on the county commission,
and defense attorney David Walbert refused today to say whether
Eaves would appeal his conviction.
   Eaves would be likely to serve about 18 months of the six year
sentence before being eligible for parole, said Walbert.
   Meanwhile, Eaves was replaced by state Rep. Mary Young-Cummings
as president of the Georgia Association of Black Elected Officials.
   Mrs. Young-Cummings, of Albany, has been acting president of the
black politicians' group since Eaves' conviction. She was named
president Saturday as the group's 18-member executive board met in
Savannah.
   Fulton County, with a population of almost 600,000, includes
most of the city of Atlanta.
</TEXT>
