<1ST_LINE>r a AM-BusCrash     06-27 0323</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bus Crash,0331</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Thousands Express Sympathy After Accident</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ELIZABETHTOWN, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A minister has stacked up four boxes
full of cards from thousands of people expressing sympathy and
support for victims' families and survivors of the school bus
accident that killed 27 people.
   ``It sort of charges me up for the day,'' Don Tennison, pastor
at Radcliff First Assembly of God, said recently. ``It's been these
cards and things like that that've really helped keep me and my
wife going.''
   Fifteen members of First Assembly were among those killed May 14
when the bus was hit by a pickup truck. The bus was carrying riders
home from an amusement park. The truck driver, Larry Mahoney, later
was charged with 27 counts of murder.
   Tennison's son, Allen, was one of the 40 people who survived the
accident.
   ``There's some beautiful mail in there,'' said church secretary
Judy Wilson, nodding toward the boxes containing letters, poems and
cassette tapes.
   Branwyn Suko, a sixth-grader from Auburndale, Fla., printed a
letter to grieving parents, telling them: ``I'm sorry to hear that
your child was killed in the bus wreck. I'm sure he-she was very
nice. God will take care of it. I'm a Christian. Just keep praying.
I will pray for you.''
   Amanda Briggs, a member of a United Methodist Church in State
College, Pa., simply scribbled, ``Hang in There'' on a card filled
with other expressions of love and compassion.
   In a May 17 letter to church members, President Reagan wrote:
``Nancy and I were stunned and saddened to hear of the tragedy that
befell your church. ... Our hearts and prayers go out to each of
you.''
   Reagan urged the church members to ``take comfort, in the days
to come, in remembrance of your loved ones.''
   Tennison said that after parents and survivors take the mail
they want, he hopes the rest can be displayed in a special part of
the church library.
</TEXT>
