<FILEID>AP-NR-06-27-88 1709EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-US-ANZUS     06-27 0261</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-ANZUS,250</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Door Should Stay Open for New Zealand Return to ANZUS, Australian
Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Australia's defense chief said Monday the door
should be kept open for New Zealand to return to the three-cornered
military alliance with his country and the United States despite
the nuclear weapons dispute that brought New Zealand's ouster.
   Defense Minister Kim Beazley commented on the eve of the annual
ministerial meeting of the ANZUS pact. New Zealand was excluded
from it two years ago for barring U.S. nuclear-armed or -powered
warships from its ports.
   ``I can't say I see any developments in either New Zealand or
U.S. policy pointing to compromise,'' but ``it is very important to
hold open the possibility'' of restoring trilateral relations,
Beazley told reporters.
   Since the breakup, he said, ``We have tried to ensure that our
bilateral relations with the U.S. and with New Zealand are fully up
to speed, and substantial ... we'll continue on that course but do
not want to act in any way that would prevent the return to
trilateral.''
   Beazley said he assumes New Zealand ``would want to get back
into trilateral ANZUS arrangements'' if possible and must be
watching the current Washington meeting with interest. ``Of course
we talk to New Zealand constantly about our strategic perceptions
and relationships in our area,'' he added.
   Beazley and Australian Foreign Minister Bill Hayden are to meet
Tuesday and Wednesday with Defense Secretary Frank Carlucci and
Secretary of State George Shultz at the annual ANZUS session, which
also covers includes foreign policy, economic and procurement
matters.
