<1ST_LINE>u w AM-US-Mexico     06-27 0359</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Mexico,350</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>US Outraged Over Mexican Prisoner Release</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GEDDA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The State Department expressed outrage Monday
over Mexico's release of a Puerto Rican nationalist wanted in the
United States for terrorist activities.
   William Morales, 37, was released from prison late last week
after serving five years of an eight-year term for the murder of a
Mexican policeman. Mexican officials said he also was granted
political asylum.
   Morales was reportedly released after Mexican Foreign Secretary
Bernardo Sepulveda rejected a U.S. request for his extradition on
the ground he was a ``political fighter for the independence of
Puerto Rico'' who had been ``politically persecuted.''
   State Department spokesman Charles E. Redman, who indicated that
the United States had not been informed officially of Morales'
release, said allowing him to go free ``would be a serious blow to
international efforts to combat terrorism.''
   He said Morales was implicated in a 1975 plane bombing in New
York in which four people were killed and 60 injured and has been
sentenced to over 100 years in prison in the United States on
weapons possession charges.
   ``We are outraged and surprised by reports that Mexican
authorities may have released Mr. Morales,'' Redman said.
   Morales was arrested in New York in 1978 after a bomb he was
making detonated, blowing off most of both hands and disfiguring
his face. He escaped from U.S. custody a year later.
   He was said to be a leader of a Puerto Rican independence group
called the Armed Forces of National Liberation.
   Morales was arrested by Mexican authorities in 1983 after a
shootout with police in which a companion and a Mexican policeman
were killed. He received an eight-year prison term.
   Redman said U.S. officials have been told that Morales has been
turned over to the Mexican Secretariat of Government, which will
decide his eventual disposition.
   He said the administration is trying to clarify reports that
Mexico may grant Morales political asylum.
   ``We would be deeply disturbed that an individual with Morales'
record of criminal behavior, a convicted felon in both our
countries, should even be considered for possible political refugee
status,'' Redman said.
</TEXT>
