<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Lefebvre     06-27 0563</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Lefebvre,0578</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Traditionalists Claim Canon Law Allows Consecration</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HANNS NEUERBOURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The traditionalist movement of Archbishop Marcel
Lefebvre on Monday challenged the Vatican's warning that Lefebvre
will be automatically excommunicated if he consecrates four bishops
without papal approval.
   The consecration, scheduled for Thursday at a seminary in Econe,
Switzerland, would lead to the first schism in the Roman Catholic
church in more than a century.
   In a letter to the media, the director of the Econe seminary
cited a German expert on canon law that no sanctions can be applied
by the church against the faithful who act in an emergency.
   The Rev. Alain Lorans said in the letter it was ``wrong to claim
that the code inflicts this punishment automatically without taking
into account certain cases of emergency.''
   Lorans cited passages from a book published in 1984 by Georg
May, a professor at the University of Mainz, who wrote that ``an
emergency situation justifies emergency rights.''
   ``Those rights can only be claimed if all possibilities to
restore the normal situation by positive (valid) law have been
exhausted,'' May wrote. ``In an emergency situation, the pastors of
the church can take extraordinary measures to protect or restore
the activity of the Church.''
   The Rev. Roland Trauffer, secretary of the Swiss Conference on
Bishops and an expert on canon law, confirmed that canon law
provides immunity for those breaking it in an emergency.
   ``But it is wrong to claim that Lefebvre acts in a state of
emergency,'' Trauffer told The Associated Press in an interview.
``An emergency is something unforeseeable, something that occurs
suddenly without warning and in which the person concerned has no
possibility to communicate with the pope.''
   Lefebvre's plan to consecrate bishops was announced last year.
It is to ensure the ``continuity'' of the church that he says is
threatened by ``neo-protestantism'' and other ``auto-destructive''
trends since the Second Vatican Council 1962-65.
   The 82-year-old prelate has been suspended from his priestly and
episcopal functions since 1976 for his campaign against the
conciliar reforms, especially against new guidelines on religious
freedom and more contacts with other faiths. In defiance of this
ban, he has ordained more than 200 priests and has scheduled 16
more ordinations at Econe on Wednesday, on the eve of the
consecration of the four bishops.
   The bishops to be consecrated are Richard Williamson,
48-year-old English-born head of the Ridgefield, Conn.,
traditionalist seminary; Bernard Tissier de Mallerais, 43-year-old
secretary general of the traditionalist St. Pius X; Alfonso de
Galarreta, 31, Spanish-born head of a seminary at Buenos Aires,
Argentina; and Bernard Fellay of Switzerland, 30-year-old chief
administrator of Lefebvre's fraternity.
   Galarreta and Fellay are under the canonical age requirement of
35 for bishops.
   Preparations for the ceremonies were in full swing at Econe, a
vineyard-flanked hamlet in the Swiss canton of Valais where
Lefebvre's fraternity was founded _ then with official approval _
in 1970.
   A tent has been set up where Lefebvre will officiate, assisted
by 84-year-old Bishop Antonio de Castro Mayer of Brazil, the only
one among more than 2,000 Roman Catholic bishops who has sided
openly with Lefebvre.
   Several thousand followers, arriving by bus from France,
Switzerland and Germany, are expected to attend.
   The Bishop of Sion, Henri Schwery, whose diocese includes Econe,
has called for three days of special prayers for the ``unity of the
church'' beginning Tuesday.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880627-0129 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-27-88 1948EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Reagan-LieDetectors     06-27 0186</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Reagan-Lie Detectors,180</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>President Signs Bill Limiting Use of Polygraphs</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan signed without fanfare Monday
legislation strictly limiting the use of lie detector tests by
private employers.
   Reagan made no statement on the legislation, and his decision to
approve the bill was contained in a terse White House bill-signing
announcement.
   Congress had approved the legislation to protect job-seekers
from inappropriate use of polygraph exams by companies. The
congressional Office of Technology Assessment had estimated that as
many as 2 million such tests were administered in 1987, about 90
percent of them by private employers.
   The bill prohibits an employee from being discharged, dismissed,
disciplined, discriminated against or denied employment or
promotion solely on the basis of the test. To take action against
the worker, an employer has to have additional supporting evidence
under provisions of the bill that Reagan signed.
   The final version of the legislation approved by House-Senate
negotiators in May would prohibit most private-sector employers
from requiring their workers or job applicants to take lie detector
tests. Exceptions would be made for drug companies and those
providing security assistance.
</TEXT>
