<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Soviet-Unrest     06-27 0673</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Unrest,0687</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Finger Pointed at Brezhnev Protege for Ethnic Trouble</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANDREW KATELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former Politburo protege of the late Soviet
leader Leonid I. Brezhnev is partly to blame for grave ethnic
problems plaguing the southern republics of Azerbaijan and Armenia,
a Communist Party official said Monday.
   Vyacheslav A. Mikhailov, a party Central Committee specialist on
the Soviet Union's more than 100 ethnic groups, also said ethnic
Armenians are ignoring appeals to end a strike they began more than
a month ago.
   Mikhailov spoke at a news conference on how ethnic problems will
figure in the 19th Communist Party conference, a meeting of 5,000
delegates convening Tuesday in Moscow to review Soviet leader
Mikhail S. Gorbachev's policies.
   He said the demands of Armenians living in Nagorno-Karabakh to
take their region out of Azerbaijan and annex it to the Armenian
republic resulted from years of inattention to their cultural,
historical and social concerns. He singled out Geidar A. Aliev, a
Brezhnev protege who was party chief of Azerbaijan from 1969 to
1982, and his successor, Kyamran M. Bagirov.
   ``Those mistakes were made by the leadership of Azerbaijan both
by the party and govermental authorities, including the first
secretary of the republic Aliev and first secretary of Azerbaijan
Comrade Bagirov. Much damage has been done and really grave
damage,'' Mikhailov said.
   The criticism put Aliev even further into disgrace. He was
retired from the ruling Politburo on Oct. 21, 1987, ostensibly for
health reasons but under a cloud of poor performance in the
industries he oversaw. The previous blow was Thursday, when the
Azerbaijani party decided to turn a mansion Aliev had built for
Brezhnev in Baku, the republic's capital, into a wedding palace.
   Aliev, who headed the Azerbaijan KGB, was chosen a candidate
member of the Politburo in 1976 and was Brezhnev's last appointment
to full Politburo status in 1982. Although Brezhnev died before
Aliev's selection could be fully ratified, the new Soviet leader,
Yuri Andropov, could not overturn Brezhnev's decision, and Aliev
was made a member of the Politburo at the end of November, 1982,
according to Soviet historian Roy Medvedev.
   Bagirov also has lost his job. On May 21, he and Armenian party
chief Karen Demirchyan were retired, officially for health reasons
but most likely for mishandling the ethnic unrest.
   The Moscow government approved a package of housing and social
services improvements for Nagorno-Karabakh in March, but has yet to
review the annexation demand. Moscow party officials have already
rejected the demand.
   Armenians in Nagorno-Karabakh began a strike and street
demonstrations May 23 to demand their region be taken out of
Azerbaijan. Residents voted at a public meeting in
Nagorno-Karabakh's main city, Stepanakert, on Saturday to end the
strike, which has cost at least $50 million in economic losses,
Soviet media have reported. But Mikhailov said the walkout was
continuing.
   ``Today the leaders of Nagorno-Karabakh launched a campaign
among the working people of the region so as to stop strikes and to
resume the normal rhythm of work and to resolve the problem. We
didn't have any definite results as a matter of fact through
today,'' he said.
   Telephone calls to Stepanakert did not go through Monday. An
operator said communications to the region were disrupted.
   The legislature of Armenia voted earlier this month to endorse
annexation of Nagorno-Karabakh, but Azerbaijan's legislature
refused to give its consent.
   Mikhailov said a plenary meeting of the central party's 300-plus
member Central Committee would be held within a year to discuss the
problems of the Soviet Union's nationalities. Gorbachev has said
the problems are among the most severe facing the country.
   In another development, Mikhailov disclosed Monday that four
more Azerbaijanis had been convicted in the ethnic rioting in
February in the Azerbaijani city of Sumgait. Thirty-two people, 26
Armenians and six Azerbaijanis, were killed, and 200 people were
injured. Mikhailov did not say when the four had been convicted or
give the charges. Soviet officials have said more than 80 people
have been charged in the case.
</TEXT>
