<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Korea-Olympics     06-27 0369</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Korea-Olympics,0381</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Korean Police to Use Electric Cattle Prods As Riot Gear</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police will use electric cattle prods,
tear gas guns and other anti-riot measures to control demonstrators
and ensure the safety of the Seoul Olympics, police and news
reports said Monday.
   Home Minister Lee Choon-ku, in charge of the country's
135,000-member police force, ordered an extensive crackdown on
criminals and political radicals before the Olympics, police said.
   The former army general urged riot troops to be ``aggressive and
offensive'' and arrest all violent demonstrators, police said.
   Newspapers said Lee is giving police permission to use electric
cattle prods, gas guns and riot clubs against demonstrators, in
addition to tear gas.
   Security has emerged as a major concern for the Olympics, which
run from Sept. 17 to Oct. 2.
   South Korea has been hit by a wave of violent student protests
and labor unrest in recent months. So far this year, more than
960,000 people took part in about 4,300 mostly anti-government
demonstrations, up 80 percent from the same period last year.
   Some radical students, who have supported North Korea's demand
to be a co-host for the Games, have also staged demonstrations
against the Olympics.
   North Korea announced it will boycott the Olympics after South
Korea rejected its demand. North Korea charges that the Olympics in
Seoul would prolong the partition of the Korean peninsula.
   The two Koreas, divided since the end of World War II, are
bitter foes. The two nations fought the bloody Korean War from 1950
to 1953 after the North invaded the South.
   South Korea, the United States and other nations have expressed
concern that North Korea will try to disrupt the Olympics or that
international terrorist groups may stage attacks.
   Security officials from seven nations and 13 airlines will meet
this week to plan anti-terrorist measures for the Olympics, the
Foreign Ministry said today.
   The United States, Japan, the Philippines, Thailand, Malaysia,
Singapore, and South Korea will attend the meeting, officials said.
Hong Kong, a British colony, also plans to send delegates.
   Thirteen airlines that fly to Seoul will also discuss ways to
ensure security for their aircraft during the Olympics, officials
said. The airlines were not identified.
</TEXT>
