<1ST_LINE>r a AM-CollegePledge     06-27 0527</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-College Pledge,0541</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>College Pledge Spreads, Sparks Debate</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELISABETH DUNHAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ARCATA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Some colleges in California are handing
out small pledge cards along with diplomas asking graduates to
consider the ethical implications of their careers.
   At Humboldt State University Andrea Pickart picked up her degree
but politely declined the card and walked on.
   Her boyfriend, Peter Jain, also graduated at the May 14
ceremony. He signed the ``Graduation Pledge of Environmental and
Social Responsibility'' as soon as he got it.
   No one wants to go on record against ethical behavior, but
detractors feel the cards are unnecessary or an invasion of the
tradition of graduation.
   ``Politically and philosophically, I feel the pledges are
responsible. But I didn't feel any need to sign it. My own
convictions are strong enough to ensure that my employment is
socially and politically responsible,'' said Pickart, who holds a
master's degree in biology, works for a nature group and is a
member of 10 environmental groups.
   But Jain, who received a bachelor's degree in music, says he
looked at the pledge as an ``acknowledgement of the greater
consideration of the work you are doing.''
   Signing the card, the graduate pledges to ``thoroughly
investigate and take into account the social and environmental
consequences of any job opportunity I consider.''
   The pledges were included in this year's graduation ceremonies
at seven West Coast colleges and universities, including Humboldt
State, University of California-Santa Cruz and Stanford, where
President Donald Kennedy praised the pledge as something that
``should be as acceptable to the politically conservative as to the
liberal.''
   Some graduates have signed them publicly, others have taken them
home for further consideration and at least one has torn his up in
protest.
   ``A reality of the world is that literally every single action
that we take has consequenses on the world around us, not just on
ourselves,'' said Matt Nicodemus, a self-described ``full-time
peace activist'' who helped start the movement at Humboldt State
last year.
   ``We're asking people to look closely at as many of the
consequenses as they can identify and look at personal values. Once
you've found those, use them as your ethical and political
yardstick.''
   ``We want them to know it is possible to investigate the
consequences,'' he added. ``In the past, that has not been the
norm. We're saying we think it would be a good idea if that became
the norm.''
   Some opponents say the pledge is coercive. Others believe
including the pledge in graduation ceremonies erodes tradition.
   The most vocal opponent at Humboldt is recent graduate David
Lofink. As a student government representative last semester, he
vowed to tear up the pledge during the ceremony.
   ``I think I hugged my mother first, and then I tore it up,''
Lofink said.
   He said he's concerned the university will have difficulty
turning down similar requests from other groups.
   ``When does it stop? Once you've let one group come in with
their idea on a pledge, when do you say no?'' he said. ``Most
students are indifferent. My philosophy is that most want to get
through college, out the door and on to a job.''
</TEXT>
