<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Iran-Resistance     06-27 0465</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Iran-Resistance,460</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Anti-Khomeini Marchers Cite Recent Military Victories in Iran</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 2,000 opponents of the Ayatollah
Ruhollah Khomeini staged a rally and march Monday to mark the
seventh anniversary of their group's expulsion from Iran and to
celebrate a recent military victory along the Iran-Iraq border.
   Two members of Congress addressed the noisy rally across the
street from the White House, terming the People's Mujahedeen of
Iran a legitimate exiled opposition movement and comparing them to
``freedom fighters'' the United States supports elsewhere in the
world.
   ``There is no question in my mind yours is a just cause,'' said
Rep. Mervyn Dymally, D-Calif., a member of the House Foreign
Affairs Committee. Dymally said he is trying to build diplomatic
and political support for the group, which is conducting its own
war against the Khomeini regime.
   A crowd that police estimated at 2,700 held neatly printed
banners condemning Khomeini and bearing photos of the resistance
movement's leaders, Massoud and Maryam Rajavi.
   Rep. Donald Lukens, R-Ohio, also spoke to the group, and told a
reporter he sees the organization as a force to establish democracy
in Iran. He said he had not even heard of the group until six
months ago, but had since become persuaded of its legitimacy.
   The United States is officially neutral in the eight-year war
between Iran and Iraq, and in the past has labeled the Mujahedeen a
terrorist organization. That criticism has been moderated in recent
months, however, and there have been staff-level contacts between
the State Department and the opposition group.
   At a press briefing before the rally, the group's international
affairs secretary, Moshen Reza'i, said the capture last week of the
Iranian city of Mehran by anti-Khomeini troops marked ``a military,
political and social turning point'' in its struggle.
   He said the group's National Liberation Army of Iran had
inflicted 8,000 casualties in four days of fighting, taken 1,500
prisoners and seized or destroyed $2 billion in weapons. Reza'i
said rebel troops had taken 44 tanks and some U.S.-made anti-tank
and anti-aircraft missiles.
   The town of Mehran itself has little strategic value and
virtually no civilian population, and was only lightly defended by
Khomeini's troops. But the victory was seen as having political
significance as one in a string of recent defeats for the Iranian
regime.
   Reza'i denied that his organization is funded by Iraq, saying
Iraq provides only sanctuary for the rebels along their border with
Iran. He declined to say how many rebel troops are under arms.
Press reports have put the group's strength at about 10,000.
   He said the group was not seeking military backing from the
United States, but was pressing for adoption of a broad embargo on
purchase of Iranian oil and an international embargo on weapons
sales to Iran.
</TEXT>
