<1ST_LINE>r a AM-MedicaidReform     06-27 0460</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Medicaid Reform,0471</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>AMA Proposes Massive $24 Billion Medicaid Overhaul</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM C. HIDLAY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A plan by the American Medical Association to
expand the government's Medicaid health insurance program to cover
27 million more poor people is laudable but may be unaffordable,
says one official.
   The report issued at the AMA's policy-making convention
recommends that Medicaid be expanded to cover 27 million more poor
people. The federal-state program now serves about 19 million poor,
elderly, blind and disabled.
   Members of the AMA's House of Delegates are expected to act on
the report during the convention, which runs Monday through
Thursday.
   ``The Medicaid program is totally inadequate to address the
problem of uninsured and underinsured people in the United
States,'' said Dr. William Hotchkiss, outgoing AMA president. ``As
physicians, we feel we must take the position of advocates for
making health care available to all low-income people.''
   The report proposes a massive overhaul of the Medicaid program
at an estimated annual cost of $24 billion. It calls for expanding
Medicaid to provide coverage for medical care to an estimated 27
million people who are living at or below the poverty level but not
receiving government health-care benefits.
   At 1988 spending levels, the AMA's proposal would raise
Medicaid's cost from $52 billion to $76 billion, but it doesn't
recommend how to pay for the increase.
   ``I think it's a laudable attempt by the AMA to address the
issue of how we provide medical care to the poor and working poor
of our country,'' said Dean Schott, a spokesman for the Illinois
Department of Public Aid, which administers the program in this
state.
   ``But the AMA, I think, has an obligation to also suggest how
this program would be funded. Do we raise taxes to pay for it? Do
we shift money from one program to another?'' Schott said Sunday.
   The AMA study found that an estimated 60 percent of U.S.
residents whose incomes are below the national poverty level don't
qualify for Medicaid because the eligibility standards vary widely
between states.
   To reduce these inequities, the AMA proposes creating uniform
national standards of eligibility and uniform payments for medical
care.
   When the federal goverment established Medicaid in 1965 it
failed to set uniform standards and any changes in the program
would require its approval.
   Without national standards, the program has evolved into a
``patchwork quilt'' with a wide variation in benefits among the
states, said Dr. Robert McAfee, an AMA trustee and a surgeon from
Portland, Maine.
   To qualify for Medicaid in 1986, for example, a family of three
who received welfare could have an income of no more than $1,416 in
Alabama, but in Alaksa the maximum income is $8,800, the AMA report
said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880627-0139 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-27-88 2032EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Cambodia-Vietnam     06-27 0341</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Cambodia-Vietnam,0351</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>400 Vietnamese Troops Leave For Home</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER ENG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KOMPONG CHHNANG, Cambodia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 400 Vietnamese troops
left central Cambodia on Monday as part of what Vietnam says will
be its largest troop withdrawal since it invaded Cambodia nearly a
decade ago.
   The Vietnamese troops boarded trucks and headed south from
Kompong Chhnang toward the capital, Phnom Pehn, local officials
said.
   The officials said the pullout left only 200 Vietnamese soldiers
in Kompong Chhnang, a central province away from the main
battlefields along Cambodia's border with Thailand. They said the
remaining troops would leave Oct. 25.
   Vietnam announced in May it would withdraw 50,000 troops from
neighboring Cambodia by the end of the year, beginning in June. It
also said all of its estimated 120,000 troops would be gone by
1990, leaving the fighting to the forces of the Phnom Penh
government it installed after the 1978 invasion.
   The Vietnamese have been fighting a coalition of guerrilla
forces in Cambodia that includes the communist Khmer Rouge, the
non-communist Khmer People's Party and followers of former leader
Prince Norodom Sihanouk.
   Vietnamese authorities have said they plan to fly their entire
military command in Cambodia from Phnom Penh to Ho Chi Minh City,
formerly Saigon, on Thursday.
   Chhim Thoeun, vice chairman of the Kompong Chhnang provincial
party committee, told The Associated Press on Monday that all
Vietnamese social, economic and military experts also would leave
Cambodia by the end of year.
   ``The people in the remote villages are not happy with the
(Vietnamese) withdrawal'' because they fear the Khmer Rouge might
return to power, Chhim said. The Khmer Rouge murdered hundreds of
thousands of people during the bloody 1975-78 reign of Pol Pot.
   Chhim said 132,000 people were killed in Kompong Chhnang
province alone under the Khmer Rouge, and another 300,000 were
reported missing.
   Mok Vanny, chief of the Cabinet of the provincial Peoples
Committe, the local government, noted that ``from 1979 up until
now, the provincial town has never been touched by an enemy
attack.''
</TEXT>
