<1ST_LINE>r a AM-SovietReunion     06-27 0299</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet Reunion,0307</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviet Refusenik and Wife To Unite in Washington</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOCA RATON, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A neurologist who has seen her Soviet
refuesnik husband just once in eight years says she always knew
they eventually would be reunited.
   Dr. Galina Vileshina and her husband, Pyatras Pakenas, were to
meet Tuesday in Washington, D.C., as he steps off the plane from
West Germany, said Ken Klein, an aide to U.S. Sen. Bob Graham.
   ``In my heart I've always been ready for him,'' Ms. Vileshina
said. ``In my heart I always knew he would come.''
   Pakenas' 18 requests for an exit visa were denied until May, but
he kept in touch with his wife through daily letters and weekly
telephone calls from Moscow.
   Ms. Vileshina, 52, last saw her husband during a 10-day visit to
Russia last year. She expressed concern about his high blood
pressure and said he needed better medical care.
   Pakenas, 55, left the Soviet Union on Friday, stopping in West
Germany. A Capitol Hill reception for the couple is scheduled
Wednesday.
   Ms. Vileshina enlisted the aid of politicans, human rights
activists, journalists and other ``divided couples'' in her
attempts to help her husband leave the Soviet Union. Her efforts
included meetings with President Reagan and Secretary of State
George Shultz.
   ``She really didn't give up, and it was tough on her,'' said
Orest Deychak of the Helsinki Commission in Washington, a group
that monitors human rights. ``Her level of commitment is
phenomenal. This case is a result of a lot of concentrated effort.''
   The couple originally applied to emigrate from the Soviet Union
10 years ago, but only Ms. Vileshina and their son were permitted
to leave in 1980. They lived in New York until 1985, when they
moved to Florida and became American citizens.
</TEXT>
