<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Scotus-Roadblock     06-27 0320</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Scotus-Roadblock,310</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court to Hear Appeal in California Roadblock Case</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court on Monday agreed to hear an
appeal by the family of a man killed when the allegedly stolen car
he was driving smashed into a police roadblock.
   The court said it will decide in the case from California
whether the roadblock _ a tractor-trailer placed at night in the
middle of a highway _ may have been an unreasonably dangerous means
of apprehending the driver.
   William James Caldwell was chased by Inyo County, Calif.,
sheriff's deputies for 25 miles on the night of Oct. 23, 1984. The
sheriff's office believed Caldwell was driving a stolen car.
   At one point during the pursuit, a deputy radioed ahead to set
up a roadblock. A tractor-trailer owned by Missouri-Nebraska
Express and driven by James M. Holmgren was placed by the deputies
in the middle of Route 395, blocking both lanes of the highway.
   Also, a sheriff's car was positioned in front of the
tractor-trailer with its headlights directed at the oncoming car
driven by Caldwell.
   Caldwell slammed into the rig and died shortly after the
collision.
   His mother, Georgia Brower, and his fiancee, Renee King, sued
the county and its sheriff's office on behalf of themselves and
Scott Daniel King, the son of Ms. King and Caldwell who will be 3
years old next week.
   The 9th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals last year ordered further
lower hearings to determine whether the sheriff's office violated
Caldwell's due process rights protected by the 14th Amendment to
the Constitution.
   But the appeals court threw out the claim that Caldwell was
``seized'' unlawfully in violation of rights under the 4th
Amendment.
   Caldwell's mother and fiancee are seeking to reinstate the 4th
Amendment claim in their suit against the county, its sheriff's
department and the sheriff's deputies who set up the roadblock.
   The case is Brower vs. Inyo County, 87-248.
</TEXT>
