<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel-Begin,0478</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Begin's Son Says He Will Run For Parliament</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALLYN FISHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The son of former Prime Minister Menachem Begin
said Monday he would run for a parliament seat with the right-wing
Herut Party that his father founded.
   Benjamin Zeev Begin, 44, not only looks like his father but he
has some of the older politician's fiery oratorical style.
   He has teased his supporters by refusing to confirm his
candidacy until just days before Herut's 1,000 Central Committee
members meet Wednesday to choose their candidates for the national
elections in November.
   Begin's announcement signaled a long anticipated move into
politics that party leaders hope will attract new voters to the
Herut Party, a senior partner in the ruling Likud coalition.
   The older Begin, 74, founder of the Herut Party and a survivor
of the Nazi Holocaust, has lived a reclusive existence in Jerusalem
since stepping down from the premiership in 1983.
   Party officials say the younger Begin _ known as ``Benny'' _
should boost prospects for Herut.
   The prospective candidate said he doesn't expect automatic
support at Wednesday's party convention.
   ``I'm not counting on anything, I have a lot of (lobbying) work
to do,'' Begin, a geologist by profession, told Army radio.
   But Herut legislators and other party leaders believe the
bespectacled Begin will be a shoe-in.
   Yossi Ahimeir, an aide to Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir, said he
expects Begin will also attract votes for the Likud, which faces a
close contest with the left-leaning Labor Party in November.
   ``He is a man who can attract votes, maybe even help gain us an
extra seat,'' Ahimeir told The Associated Press.
   A public opinion poll published Friday in the Yediot Ahronot
daily showed Labor with a slight edge over Likud.
   The poll gave Labor 42 out of 120 seats in the Knesset and Likud
only 40, while the remaining seats would be divided among several
smaller parties.
   Like his father, Benny Begin is a hawk and objects to
relinquishing the Israeli-occupied territories to the Palestinians.
The Herut Party considers the West Bank and Gaza Strip to be
inextricably linked to the history of Israel. Begin, a researcher
at Hebrew University in Jerusalem, gradually entered politics over
the past two years by giving interviews and appearing at party
meetings.
   He told the Hadashot daily he weighed his options carefully
before deciding to enter politics and also indicated he had
consulted closely with his father.
   Menachem Begin has never explained why he quit his job five
years ago. Aides say the older Begin was melancholy over Israel's
heavy casualties following his government's decision to invade
Lebanon in 1982, and depressed about the death of his wife, Aliza,
the same year.
</TEXT>
