<FILEID>AP-NR-06-27-88 2050EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-FuelSpill-EPA     06-27 0476</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Fuel Spill-EPA,490</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Report: Tougher Regulations Needed On Oil Spills</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFF BARKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The massive fuel spill in the Ohio River last
January demonstrated the need for stiffer regulations to guard
against such accidents, a congressional report said Monday.
   The Congressional Research Service said in a 21-page analysis
that Ashland Oil Inc. complied with federal standards in assuming
responsibility for the difficult cleanup of more than 700,000
gallons of diesel fuel from a terminal near Pittsburgh on Jan. 2.
   The problem, CRS said, appears to lie in loosely-written
regulations that make it difficult for the Environmental Protection
Agency to detect problems before they occur. The research agency
noted that it was only after the collapse of an Ashland tank that
EPA found faults with the company's spill prevention plan.
   The fuel-tank collapse at Ashland's Floreffe Terminal caused the
contamination of drinking water in Pennsylvania, West Virginia and
Ohio. The rupture stemmed from a dime-sized flaw in the tank's
nearly 50-year-old steel wall.
   Ashland and other owners of above-ground oil tanks holding more
than 660 gallons are required to file oil spill prevention plans
which must be reviewed every three years. Ashland's plan was on
file near Pittsburgh, as required.
   But the government did not learn about alleged flaws in the plan
until after the accident. EPA said in a memorandum on Jan. 15 that
Ashland's Spill Prevention Control and Countermeasures plan ``does
not adequately address spill prevention and control specific to the
facility.''
   ``Instead,'' the EPA said, ``it merely paraphrases the SPCC
regulations.''
   But Monday's report said the EPA never saw the plan before the
accident because regulations only require that the document be
prepared, not that it be inspected by EPA.
   Under the regulations, EPA only gets involved after spills have
occurred, unless it has reason to suspect problems.
   ``Minor spills should not be the only reason for an SPCC plan to
come before federal and state officials,'' CRS said in the report.
``More automatic review by EPA and state officials might be
desired, and perhaps the regulations should state this.''
   CRS also said Congress should consider harsher penalties for
companies that fail to comply with spill prevention regulations.
   The regulations now call for penalties of $5,000 for each day
the violation continues. ``This could be construed as to have very
limited application, perhaps technical violations of only one or
two days duration,'' CRS said.
   The EPA has been reviewing whether problems with Ashland's spill
prevention plan merit penalties.
   Ashland spokesman Roger Schrum said Monday that company believes
the plan met EPA regulations.
   ``We have not been fined and it's been our contention that we
had an adequate plan,'' he said.
   The CRS report was requested by Sen. Jay Rockefeller, D-W.Va.
The senator said he was ``committed to pursuing legislation drawing
from CRS recommendations to prevent future spills.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
