<1ST_LINE>r w AM-China'sAgriculture     06-27 0203</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-China's Agriculture,200</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Steady Gain in Chinese Grain Output Seen by Next Century</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   China's grain production may increase by as
much as 25 percent to around 500 million metric tons by the year
2000 from an average of 394 million tons in the 1980s, an
Agriculture Department report said Monday.
   ``Area sown to grain probably will decrease over the next 12
years, but improved yields could boost total output,'' the report
said. ``However, per capita consumption probably will rise slowly,
as gains in output may be offset by increases in population and
(livestock) feed use.''
   Although small amounts of corn and other so-called coarse grains
are likely to be exported by efficient producers in the Northeast
and rice producers in the South, China is expected to remain a net
grain importer.
   ``Costal urban areas will import sizable quantities of wheat for
human consumption and limited quantities of feed grains,'' the
department's Economic Research Service said.
   U.S. agricultural exports to China in the fiscal year that began
last Oct. 1 could exceed $400 million in value, about double the
$211 million of 1986-87, the report said. A number of subsized
sales of U.S. wheat have helped account for the increase.
</TEXT>
