<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Trains Collide In Paris Station; At Least Four Dead</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 2 grafs to UPDATE with lower confirmed death toll,
but expected to rise. PICKS up 2nd graf pvs bgng, Cars were
buckled...</NOTE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two suburban trains collided at a Paris train
station today, killing at least four people, injuring 40, and
leaving an unknown number trapped inside the two trains, police
said.
   Earlier, unofficial reports put the number of dead at 15.
Although the official toll was lower, police said the number of
dead was expected to rise as workers pulled more bodies from the
wreckage.
   Cars were buckled from the violent impact of the accident.
   As many as five people were seriously injured in the accident,
according to rescue workers.
   The collision occurred shortly after 7 p.m. (1 p.m. EDT) on the
Gare de Lyon station's underground level, said fire officials
handling rescue efforts.
   The oncoming train entering the underground level of the
station, on the Right Bank of the Seine River in eastern Paris,
crashed into the rear of another train about to leave, according to
witnesses.
   The engine of one train was mounted on the rail cars at the end
of the other. The front of the oncoming train was gaping opon.
   Details of the accident were not immediately clear.
   Rescue workers set up an emergency station in the station. Its
underground section was sealed off while the operation continued.
   Transport Minister Louis Mermaz went to the scene of the
accident.
   Other details about the accident were not immediately available.
</TEXT>
