<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Drought-Hamburger     06-27 0135</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Drought-Hamburger,130</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Drought Will Mean More Burgers in School Cafeterias Next Fall</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The summer drought will put more hamburger
into school cafeterias next fall when children return to class,
Agriculture Secretary Richard E. Lyng announced Monday.
   An additional $50 million was authorized to buy surplus ground
beef for donation to schools and other institutions. Officials
estimated the money will buy about $45 million of bulk frozen
ground beef, in addition to the regularly scheduled purchases.
   In 1986-87, USDA spent $113 million for 115 million pounds of
frozen ground beef for donation to schools.
   Drought has reduced forage supplies and has forced more cows
onto the market, depressing prices. According to department
figures, Utility-grade cows sold for $50 per 100 pounds of live
weight in May, and by mid-June were bringing $37.50.
</TEXT>
