<FILEID>AP-NR-06-27-88 2055EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Drought-Feed     06-27 0140</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Drought-Feed,130</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>USDA Allows Farmers in Drought Areas to Sell Some Hay</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Farmers in 1,502 counties designated for
drought aid will be allowed to cut hay on conservation land and
sell it to others, Agriculture Secretary Richard E. Lyng said
Monday.
   Regulations earlier permitted farmers only to receive harvesting
expenses if hay was sold. Lyng said the rules were changed to
``provide incentives to producers'' to increase hay supplies in
drought-stricken areas.
   A related action will allow producers in the eligible counties
to use consevation acreage to be green-chopped for immediate
feeding to livestock or for silage. This is in addition to
harvesting for hay.
   More information on these and other changes in the use of
conservation land for livestock forage can be obtained at local
offices of the Agricultural Stabilization and Conservation Service,
officials said.
</TEXT>
