<FILEID>AP-NR-06-27-88 2001EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-SurrogacyBan     06-27 0456</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Surrogacy Ban,0465</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Governor Signs Bill; Paid Surrogate Parenting Contracts Outlawed
In Michigan</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHERINE RIZZO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LANSING, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gov. James Blanchard signed into law
Monday a ban on pregnancy for pay, making Michigan the first state
to establish surrogate parenting as a crime.
   Brokers who arrange surrogate-parent contracts in Michigan will
be subject to felony penalties of up to five years in jail and a
$50,000 fine under the statute, effective Sept. 1. Those who
contract for a birth or agree to bear a child for money will risk
misdemeanor penalties of up to 90 days in jail and a $10,000 fine.
   Blanchard said he was signing the bill ``with reservations'' but
added: ``It is a significant improvement over the uncertainty and
confusion of existing state law. By taking the profit out of
childbirth, it stands firm against the buying and selling of human
life.
   ``Taking no action to regulate surrogacy contracts would be more
harmful than taking incomplete or imperfect action.''
   State Sen. Connie Binsfeld, a former Michigan Mother of the
Year, pushed the bill through the Legislature. She has said her
goal was to drive out of Michigan one of the nation's most prolific
surrogate matchmakers: Dearborn attorney Noel Keane. Keane takes
credit for arranging 228 surrogate births, including New Jersey's
``Baby M.''
   Under the new law, women who want to bear a child then give up
the baby to another couple still could do so and brokers could
still arrange surrogate births, but they all would have to do it
for free.
   Typically, infertile couples pay a broker $10,000 to match them
with a would-be mother. They pay another $10,000 to the woman who
agrees to be artifically inseminated, carry the child, then give up
custody. They also pay for the inseminations, medical procedures,
prenatal care, hospital bills and other pregnancy-related expenses.
   The new Michigan law declares those contracts unenforceable. If
people still wish to enter such a pact, the mother can be
reimbursed for her medical expenses and other pregnancy-related
expenses but nothing else.
   Despite the new law, some people question whether it might be
legal for a Michigan couple to sign a contract in another state and
carry out everything else in Michigan.
   Michigan is the first state to attach criminal penalties to
surrogate-parent contracts, but not the first to tackle the issue.
   Kentucky and Louisiana have enacted laws declaring such
contracts illegal, but don't impose criminal penalties. Nebraska
doesn't recognize the legal validity of surrogate-parenting
contracts. Indiana has put enforcement of such arrangements on hold
while the issue is researched, and proposed regulations were vetoed
in Arkansas. In the landmark ``Baby M'' case, the New Jersey
Supreme Court outlawed surrogate-parenting contracts in that state.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880627-0160 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-27-88 1731EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w AM-Soviet-Nicaragua     06-27 0402</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Nicaragua,400</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviet Arms Deliveries To Nicaragua May Be Tapering Off</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NORMAN BLACK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Military Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet Union has continued to ship arms to
Nicaragua despite a cease-fire and peace talks between the
Sandinista government and the U.S.-backed Contra rebels, but the
amount of war materiel being delivered appears to be dropping
rapidly, Pentagon figures show.
   During the first five months of the year, Russia and its Warsaw
Pact allies shipped 5,500 metric tons _ or about 6,050 regular tons
_ of military equipment to the Sandinistas, according to Defense
Department estimates released Monday.
   By comparison, shipments of Soviet equipment during calendar
1987 arrived at an average rate of 1,808 metric tons per month _ or
9,040 metric tons for the first five months of 1987. That
translates to 9,944 regular tons.
   The drop in shipments is equally pronounced when expressed in
terms of estimated dollar value. The Pentagon estimated the
materiel delivered during the first five months of this year was
worth $160 million. Shipments in 1987 were worth about $42 million
a month _ or about $210 million for five months.
   During all of 1987, the Nicaraguans received 21,700 metric tons
of arms valued at $505 million, the Defense Department estimates.
   The new figures are contained in a Pentagon briefing paper that
is updated on a monthly basis for top administration officials. The
latest update provides estimates through the end of May.
   Defense officials who spoke only on condition they not be named
said Monday it was too early to predict Soviet intentions for
arming Nicaragua for the year. The military deliveries normally
fluctuate from month to month and there always could be a spurt
later in the year, one source noted.
   On the other hand, ``there is a feeling that perhaps the
Russians are less enthusiastic right now under (Soviet leader
Mikhail) Gorbachev about handing out their resources around the
world.''
   The slowdown in deliveries to Nicaragua's leftist Sandinista
government comes at a time when U.S. aid to the Contra guerrillas
has been cut completely. The Reagan administration, under
congressional pressure, ended its military assistance to the
Contras at the end of February, three weeks before a truce and
cease-fire took effect.
   Soviet arms shipments to the Sandinistas have climbed steadily
over the past eight years, rising from only about 1.6 metric tons
in 1980 to peak at 22,000 metric tons in 1986.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
