<FILEID>AP-NR-06-27-88 2034EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Turkey-Landslides     06-27 0401</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Turkey-Landslides,0413</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Villagers Throw Stones at Rescue Workers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VEDAT ERDAMAR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CATAK, Turkey (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Villagers stoned rescue teams at the site
of a deadly landslide Monday, shouting at emergency crews: ``Why
don't you work faster to find the bodies?''
   Several hundred residents of this mountain village near the
Black Sea scuffled with police and soldiers near heaps of earth and
rock that buried a crowded roadside coffeehouse Thursday and
trapped up to 100 people.
   Witnesses of the protest in Catak, 575 miles southeast of Ankara
said two civil defense workers were injured by stones but no one
was arrested.
   One body was found the day of the landslide but none has been
discovered since. The crew of about 170 rescue workers has combed
about five acres of the mud and rock that crashed down on the
village, and officials have halted work frequently for fear of
causing more slides.
   A stream diverted by landslides also flooded part of Catak.
   Huseyin Gul, whose uncle ran the coffeehouse, shouted at the
rescue workers Monday: ``Five days have passed and my uncle is
still buried. What are you doing there?''
   Enver Hizlan, governor of Trabzon province, said the protest
began after workers temporarily halted the search, leading some
villagers to believe the effort had stopped.
   Officials said rescue teams would work all night under
searchlights.
   West German rescue teams helping with the work said they had
located debris from the coffeehouse but there was no chance of
finding any survivors.
   ``The building was shifted 30 meters by the force of the
landslide. Nobody could possibly have survived,'' said Wolfgang
Kretschmer, leader of a 32-member team from the West German Rescue
Dog Association.
   Deputy leader Hans Ruhl said he found ``a plate from the
coffeehouse but there was too much water around to take the dogs to
search for bodies.''
   Ruhl said the search was poorly organized at first, and ``for
the first three days there was no system to the rescue effort.
Nobody seemed to be in charge.''
   Catak is about 20 miles above Trabzon, a black sea port, among
hazelnut orchards and lush pasture land. The district attracts
growing number of foreign tourists who visit Byzantine ruins.
   Three West Germans and 50 Turks have been listing as missing. An
official of the regional government was killed by falling rocks and
31 people were reported injured in the landslide.
</TEXT>
