<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Israel 1stLd-Writethru a0639 06-27 0829</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0639,0852</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Army Closes Schools, Blocks Street to Stop Stone-Throwing</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 5 grafs to include Arab youth wounded in Nablus.
Picks up 4th pvs bgng, Israeli leaders ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MASHA HAMILTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soldiers chased masked stone-throwers into a
West Bank high school Monday, closed 40 other schools and blocked a
main Jerusalem street to stop young Arabs from hurling rocks.
   Despite the measures, dozens of incidents were reported.
   Reports said soldiers arrested more than 50 Palestinians who
responded to a new underground leaflet urging ``escalation of the
struggle'' in the West Bank and Gaza Strip, where a rebellion
against Israeli occupation began Dec. 8.
   In the West Bank city of Nablus, masked Arab youths stoned
troops in the casbah, or central marketplace.
   Israel radio said soldiers opened fire on the stone-throwers,
wounding one of them in the leg. The army confirmed the clash and
said it was investigating the incident.
   Israeli leaders met privately Monday with U.S. envoy Michael
Armacost about a stalled American plan aimed at reaching a
settlement in the occupied territories and a Middle East peace
agreement.
   Foreign Ministry officials said Richard Murphy, the assistant
secretary of state who specializes in the Middle East, would meet a
Soviet representative next month in Europe to discuss coordinating
U.S. and Soviet approaches to peace.
   Ariel Sharon, a right-wing Cabinet minister, said the government
should be ``eliminating'' Palestinians who throw firebombs and
deporting those who take part in violent protests.
   During a speech in English at the Jewish settlement of Ariel in
the West Bank, he criticized Defense Minister Yitzhak Rabin for not
ending the rebellion and Rabin's Labor Party for recommending a
political solution rather than force.
   At least 211 Palestinians have been killed in nearly seven
months of violence among the 1.5 million who live in the occupied
territories, and four Israelis have been slain.
   About 500 more police were deployed in Jerusalem on Monday,
bringing the total number of security personnel in the city to
1,500, police spokesman Rafi Levy reported, but the reinforcements
could not stop stone-throwing.
   Police said eight stoning incidents were recorded in a single
hour Monday and seven Palestinians were arrested.
   Authorities closed Salah Eddin, the main shopping street of Arab
east Jerusalem, for an hour after stoning attacks in which an
Orthodox Jewish seminary student was slightly injured, police said.
Palestinians in east Jerusalem raised Palestinian flags, which
Israel has declared illegal.
   Palestinian protests Monday responded to an order in underground
Leaflet No. 20 signed by the Palestine Liberation Organization and
underground leaders.
   It called for ``escalation of the struggle'' on Monday and
Tuesday, ``particularily in Jerusalem under the slogan of
`Jerusalem, the capital of Palestine.'''
   The Holy City is among the most contentious issues between
Israel and the Arabs. Israel captured the eastern sector in the
1967 war, along with the West Bank and Gaza, annexed it soon after
and made Jerusalem the Israeli capital.
   Most governments do not recognize Jerusalem, which is a holy to
Jews, Moslems and Christians, as Israel's capital.
   About 200 soldiers surrounded Al Hussein high school Monday in
Hebron, 20 miles south of Jerusalem, after students threw stones at
army vehicles, Arab witnesses told The Associated Press.
   Soldiers chased students into the school, firing rubber bullets
and tear gas, the witnesses said.
   Officials at Hebron's Alia Hospital said 25 students were
treated for injuries caused by tear gas or beatings. Witnesses said
soldiers detained about 50 students.
   Army spokesmen confirmed clashes with stone-throwing youths at
Al Hussein, including some who covered their faces with checkered
Arab scarves, but would not give details or say how many Arabs were
detained.
   Trouble started hours after the army bulldozed the home of Abdel
Majid Sharawne, 22, who is charged with stabbing a Jewish settler
in Hebron three days ago. The settler chased Sharawne after the
stabbing and shot him, and the Palestinian later was taken into
army custody.
   Sharawne's home was the second building wrecked by Israeli
authorities in two days. On Sunday, soldiers blew up the second
story of a building in the Gaza Strip from which they said
assailants threw a firebomb that badly burned two troopers last
week.
   The army closed 40 schools in Nablus, 40 miles north of
Jerusalem and the West Bank's largest city, citing repeated
stone-throwing incidents. Military officials said they would be
closed at least several days.
   High school students in Bethlehem boycotted classes Monday and
soldiers were seen turning several hundred pupils away from two
junior high schools in the nearby Dheishe refugee camp.
   The army denied allegations that soldiers gave Palestinians
injections in the West Bank's Al Amari refugee camp to obtain
information about stone-throwers.
   Nader Mahli, 24, said soldiers seized him Friday, gave him an
injection, then demanded the names of stone-throwers and members of
the Shabiba, a PLO youth movement. Masaad Jaber, a U.N. driver,
said soldiers also gave his son Midhad an injection during
interrogation.
</TEXT>
