<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Soviet-Latvia     06-27 0467</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Latvia,0480</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Latvian Delegates Call for Mandatory Retirement Age</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Soviet-Party, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARK J. PORUBCANSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Latvian Communists have proposed in their program
for a 5,000-member conference that the Soviet Communist Party
leader be elected by direct secret ballot and face a mandatory
retirement age.
   The Latvians followed proposals of another Baltic state,
Estonia, in demanding more economic and political autonomy, but
they were the first to call openly for such firm limits on the
position of general secretary, now held by Mikhail S. Gorbachev.
   Suggestions approved by the policy-making Central Committee in
May call for the tenure of party elected officials to be limited to
two five-year terms. That could be one of the key items of debate
at the party conference, which begins Tuesday.
   Unlimited terms of office and the absence of any retirement age
have allowed party leaders to build over the years a system of
entrenched power and privilege.
   The program of the Latvian delegation was published in the June
18 edition of the official newspaper Sovietskaya Latvia. The
newspaper was received in Moscow on Monday, the eve of the first
party conference since 1941.
   ``For this, in part, it is proposed to carry out direct
elections by secret ballot for the top leaders of party organs
(from the secretary of the party bureau of primary party
organizations to the Central Committee's general secretary),
establish limited terms of office for all without exception, to
establish a single retirement age for all party leaders,'' the
platform said.
   The party leader now is chosen by the ruling Politburo and
confirmed by the Central Committee. It was not clear from the text
of the Latvian proposal who would be allowed to vote for the
general secretary.
   Gorbachev has said he supports limits on the terms of party
officials.
   The Latvian group also proposed that a national monument to the
victims of Stalin's purges be built in Moscow.
   Earlier this month, the official Soviet media said such a
monument had been approved in Latvia to commemmorate those deported
by Stalin after the Soviet Union annexed Latvia, Estonia and the
third Baltic republic, Lithuania, in 1940.
   The Baltic republics are the Soviet Union's most
westward-looking and technologically advanced. Latvia followed the
lead of Estonia in demanding greater economic freedom from Moscow
and the power to exercise it.
   Latvians must have the power to determine ``the basic questions
connected with the determination of structure and activity of the
republic and local organs of government power and administration,''
it said.
   They also demanded control over ``key functions of running the
economy of the republic, decision of questions of establishing
prices, tariffs, pay for labor, financial and credit policies.''
   The program called for legal guarantees against interference in
local affairs by officials in Moscow.
</TEXT>
