<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Lebanon 1stLd-Writethru a0640 06-27 0806</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Lebanon, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0640,0830</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dissidents Overrun Chatilla Camp In Palestinian Power Struggle</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New material and editing throughout, UPDATING with PLO
blaming Syria, fighting reported in Bekaa Valley, PLO appeal to
Assad. No pickup.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RIMA SALAMEH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Syrian-allied Palestinian dissidents
overran Beirut's Chatilla refugee camp in a 13-hour battle Monday,
and PLO Chairman Yasser Arafat's fighters surrendered or laid down
their weapons, police said.
   The fall of the camp dealt a serious setback for Arafat's
mainstream Fatah, which has been fighting Col. Saeed Mousa's
radical Fatah-Uprising faction since May 1 for control of the
Chatilla and nearby Bourj el-Barajneh camps.
   The Palestine Liberation Organization openly blamed Syria for
the fighting.
   The PLO Executive Committee, the guerrilla movement's
policy-making body, said the government of Syrian President Hafez
Assad ``is implementing a black political scheme aimed at
undermining the Palestinian presence in Lebanon.''
   About 140 of Arafat's men in Chatilla surrendered to Syrian and
Libyan officers, police said.
   Sixty other Arafat loyalists, including 45 believed to be
wounded, told Libyan mediators they had put down their weapons and
asked to be taken to Arafat's bases in south Lebanon, police said.
   Police said arrangements were being made to take the 60
fighters, holed up in the camp's only bomb shelter, in a bus convoy
with Syrian and Libyan escorts to the southern port city of Sidon
on Tuesday.
   ``We're not going to hurt them after they've surrendered,'' said
one Mousa fighter who declined to give his name.
   In Sidon, police said a car bomb exploded near a Fatah office in
the Mieh Mieh refugee camp, killing three Palestinian guerrillas
and wounding six.
   There was no claim of responsibility, but radio stations said
the bombing was an attempt to assassinate guerrilla leader Munir
Madbah, who commands Fatah's Force 17 security unit in Sidon. Force
17 has claimed responsibility for several terrorist attacks in
Israel over the last three years.
   Heavy fighting also broke out for a half-hour Monday night
between the Iranian-backed Hezbollah, or Party of God, and Syrian
troops in the Bekaa Valley in east Lebanon, the Christian-run Voice
of Lebanon radio reported.
   There was no independent verification of the clashes reported in
Baalbeck, 42 miles east of Beirut, and the radio said nothing of
casualities.
   Syria, Iran's main Arab ally in Iran's war against Iraq, has
been alarmed by the Tehran government's attempt through Hezbollah
to dominate Lebanon's 1.2 million Shiite Moslems, the nation's
largest sect.
   Virtually every building in the Chatilla camp was wrecked or
heavily damaged in the fighting.
   ``No earthquake could have wreaked such devastation,'' said a
Syrian officer, who spoke on condition of anonymity.
   In all, 127 people have been killed and 527 wounded since May 1,
when the rival factions began fighting for control of the two camps
on Beirut's southern outskirts.
   Mousa's guerrillas stormed into Chatilla during the night and
trapped Arafat's men, police said.
   ``You have a last chance to surrender and turn yourselves in to
the Syrian army or face a final onslaught,'' the dissident command
said in a statement communicated to the encircled loyalists.
   Many of Arafat's men stumbled out of the cement block shanties
with their hands clasped on their heads.
   Police said Syrian Army officers and Libyan observers took
charge of the men who surrendered, while negotiations continued for
the surrender of the other 60.
   Four Libyan mediators headed by Maj. Salim Farjani, shuttled
between the bomb shelter and Mousa's headquarters.
   ``We're here to stop the bloodletting,'' Farjani told reporters.
``Any new attack from either side is going to be considered an
aggression against Libya.'' He did not elaborate.
   The Syrians, whose troops ring the camps, insisted on arresting
Fatah's commander in Chatilla, Youssef Sharkawi, his
second-in-command who also is known as Nader, and his assistant,
Amneh Jibril, the official said.
   Sharkawi and Nader were among the wounded, he said.
   The official predicted that Mousa's guerrillas would soon start
bombarding the sprawling Bourj el-Barajneh camp ``within a few
days, possibly hours.''
   Radio stations reported that Arafat appealed to Soviet leader
Mikhail S. Gorbachev to pressure Syria to stop the bombardment of
the Beirut camps. He reportedly made similar pleas to Libya,
Algeria and Tunisia.
   PLO officials earlier appealed to Assad to intervene to rein in
the dissidents, or at least stop them using Syrian-controlled
territory to shell the camps.
   Syria has thousands of troops enforcing security in west and
south Beirut. But they made no move to stop the fighting, which
flared despite a reconciliation between Arafat and Assad in April
to end a 5-year-old feud over who would control the Palestinian
movement.
   Monday's PLO statement attacking Syria _ issued in Nicosia,
Cyprus, and Tunis, Tunisia, where the PLO has its political
headquarters _ did not say what effect the latest events would have
on the Assad-Arafat reconciliation.
</TEXT>
