<1ST_LINE>u a AM-EmbattledEditor     06-27 0439</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Embattled Editor,0456</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Editor Indicted On Criminal Libel Charge</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TRIP DuBARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KINGSTREE, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A weekly newspaper editor was indicted
Monday on a charge of criminally libeling two state lawmakers.
   If convicted on the rarely used law, the editor, Jim Fitts,
could be the first journalist sent to prison for libel in recent
memory, journalism advocates said.
   Fitts said afterward that he expected the decision by the grand
jury and would ask to have the trial moved out of the county.
   ``The power structure has long roots in Williamsburg County,''
he said.
   But the attorney for the two men who brought the suit said Fitts
is only seeking publicity. ``I think he's got a million dollars
worth of publicity for a slander sheet,'' Wallace Connor said.
   State Rep. B.J. Gordon and state Sen. Frank McGill, both
Democrats, brought the charges in response to a May 17 column in
which Fitts urged voters to reject the county's legislators in the
June primary and accused them of stealing.
   Both McGill and Gordon won re-nomination in that election.
   Fitts, the 62-year-old black editor of The Voice, a
black-oriented newspaper with a circulation of 2,300, riled Gordon,
who is black, and McGill, who is white, with the column.
   It said: ``I will say to you, without fear of contradiction, if
every black in Williamsburg County would start stealing today and
steal every day for the rest of their lives, they could not steal
as much as those two have stolen during their time in power.''
   The column gave no specifics. When asked later what he thought
they had stolen, Fitts said only that they had taken the pride of
people of Williamsburg County.
   Sitting in the first row of the 165-year-old county courthouse,
Fitts showed no emotion as the indictment was read.
   ``I'm not surprised. I'm not disappointed,'' he said afterward.
``And I welcome the opportunity to be heard in court. I got what I
wanted.''
   The case probably will be tried in late August or early
September at the earliest, Solicitor Wade Kolb has said.
   If convicted, Fitts could face $5,000 in fines and a year in
prison on each of the two counts. He is free on personal
recognizance bond.
   Though libel lawsuits are not unusual, criminal libel cases that
can send a journalist to jail are.
   The Williamsburg County case is believed to be only the fourth
involving journalists in 40 years in South Carolina and the first
such case in the nation since 1984.
   The South Carolina chapter of the American Civil Liberties Union
said Monday it will ask dismissal of the charges.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
