<FILEID>AP-NR-06-27-88 1902EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Pope-Cardinals     06-27 0441</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Pope-Cardinals,0453</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>First Mozambique Cardinal Reports Progress in Church-State
Relations</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEPHEN R. WILSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The man chosen as the first cardinal from
Marxist-governed Mozambique said Monday that relations with the
church have improved and predicted the government will establish
diplomatic relations with the Vatican.
   Archbishop Alexandre Jose Maria dos Santos of Maputo also
expressed hope his appointment will help persuade the government to
accept the appeal of the Roman Catholic Church for negotiations
toward ending the African nation's civil war.
   Dos Santos is one of 24 new cardinals Pope John Paul II plans to
elevate at a Vatican ceremony Tuesday. In other appointments with
special political signifance, John Paul named cardinals from
Lithuania and Hong Kong to strenghthen the church in the Soviet
Union and China.
   Two American archbishops also are on the list of new princes of
the church: James A. Hickey of Washington and Edmund C. Szoka of
Detroit.
   John Paul is scheduled to visit Mozambique during his September
tour of southern Africa. Church-state relations in Mozambique were
severely strained after independence from Portugal in 1975, when
religious were either closed or nationalized, and some churches
were shut down in the late 1970s.
   In his comments Monday, dos Santos said Mozambique's government
said last week it would return all church property seize in 1975,
including a large Catholic seminary in Maputo.
   ``It is true that the government is changing its attitude toward
the church and I hope the government is now open to solve all the
problems through dialogue with the church,'' the 64-year-old
prelate said.
   ``The government is not against religion any more. The
government has now come to understand that we have the right to
practice our religion.''
   He said churches are crowded and his appointment as cardinal was
greeted with ``much rejoicing, dancing, singing and shouting. This
gives more hope to the Mozambique people.''
   The Vatican and the government in Maputo, Mozambique's capital,
have indicated interest in diplomatic relatons and the issue was
discussed when President Joaquim Alberto Chissano met John Paul at
the Vatican in May 1987.
   ``I think the government is open, willing and asking for
diplomatic relations with the Holy See,'' dos Santos said. ``The
government has said to us, `We are ready.' Now it depends on the
Holy See. I think that it will not be long before diplomatic
relations are established.''
   He said the church and state continue to differ on the
11-year-old war waged by the Mozambique National Resistance
guerrillas, known as Renamo.
   Bishops have called for negotiations but the government has
refused, contending that the guerrillas are terrorists controlled
by South Africa.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
