<FILEID>AP-NR-06-27-88 2135EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Hungary-Romania     06-27 0425</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hungary-Romania,0441</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Thousands Demonstrate Against Romanian Village Destruction Plan</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROLAND PRINZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 30,000 Hungarians rallied Monday
against a Romanian plan to destroy thousands of villages that would
affect many members of the ethnic Hungarian minority, the official
MTI news agency said.
   The hour-long torchlight gathering at the downtown Heroes Square
was the biggest unofficial demonstration in Hungary since the
anti-Soviet uprising that was crushed in 1956, and the first such
rally permitted by police in this communist nation.
   There had been fear Romanian instigators might use the gathering
to incite illegal actions, but no incidents were reported.
   In March, President Nicolae Ceausescu announced plans for
demolishing 7,000 Romanian villages that would be replaced by big
agricultural-industrial centers.
   The forced resettlement program would affect hundreds of
villages Romania's 1.7 million ethnic Hungarians, who complain of
official discrimination and say they are denied ethnic and cultural
rights.
   A manifesto read to the crowd said: ``After 50 years there is
another criminal committing genocide.''
   Hungarian intellectuals have repeatedly denounced as genocide
both the project for demolishing villages and Romania's alleged
policy of discrimination against ethnic Hungarians.
   The manifesto also referred to the mass murder of Jews and other
civilians committed by the Nazis before and during World War II.
   It was composed by Istvan Csurka, a prominent Hungarian
non-conformist writer, and read by actor Istvan Bubik. It combined
appeals for restraint and for solidarity with ethnic Hungarians in
Romania.
   Thousands were allowed to assemble in historic Heroes Square
without police interference, the manifesto said, and declared: ``It
is a victory that we are here but it is also a tragedy.''
   Relations between the neighboring Warsaw Pact nations have
deteriorated rapidly over the issue of ethnic Hungarians. Romania
accuses Hungary of interfering in its internal affairs.
   Observers as a possible sign the new Hungarian leadership will
take a tough stand regarding Romania.
   Csurka appealed to Hungarians to show solidarity and
determination in trying to prevent what the Magyar Nemzet newspaper
earlier Monday called Romania's ``bulldozer revolution.''
   Numerous banners at the rally denounced the resettlement plan.
   Scores of demonstrators held up signs of place names in
Hungarian, German and Romanian that they fear will vanish from the
map.
   After the rally, most of those assembled marched to the Romanian
Embassy with a memorandum for the Romanians protesting the
demolition project.
   The Romanian state-run media have said the program aims at
gaining more farmland for use by the country's collectivized
agriculture, plagued by lack of incentives for farmers and
livestock fodder shortages.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880627-0178 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-27-88 1924EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p AM-PoliticalRdp 2ndLd-Writethru a0741 06-27 1024</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Political Rdp, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0741,990</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Democrats Choose Ann Richards of Texas as Keynoter</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 2nd graf to CORRECT Rabin title; INSERTS 1 graf after
12th graf pvs, No names, with Nunn comment</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DAVID ESPO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Democratic officials tapped Texas State Treasurer Ann Richards
on Monday to ``draw the distinctions'' between Democrats and
Republicans in the keynote address at their national convention
next month, while Michael Dukakis intensified his search for a vice
presidential running mate.
   The pre-convention Democratic flurry came as Vice President
George Bush, alternating campaign activities with his official
duties, met with Israeli Defense Minister Yitzhak Rabin in
Washington.
   Democrat Jesse Jackson was in Atlantic City, N.J., to watch two
other heavyweights in action, boxers Mike Tyson and Michael Spinks.
   And a fresh poll indicated that Dukakis owns a double-digit lead
over Bush, but may be vulnerable to attack since he is not well
known among the voters despite months of campaigning through the
primaries.
   Democratic Party chairman Paul Kirk held a news conference in
Washington to announce that Ms. Richards, 54, would deliver the
keynote address in prime time on the July 18 opening night of the
convention in Atlanta. He said the decision was cleared in advance
with Dukakis.
   The choice seemed to signal a desire to court not only female
voters, who favor Dukakis in the polls, but also Southerners, who
do not.
   Kirk said she was picked to ``set the tone for Democrats in
Atlanta and to draw the distinctions between the party of the
working American people and the party of of the establishment. Ann
Richards is a mainstream Democrat and a fiery populist from Texas,
one of George Bush's adopted states.''
   In Texas, Ms. Richards, the divorced mother of four grown
children, said, ``I probably will be talking very much about
American families. I think that's what I know the most about, other
than my professional job.''
   She said the speaking ability praised by Kirk and others was
sharpened on the soap boxes of small-town Texas.
   ``For about the past 10 years I've been making speeches at the
Madisonville Cattlemen's Association and the McAllen
Mexican-American Democrats convention and the Nacogdoches Chamber
of Commerce and in any number of places that you think of,'' she
said.
   Dukakis was wrapping up a four-day vacation at the Massachusetts
island resort of Nantucket. Aides said he would travel to
Washington on Wednesday to meet with several dozen senators,
including some who have been mentioned as possible running mates.
   No names were disclosed, but sources said the campaign has asked
for background information from several possible vice presidential
contenders, including Jesse Jackson, Sens. John Glenn of Ohio, Bob
Graham of Florida, Llyod Bentsen of Texas and Sam Nunn of Georgia
and Reps. Thomas Foley of Washington and Lee Hamilton of Indiana.
   Nunn, however, said Monday in a telephone interview that he does
not have plans to provide any such information to the Dukakis
campaign. And he said he has told Dukakis he is not interested in
being on the ticket, though he expressed willingness to confer with
him on the selection of a running mate and other issues.
   Sen. Dale Bumpers of Arkansas and Rep. Richard Gephardt of
Missouri have surfaced as additional contenders in recent days,
even though Gephardt and Dukakis targeted one another with
hard-hitting television commercials last winter during the primary
campaign.
   Dukakis' aides cast doubt on published reports that the governor
might announce his selection as early as this weekend. But Dukakis
himself has said he hopes to make his choice in advance of the
convention, and aides expect him and his running mate to make a
quick campaign trip immediately after the convention in Atlanta.
   Ms. Richards, the first woman to hold statewide office in Texas
in 50 years, is known for her fiery speaking style and her populist
views.
   ``He was very hopeful that we might make a selection of a
woman,'' Kirk said of Dukakis. ``Not only because of the importance
of the family concerns, the issues of stress and struggle that
women are going through in the daily work lives and family lives,
but I think it is symbolic of the importance of women to the
American family and the realities of all of that.
   ``And the fact that, let's face it, that is a strength of the
Democratic Party and a weakness of George Bush and the
Republicans.''
   Kirk defended House Speaker Jim Wright's role as chairman of the
convention, despite the investigations focusing on charges of
unethical behavior. He also announced the appointment of four
co-chairmen for the convention: Vermont Gov. Madeleine Kunin, Rep.
Norman Mineta of California, former New Mexico Gov. Toney Anaya and
Little Rock, Ark., Mayor Lottie Shackelford.
   Bush has been buffeted with bad news in the polls in recent
weeks, and a large new survey conducted for the Times Mirror Corp,
was no exception. Bush trails Dukakis by 53 percent to 40 percent,
the survey found, and analyst Norman Ornstein said voters'
satisfaction with the current state of the economy is overwhelmed
by their fears about the long-term fate of the nation.
   Still, Ornstein said Bush should be able to exploit Dukakis'
relatively fuzzy image among the voters.
   ``This poll doesn't tell who will win the election,'' Ornstein
told reporters. ``For most Americans, Michael Dukakis is a blank
slate. In the next couple of months, there will be a lot written on
the slate, and not just by Dukakis _ but also by the media and by
George Bush and the Republicans.''
   The survey, the latest in a series for the media company
conducted by the Gallup Organization, was based on interviews with
3,021 adults in person from May 13-22. The margin of potential
sampling error was two percentage points.
   In another development, a Democratic-controlled legislative
committee in Massachusetts refused to begin an investigation into a
Dukakis administration plan to build a state prison in the town of
New Braintree. The FBI announced last week that is is conducting a
preliminary investigation into the affair, although it said in an
unusual statement that Dukakis was not a subject of the probe.
