<1ST_LINE>r w AM-RailBill-Burnley     06-27 0336</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Rail Bill-Burnley,340</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Burnley Warns Of Veto If Congress Tampers With Rail Deregulation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFF BARKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Transportation Secretary Jim Burnley told the
Senate Commerce Committee Monday that Congress should expect a veto
if it passes legislation rewriting the 8-year-old law deregulating
the railroad industry.
   Burnley's message came in the form of a letter to key members of
the Senate panel on the day before it was to consider a bill
sponsored by Sen. Jay Rockefeller, D-W.Va.
   The legislation would amend the Staggers Rail Act of 1980 to aid
shippers of coal, grain and other commodities who contend they are
being harmed by railroad monopolies.
   But Burnley said in his letter that Rockefeller's measure
``would erode the substantial gains achieved under the Staggers
Act. The president's senior advisers would recommend a veto of (the
legislation) or a bill resembling this bill if it were presented to
the president for his signature.''
   Many railroads have opposed altering the Staggers Act, which
they say gave them needed pricing and service flexibility and
enabled them to better compete with trucks. Congress enacted the
1980 law to give Conrail and other railroads incentives to rebuild
failing and antiquated systems.
   But a coalition of shippers has said the Interstate Commerce
Commission, in its interpretation of Staggers, has failed to
protect shippers, especially those dependent on a single railroad
to transport their wares.
   A key provision of the bill would force the ICC to periodically
adjust its cost index to reflect productivity gains by railroads.
The ICC uses the index to determine how much freight railroads can
increase their rates each quarter to keep up with inflation.
Shippers contend the formula does not account for gains railroads
have made to make them more efficient.
   Congressional and administration aides said that Rockefeller was
negotiating with several railroads Monday to try to win support for
the bill.
   Burnley sent his letter to committee chairman Sen. Ernest
Hollings, D-S.C.; and to Sen. John Danforth, R-Mo., the panel's
ranking Republican.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
