<FILEID>AP-NR-06-27-88 1958EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-BishopsConference 2ndLd-Writethru a0758 06-27 0852</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bishops Conference, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0758,0872</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S. Bishops Decide To Formulate New Paper On AIDS</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 19 grafs to recast, add further quotes, detail
from bishop's press conference, Bernardin's statement. Picks up
10th graf pvs, `A Vatican...'.</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto MP3</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM KRATTENMAKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLLEGEVILLE, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Acknowledging problems with a
controversial paper on AIDS, a national conference of Roman
Catholic bishops decided unanimously Monday to write a new
statement in consultation with the Vatican.
   Cardinal Joseph Bernardin of Chicago, who made the motion for a
new paper on AIDS teachings, said the paper ``The Many Faces of
AIDS _ A Gospel Response'' could still be used however bishops wish.
   The last of the major items on the agenda at the National
Conference of Catholic Bishops at St. John's University, the AIDS
paper proposed to have the church teach about condoms as a way to
stem transmission of AIDS.
   The paper, written by the bishops conference's administrative
board, had been criticized by some church officials as an apparent
endorsement of condoms. The church opposes all forms of artificial
birth control.
   ``We're not replacing it. The first document stands,''
Archbishop John May of St. Louis told a news conference following
Monday's closed session.
   ``This new document will be a document of the whole conference,
all the bishops together,'' May said. ``It will carry the
discussion further.''
   The church leaders said the existing paper on AIDS should have
been clearer on the church teachings about condoms and should have
been drafted in closer consultation with the Vatican.
   May said he would appoint a panel of bishops to draft a new AIDS
statement in time for consideration by the next conference, to be
held in November in Washington, D.C.
   In retrospect, May said, it was a mistake for the administrative
board to release the AIDS document before review by the Vatican and
the full conference of roughly 300 bishops.
   On the other hand, he said, ``Many bishops were clamoring for
something to use in their general communities. It was a judgment
call that it was more important to get it done and get it out.''
   The paper framed sharp differences between conservative and
liberal factions and questions over the role of the bishops
conference in teaching parishioners.
   It had stressed abstinence from sex outside marriage and
fidelity within marriage. But, noting that many in society reject
church teachings on sexuality, it says education programs could
include ``accurate information about prophylactic devices'' as a
means of preventing transmission of AIDS.
   The incurable, fatal disease is spread mainly by the exchange of
blood or semen during sexual contact or by intravenous drug use.
   Bernardin said the new paper would try to clarify the church's
position on the acceptability of condoms as an AIDS-prevention
measure. But it was ``grossly premature'' to speculate on what
position the new paper would take, he said.
   The new document, he said, ``can make any clarifications which
are needed to put to rest any doubts which might exist regarding
the church's teaching on sexuality and how that teaching applies to
the current (AIDS) crisis.''
   Bernardin said the still-to-be-appointed authors would consult
with the Vatican while writing the new statement.
   In a statement, Bernardin noted that some critics had called for
the original document to be scrapped outright, but said that in his
opinion that would be ``disastrous.''
   ``Withdrawal could give the impression that the entire document
is flawed and that the entire administrative board was in serious
error,'' he said. ``Such action could reopen the debate with
greater intensity.''
   The bishops, he said, cannot allow criticism of the document
``to continue festering. Our unity must be restored so that we can
get on with our business.''
   A Vatican official, in a private letter to the bishops,
criticized the AIDS paper and faulted them for sowing confusion
among Catholics by considering it, a newspaper reported.
   The Milwaukee Sentinel said it obtained a copy of the letter by
Cardinal Joseph Ratzinger, who says bishops should approve use of
condoms under no circumstances and should have consulted the
Vatican. Ratzinger, chief of the Vatican's Congregation for the
Doctrine of Faith, had the comments included in a confidential
booklet prepared for the bishops' study before Monday's session.
   In conclusion, Ratzinger expressed confidence the bishops would
follow ``these considerations, which are known to his Holiness and
have his fullest support.''
   Milwaukee Archbishop Rembert G. Weakland said he was surprised
because the letter marked the first time the conference had
received a private communication from Rome before discussing an
issue.
   In previous business at the four-day conference, the roughly 280
bishops approved a report condemning the morality of deploying a
so-called Star Wars defense initiative but recommending continued
research in the context of disarmament negotiations.
   The bishops also approved a campaign to raise $20 million to
help orders support their retired members.
   Underlying the conference was a larger debate over the role and
authority of the meetings. A recent Vatican working paper said the
U.S. conference and 99 similar conventions around the world have no
authority as a teacher of Catholic doctrine.
</TEXT>
