<1ST_LINE>r a AM-ValedictorianCharged     06-27 0333</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Valedictorian Charged,0344</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Valedictorian Arraigned On Charges of Murdering Mother</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NIAGARA FALLS, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than a dozen high-school friends
showed up in court Monday to show support for the 17-year-old
accused of murdering his mother on the day he was supposed to
graduate as class valedictorian.
   William Shrubsall pleaded innocent to second-degree murder
during a brief arraignment. Judge John Mariano ordered him held
without bail and granted an adjournment until Friday.
   His friends, who over the weekend expressed shock and disbelief
that the handsome and popular honors student could have committed
the crime, sat silently in the courtroom and filed out of the
building without talking to reporters.
   Shrubsall had no comment as his attorney, Paul Cleary, entered
the plea.
   Cleary later said the boy was ``heartbroken'' at losing his
mother.
   ``No one, not anyone who knew William, had any inkling that he
could have done this,'' Cleary said.
   Shrubsall is accused of using a baseball bat to crush the skull
of his 56-year-old mother, Marianne, following an argument early
Saturday morning.
   Shrubsall originally told police that someone had broken into
his house and attacked his mother, and that he scared off the
assailant with a kitchen knife. But under questioning he later
confessed to the killing, saying his mother had threatened to call
his girlfriend's parents after he'd returned late from her home.
   Shrubsall also claimed that his mother struck him with the
telephone receiver during the argument. He told police that she
wouldn't allow him any freedom.
   Cleary said Saturday that there was a history of problems
between the mother and son that would come out in court. The two
had lived alone since the death of Shrubsall's father in 1985.
   One report said that Mrs. Shrubsall beat the teen-ager on
previous occasions. But police said Monday those reports were ``too
strong.''
   Shrubsall, first out of 250 students at LaSalle High School in
Niagara Falls, was to attend the University of Chicago in the fall
and study pre-law.
</TEXT>
