<2ND_LINE>AM-Jackson,320</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jackson Hints At Convention Dispute Over Palestinian Issue</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRENDA C. COLEMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ROSEMONT, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jesse Jackson said Monday he is pleased
with many of the domestic provisions in the Democratic Party
platform, but hinted that some foreign policy issues _ the
Palestinian question in particular _ may be contested.
   He said he is weighing a dozen possible issues that were left
out of the platform to bring up at the Democratic National
Convention in Atlanta next month.
   ``By and large, we got many of our campaign priorities in the
platform,'' Jackson said at a news conference at the annual
convention of Operation PUSH, the civil rights group he founded.
``And we protected our right to ... protest or raise other issues
in Atlanta.''
   His comments came after Democrats, meeting in Denver and
Washington over the weekend, agreed to a platform draft and an
overhaul of party rules in a rare atmosphere of unity.
   Jackson indicated that a call for the creation of a Palestinian
homeland _ rejected by the Dukakis forces for inclusion in the
platform _ might well be an issue at the convention.
   ``Reasonable discussion on this matter should not alienate
anyone,'' he said when asked whether such a plank might anger Jews.
``We must put forth a formula that represents security for Israel
and justice for Palestine, and peace for both.''
   He declined to name the other issues his camp might bring to the
floor.
   Jackson also continued to put himself forth as the one who most
deserves to be offered the No. 2 spot on the Democratic ticket with
Michael Dukakis.
   Jackson said no senator or governor has achieved his broad base
of support, and ``no Democrat alive has registered as many voters
as I have.''
   On the platform, Jackson took credit for getting a number of
issues into the document, including a call for a comprehensive
anti-drug effort, a plank calling for designation of South Africa
as a ``terrorist state,'' and a program of Third World development.
</TEXT>
