<1ST_LINE>u i AM-UN-Disarmament     06-27 0487</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-UN-Disarmament,0501</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Says Nuclear Worries Caused Discord At Disarmament Session</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Worries about whether Israel and South
Africa have nuclear weapons contributed to the lack of agreement on
disarmament policy at a monthlong special General Assembly session,
a U.N. official said Monday.
   Yasushi Akashi, U.N. undersecretary-general for disarmament
affairs, told reporters ``the United Nations did not fail. ... The
membership failed the United Nations.''
   ``I think it is a temporary setback, but ... it should be looked
at in the overall context of the continuous process of the United
Nations to identify and broaden the areas of common interest in
multilateral disarmament,'' Akashi said.
   Delegates to the special session debated throughout last week
and into Sunday morning on disarmament issues.
   The main difference at the session, which ended Sunday, was
between sweeping disarmament proposals advanced by the Soviet Union
and developing nations, and more cautious suggestions of the United
States and some of its Western allies.
   By Sunday morning, delegates had given up trying to write a
mutually acceptable document and the session adjourned.
   Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar said Monday: ``Member
states came close to a final agreement on most of the provisions. .
.. In the end, however, basic national positions were not amenable
to a compromise text.''
   The 159-member General Assembly has no power to enforce its
decisions, but delegates said they believed a final resolution
adopted by consensus would have carried moral authority.
   Akashi said fears among African nations that South Africa was
developing nuclear weapons were partly responsible for the lack of
consensus, as were similar concerns of Arab nations about Israel.
   Non-aligned nations were said to have favored identifying Israel
and South Africa as regionl offenders in a final document.
   The Iran-Iraq war, allegations that Iraq has been using chemical
weapons, and ``the scope of the secretary-general's role in the
investigation of the alleged use of chemical weapons'' created
another obstacle, he said. Iran and Iraq have been at war since
September 1980.
   Another of the ``thorny areas'' involved India and Pakistan,
which regularly accuse each other of developing nuclear weapons, he
said. Neither has signed the Nuclear Non-Proliferation Treaty.
   One question about the treaty is whether developing nations have
a duty to sign it before the United States and Soviet Union reduce
their huge nuclear arsenals, he said.
   As another sticking point, Akashi mentioned ``concerns of the
major powers for their military and strategic positions.''
   Reports at the conference indicated U.S. delegates argued in
committee against naval disarmament, a nuclear test ban and
proposals that would affect the U.S. space-based defense system
commonly called ``Star Wars.''
   Other issues dividing delegates were nuclear-free zones and
militarization of outer space, Akashi said.
   He declared the session successful, despite the lack of
consensus, on grounds that prepared the way for progress on arms
control at the regular General Assembly session this fall.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880627-0185 </DOCNO>
