<HEAD>Foreign Minister Calls in Soviet Ambassador To Discuss Spy
Squabble</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New grafs 1-9 UPDATE with Clark and Soviet ambassador
meeting, Clark threatening new sanction. Picks up 8th graf pvs The
government ...</NOTE>
<DATELINE>OTTAWA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A diplomatic row which began with Canada's
expulsion of purported Soviet spies cooled down Monday when Foreign
Minister Joe Clark called Soviet Ambassador Alexei Rodionov into
his office for a 25-minute chat.
   Rodionov emerged from the meeting and told reporters he was
satisfied the misunderstanding was over.
   But Clark, who postponed an Asian trip Monday to meet with
Rodionov, said when asked if there was a truce: ``I wouldn't apply
that term at this stage.''
   And, after 32 Soviet and Canadian diplomats and officials were
either expelled or prohibited from re-entry, Clark announced one
final sanction.
   He said Soviet workers coming to Montreal to rebuild the
fire-damaged Soviet consulate may not get visas unless the Kremlin
rescinds its decision to withdraw 25 Soviet citizens from their
jobs at the Canadian Embassy in Moscow.
   Visas will be reviewed on a case-by-case basis as long as Moscow
insists on limiting Soviet staff at the embassy, the foreign
minister said.
   The mild threat appeared a face-saving gesture, however, as the
Soviets had pledged to retaliate again and again until Canada
backed off.
   Since Tuesday, Canada has expelled or barred 19 Soviet diplomats
and officials for purported military and commercial espionage. The
Kremlin retaliated with action against 13 Canadian diplomats, three
of whom are accused of military espionage.
   The Soviets shot their last volley on Saturday, damaging
Canadian diplomatic operations in Moscow even further by
withdrawing 25 of the 39 Soviet citizens who cook, clean and do
clerical tasks at the Canadian Embassy.
   The government has given no details of the alleged Soviet
espionage, except to say Moscow tried to infiltrate Canadian
security agencies.
   Intelligence sources told The Associated Press the Soviets were
after highly classified U.S. naval secrets and technology from a
Montreal electronics plant making communications and guidance
systems for a new generation of Canadian frigates and from the U.S.
submarine-monitoring base at Argentia, Newfoundland.
   Clark said he remained confident Canadian security was not
breached by the Soviet activities.
   He had been due to leave Monday for bilateral talks in Tokyo,
followed by a meeting of the Association of Southeast Asian Nations
in Thailand. He is now likely to leave Wednesday, officials said.
</TEXT>
