<1ST_LINE>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     06-27 0429</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0440</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Heavy Rains Fall on Texas; Record Highs and Record Lows Set</HEAD>
<HEAD>By The Associated Press</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Both record highs and lows were set for the date across the
nation, while thunderstorms continued to produce heavy rain in
portions of Texas on Monday.
   Cars stalled as streets flooded in Odessa, Texas, and a flash
flood watch was posted for parts of northwest Texas. Two inches of
rain fell in that region.
   A flash flood watch also was posdted in Apache County in the
northeast corner of Arizona, where heavy thunderstorms were
forecast on top of previous heavy rain during recent days.
   Scattered thunderstorms developed from South Carolina across
Florida and the Gulf Coast states to southeastern Texas.
Thunderstorms also developed in the Rockies.
   Unseasonably cool air began to move into western Washington on
Monday afternoon, and freezing levels are expected to lower to
between 4,000 and 5,000 feet by midweek. Snow accumulations may
occur in portions of the Cascade and Olympic mountain ranges.
   Pleasantly cool temperatures prevailed Monday afternoon from the
Carolinas to New England and from the Appalachians to the upper and
middle Mississippi Valley. Readings in these areas were mostly in
the 70s to lower 80s.
   In contrast, temperatures reached 100 degrees and set record
highs in portions of the central Gulf Coast region and the northern
Plains. The desert southwest also saw triple-digit readings.
   Record low temperatures for the date were set at Jackson, Mich.,
(44 degrees); Parkersburg, W.Va., (49); and Toledo, Ohio, (45).
   Record highs for the date were marked at Bismarck, N.D. (102
degrees); Meridian, Miss. (102); and Pensacola, Fla. (101).
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 56
degrees at Everett, Wash., to 105 at Phoenix, Ariz. The nation's
low Monday morning was 37 degrees at Truckee, Calif.
   The National Weather Service forecast Tuesday called for
scattered showers and thunderstorms extending from the Rockies
across western portions of the central Plains, Oklahoma, Texas and
along the Gulf Coast region to Florida.
   Showers and thunderstorms were expected to be most numerous in
central Florida and from the Texas Panhandle to eastern Colorado.
Widely scattered showers were forecast in Washington, in Oregon and
along the Canadian border from Minnesota to Maine.
   Most of the nation should have high temperatures in the 80s or
90s. Highs were forecast in the upper 60s and 70s in the northern
Great Lakes and from the upper Ohio Valley to the northern Middle
Atlantic States, as well as along the Pacific Coast. Temperatures
were expected to reach 100 to 110 degrees across the desert
southwest.
</TEXT>
