<1ST_LINE>r a AM-BrawleyCase     06-27 0296</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Brawley Case,0303</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Brawley Case Figure Gets At Least Another Night In Jail</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN M. DOYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The man charged with lying to a grand jury about
bugging the conversations of Tawana Brawley's advisers was jailed
overnight without bail pending another detention hearing Tuesday.
   Federal prosecutors claimed Samuel McClease's checkered military
and employment records made him a poor candidate for release on
bail.
   U.S. Magistrate James C. Francis IV had disagreed, ordering
McClease released on $100,000 unsecured bond. But prosecutors
appealed the ruling to a higher court and U.S. District Judge
Shirley Wohl Kram delayed releasing McClease pending a bail hearing
Tuesday morning.
   McClease, 26, claimed last week that he had taped conversations
of the Rev. Al Sharpton and two legal advisers to the Brawley
family _ casting doubt on the Dutchess County teen-ager's tale of
being sexual assaulted by six white men.
   But McClease, a self-proclaimed surveillance expert, was charged
Saturday with one count each of obstruction of justice and perjury
after it was revealed the tapes he turned over to authorities were
blank.
   McClease, of Jersey City, N.J., claimed that Sharpton had hired
him to bug conversations involving the two Brawley lawyers, C.
Vernon Mason and Alton Maddox.
   McClease said during an interview broadcast June 20 on WCBS-TV
that Sharpton hired him in February to plant voice-activated
listening devices in Mason's home and office and in Sharpton's own
home.
   In the interview, McClease said the tapes revealed that there
was no evidence to support the black teen-ager's contentions that
she was abducted by a gang of white men and raped repeatedly last
November _ and that the advisers knew this.
   But prosecutors announced Saturday that FBI analysis indicated
the tapes McClease turned over were ``completely blank.''
</TEXT>
