<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Pope 4thLd-Writethru a0794 06-27 0947</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Pope, 4th Ld-Writethru, a0794,0971</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Pope Ends Austrian Visit; Reported Assassination Plot Against Pope
Foiled</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: LEADS with 14 grafs to UPDATE with reax from officials in
Vienna, Turkey, Vatican. PICKS up 8th graf pvs, On his last day
.... EDITS from 20th graf pvs to bottom `In an address ...
behavior,'' he said.' to TRIM.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By VICTOR L. SIMPSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>INNSBRUCK, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pope John Paul II ended his
controversial Austrian tour Monday with warm thanks to President
Kurt Waldheim. A news report said a new plot by Turkish extremists
to assassinate the pontiff was foiled in Vienna.
   On May 13, 1981, a Turkish terrorist shot and badly wounded the
pope in St. Peter's Square in Rome.
   ABC News in New York quoted unidentified sources as saying two
Turkish extremists were the prime suspects in the latest
assassination plot. In its 6:30 p.m. EDT Monday newscast, ABC said
the attempt was to take place last Thursday, and that police
believed the gunfire was to come from a construction site across
from a cathedral where the pope said Mass.
   The Austrian government confirmed that Austrian anti-terrorist
police found photographs ``that show several sniper positions in
the building plus firing angles to the square'' in front of St.
Stephen's Cathedral, according to ABC.
   The network said that a police raid at an Islamic prayer
building used mainly by Turkish immigrants apparently foiled the
plot.
   ABC said that Mehmet Ali Agca, the man who shot the pope in
1981, and other members of a right-wing extremist group in Turkey
called the Gray Wolves, from time to time sought sanctuary in the
Turkish quarter in Vienna. Agca is serving a life term in a prison
in Rome.
   The pope's tour ended without incident.
   Leo Lauber, overnight police supervisor in Vienna, told The
Associated Press in a telephone interview shortly after 3 a.m.
Tuesday (9 p.m. EDT Monday): ``I don't know anything about this. I
don't know anything about two Turks being prime suspects in such a
plot.''
   Lauber added that any such information, if in fact it exists,
would only be available once the police day shift comes on duty
Tuesday morning.
   Hans Schengersbauer, overnight supervisor at the Interior
Ministry in Vienna, told the AP: ``I haven`t heard of any such
thing. That sounds like a made-up story to me.'' The Interior
Ministry oversees many police and security functions in Austria.
   Schengersbauer said that he had not been informed of every
detail of the papal visit, but that as far as he knew it went off
without incident.
   ``Surely, if something like that had happened, it would have
come out in the news media before,'' he said.
   In Ankara, the Turkish capital, overnight duty officers at the
Interior Ministry and the state security department told the AP
they had no information on any such plot.
   In Rome, repeated telephone calls to the Vatican press office
and the home of Vatican spokesman Joaquin Navarro were unanswered.
   On his last day in Austria, John Paul spoke against ``bitter
confrontations'' that cause divisions in Christianity and the
church.
   Some Jewish leaders objected to his meetings with Waldheim, who
has been accused of involvement in war crimes while serving as a
German army officer in World War II. He denies wrongdoing.
   A looming schism prompted by activities of traditionalist French
Archbishop Marcel Lefebvre, which would be the first split in the
Roman Catholic Church for more than a century, is one of several
items awaiting John Paul at the Vatican.
   He is to elevate 24 new cardinals Tuesday and will announce a
major reform of the curia, the church administration. The
68-year-old pontiff ended his five-day visit at Innsbruck, site of
the 1964 and 1976 Winter Olympics.
   Standing on the airport runway, he thanked Waldheim for ``your
kind words of farewell and for the warm and generous hospitality
which your country and its people have again extended to me,'' then
added:
   ``Cherish and deepen above all the great good of unity and of
the common profession of faith in sincerity and mutual love.''
   During his second trip to this predominantly Catholic nation of
7.5 million people, John Paul repeatedly emphasized that Christians
as well as Jews suffered at Nazi hands.
   Recalling another part of his trip, the pontiff also said Monday
he was ``especially happy'' tens of thousands of East European
Catholics were able to attend his Masses in Austria. Most were from
Hungary and Yugoslavia.
   He has been permitted to visit his native Poland, but not the
other communist-ruled nations of Europe.
   Waldheim also mentioned the Nazi past in his parting remarks.
   ``The somber walls of the concentration camp of Mauthausen
forcefully remind us of the martyrs of our own time,'' Waldheim
said of the concentration camp the pontiff visited Friday. He
called the walls ``relics of a shameful period of our century.''
   A light rain fell as two talked, and when the shower had passed
a rainbow colored the sky. The pontiff's red-and-white Austrian
Airlines DC-9 left for Rome at 6:57 p.m., threading its way through
the craggy, snow-covered Tyrolean peaks.
   John Paul drew repeated lessons from the Nazi horrors during his
tour, beginning with mention of the ``burdensome legacy of the
past'' during a meeting with Waldheim soon after he arrived.
   Waldheim, 69, was U.N. secretary-general from 1972 to 1982 and
allegations about his wartime activities arose during the
presidential campaign two years ago.
   An international panel of historians appointed by the Austrian
government concluded that he knew of Nazi atrocities while serving
as a German officer in the Balkans and did nothing to stop them,
but its report left open the question of personal guilt.
</TEXT>
