<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Bolivia-CocaineAttack     06-27 0540</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bolivia-Cocaine Attack,0559</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Thousands of Coca Leaf Farmers Attack Authorities; Six Killed</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER McFARREN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LA PAZ, Bolivia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 5,000 farmers, enraged over a bill
to ban coca leaf growing, attacked a police and U.S. Drug
Enforcement Agency base Monday and blocked roads in clashes that
killed at least six farmers, officials said.
   Bolivian anti-drug police first fired into the air, but then
fired at the crowd after the farmers continued to march on the base
at Villa Tunari, 180 miles east of the capital city of La Paz,
authorities reported.
   Jorge Alderrete, undersecrtary for the Ministry of Interior,
said some protesters carried dynamite sticks and rifles.
   Five DEA agents were at the base but did not take part in the
fighting and were not hurt, said James Danbridge, spokesman for the
U.S. Embassy in La Paz.
   The takeover attempt failed.
   Police said scores of people were injured in other protests in
the Chapare, a lush tropical region in the heart of Bolivia where
80 percent of Bolivian cocaine is produced.
   Julio Rocha, head of the Chapare Coca Leaf Growers Federation,
said farmers tried to take over the base peacefully and were
repelled by armed police. He said DEA agents helped break up the
roadblocks.
   Two cocaine traffickers who were being detained at the base fled
during the attack, said Interior Minister Juan Carlos Duran.
   Duran said a camp of a development program in the Chapare
financed by the U.S. Agency for International Development was
overrun by coca leaf farmers. There were no U.S. personnel at the
development camp when the attack occurred. The farmers later were
driven away.
   Duran reported that 100 police were being sent in to the Chapare
to reinforce the 300 troops based there.
   A reporter for Radio Panamericana said he saw DEA agents and
Bolivian police fire tear gas at farmers who blocked the bridge and
the main road through the Chapare. Huey helicopters on loan from
the U.S. government also fired tear gas at farmers who were on the
road and bridge, he said.
   Bolivia mobilized the special anti-drug police based in the
Chapare to keep roads open and disperse crowds. At least 350,000
farmers, most of whom live off coca leaf growing and cocaine
processing, live in the Chapare, an area about as big as New Jersey.
   There are an estimated 40 U.S. troops, DEA people and U.S.
Border Patrol agents assisting Bolivian police in the Chapare. The
Americans will remain in the area despite the confrontations, said
Danbridge.
   In recent weeks coca leaf farmers have staged protest marches
and threatened roadblocks and confrontations if the Bolivian
Congress goes ahead with an anti-narcotics measure that would
declare illegal most coca leaf cultivations in the Chapare.
   Congress is expected to pass the bill this week. Part of the
U.S. government's aid program to Bolivia is contingent on the
bill's becoming law.
   There are nearly 100,000 acres of coca plantations in Bolivia
which produce 90 metric tons of cocaine a year, a U.S. Embassy
report says.
   A metric ton is equivalent to 2,205 pounds, or 1.1 short tons.
   Bolivia has intensified its interdiction efforts in the Chapare
this year and captured five tons of cocaine paste, police say.
</TEXT>
