<FILEID>AP-NR-06-27-88 2252EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w AM-Rabin 1stLd-Writethru a0763 06-27 0775</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Rabin, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0763,760</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Israeli Official Wants New Missile With US Help</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: ADDS 2 grafs to bottom with Carlucci comment at dinner with
Rabin</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israeli Defense Minister Yitzhak Rabin said
Monday he expects the Reagan administration to approve joint
development with Israel of a new surface-to-air missile, to counter
a threat posed by the supply of Soviet and Chinese missiles to Arab
countries.
   ``We have to be capable to cope with this new threat,'' Rabin
said after a meeting at the White House with senior Reagan
administration officials.
   He said Israel could not stop the Soviet Union and China from
supplying the missiles to Arab foes, and that U.S. efforts to
persuade them to stop had also failed.
   As a result, Rabin said, he had urged the administration to
approve joint production and development of the ``Arrow'' missile
as a countermeasure.
   ``There wasn't agreement in the past about the Arrow program,''
the Israeli official told reporters after meeting with Defense
Secretary Frank C. Carlucci, Secretary of State George P. Shultz
and Colin Powell, the president's national security adviser.
   But, Rabin said, ``I hope everything will be circled by
tomorrow.''
   The Soviet Union has moved closer to resuming diplomatic ties
with Israel, and has improved its relations with the United States.
Even so, Rabin said, the Soviets supplied missiles to Syria, Iraq
and Libya while China sold a new missile to Saudi Arabia.
   ``For us it's a new strategic threat,'' Rabin said. He cited
also the use of chemical weapons by Iran and Iraq ``and the
legitimization'' given this kind of warfare.
   ``I brought up all these issues, the ways that we, as Israelis,
would like to cope with it, and to find out to what extent certain
projects in which we agreed in the past can get more impetus
towards the future,'' he said.
   In past wars, he said, the Arab nations' air forces could not
penetrate Israeli air defenses and reach population centers.
``Missiles can reach, and no doubt the situation can be aggravated
if chemical war will be added to the missiles,'' Rabin said.
   ``We first would like to be in a position to have the capability
to defend the population of Israel, the armed forces of Israel and
then to destroy the means that might threaten Israel once a war
starts,'' he said.
   The Israeli official is on a semiannual visit to Washington to
develop the strategic ties that bind the United States with its
leading Middle Eastern ally.
   On the human rights situation on the West Bank, which is also on
the agenda for Rabin's visit, Carlucci said, ``We did have some
discussions on disturbances taking place and the Israelis are very
much aware of our position.''
   That is, Carlucci said, ``We do not support beatings or
deportations, but we do recognize that the Israelis have a security
responsibility on the West Bank.''
   Rabin, as defense minister, is trying to control the volatile
situation in the West Bank and Gaza, where Palestinian Arabs have
demonstrated against Israeli control since last December.
   Richard Schifter, the assistant secretary of state for human
rights, has criticized Israel for what Schifter called ``clear
human rights violations,'' and called for a new system of reviewing
appeals by Palestinians who claim they were mistreated by Israeli
soldiers.
   State Department spokesman Charles E. Redman disputed, however,
reports that Schifter is urging joint U.S.-Israeli monitoring of
the situation in the territories.
   Redman said a ``channel of communication'' between the two
countries was what Schifter had proposed.
   In the meantime, the Palestine Liberation Organization, with
strong Arab support, has promoted an ``uprising'' on the West Bank
and in Gaza to try to wrest the area from Israeli control.
   Kuwait and Saudi Arabia, oil-rich countries in the Persian Gulf,
have committed themselves to contribute $50 million to the PLO
treasury to keep the unrest going, Palestinian representatives
reported Saturday in Beirut, Lebanon.
   Rabin and Israeli Foreign Minister Shimon Peres both supported
Shultz's attempt to arrange a peace conference that would be aimed
also at Arab recognition of Israel. But Shamir refused to provide
the assurances sought by Jordan's King Hussein through Shultz that
Israel would surrender the West Bank and Gaza.
   Rabin is seeing Carlucci and President Reagan and congressional
leaders on Tuesday.
   Carlucci, at a dinner for Rabin on Monday night at Fort McNair,
said, ``We think of ourselves as your partners. We have a common
sense of purpose.''
   The U.S. defense secretary, mindful of the November presidential
elections, said, ``This country, no matter what administration is
in power, will always be a friend and supporter of Israel.''
</TEXT>
