<FILEID>AP-NR-06-27-88 2301EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-France-Haiti     06-27 0465</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-France-Haiti,0481</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court Puts Off Date for Duvalier Hearing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By THIERRY BOINET</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   AIX-EN-PROVENCE, France (AP) _ A French court on Monday put off
until a later date Haiti's legal efforts to recover $120 million
allegedly taken by dictator Jean-Claude Duvalier when he fled to
France, a court official said.
   The official, who was not identified in keeping with French
practice, said an investigating magistrate will be named to
determine a new hearing date after consulting lawyers for the
Haitian government and Duvalier.
   Duvalier, who fled here during anti-government demonstrations in
April 1986, is accused of misappropriating at least $120 million in
public funds.
   Attorney Yann Colin, representing the Haitian goverment, told
reporters that Gen. Henri Namphy's seizure of power June 20 in
Haiti would not interrupt the judicial procedure begun in France by
Haiti.
   ``We are not the lawyers of the government but of the state of
Haiti,'' Colin said. ``We maintain our power as its legal
representative.''
   In April, a French court ruled it had juridsiction in the case
against Duvalier.
   According to judicial sources, who by practice cannot be
identified, a household budget sheet seized during the course of
the investigation, shows that Duvalier and his wife, Michele,
continue to enjoy a comfortable life style.
   The sources said the information could undermine the Duvaliers'
lawyer's claim that the couple left all their money in Haiti and do
not have any funds elsewhere to spend.
   According to the budget sheet, Mrs. Duvalier spent $5,000 on
Nov. 27 for sweaters for her husband, referred to as ``Tonton'' in
the accounts, which in familiar French means uncle.
   Another entry shows $5,600 for a dress and $1,300 for shoes for
the couple's two children.
   According to the accounts, in some months the couple's
expenditures are substantial. There are unexplained entries in
December 1987 for $287,000 and $28,000.
   The sources said the accounts are quite detailed and show that
Mrs. Duvalier kept a separate ledger for herself. They show that
from July 1987 to January 1988 she spent $83,000 on jewelry.
   Mrs. Duvalier, according to the accounts, is also apparently
responsible for the day-to-day running of the house, paying gas,
telephone and electricty bills.
   For example, she paid out $3,314 in international telephone
calls and $1,060 in local telephone calls in November 1987.
   Many of these expenditures, the accounts show, were made in cash.
   But there were other notations showing that Mrs. Duvalier
transferred funds to relatives apparently to make purchases for the
couple.
   Since arriving in France on Feb. 7, 1986, Duvalier, his wife and
other family members have lived in a mansion in southern France
rented from Saudi businessman Adnan Kashoggi.
   Duvalier has consistently declined to coment on political
developments in Haiti since his downfall. He has said he is without
resources.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
