<DOCNO> AP880627-0196 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-27-88 2310EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w AM-Paisley 2ndLd-Writethru a0745 06-27 0990</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Paisley, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0745,930</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Key Figure in Defense Probe Known as Hard-Nosed, Bon Vivant</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 1 graf after 14th graf pvs bgng, `Barcella has,' to
UPDATE with report that investigators found `stacks' of classified
documents Paisley shouldn't have had when they searched his home
and office</NOTE>
<HEAD>With AM-Defense Probe Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOAN MOWER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In nearly 5{ years as a top Navy official,
Melvyn R. Paisley gained a reputation both as a hard-nosed
administrator with little tolerance for functionaries and a bon
vivant who loved a good party.
   With his stylish young wife at his side, the 63-year-old Paisley
_ now a key figure in the Defense Department bribery case _ seemed
to make an impression on just about everyone with whom he worked or
socialized, according to former colleagues and acquaintances.
   ``He's an affable person, but he is tough as nails,'' said a
former Navy official who worked with Paisley, but did not want his
name used. ``Colorful is the way people describe Mel,'' another
official said.
   But Paisley had his detractors at the Navy, where he became
assistant secretary for research, engineering and systems in 1981
after a 28-year career with Boeing Co. in Seattle.
   With John F. Lehman Jr. as Navy secretary, Paisley joined a
small coterie of men who oversaw the massive buildup of the Navy to
600 ships. Paisley supervised procurement, specializing in
acquisition of aircraft and combat systems.
   ``There are lots of people in the Navy who don't like him, just
as they don't like Lehman,'' conceded Paisley's lawyer, E. Lawrence
Barcella. But he attributed those feelings to sour grapes over the
Lehman-Paisley effort to streamline costs and ``revitalize Navy
procurement.''
   But James Durst, a former Boeing executive, said Paisley had a
tarnished reputation before he joined the government.
   ``Usually every major company has one guy who does the dirty
business,'' Durst said. ``He was the guy.''
   Durst said he told the government in the early 1980s that
Paisley, while at Boeing, bragged of committing a felony
wiretapping operation and bribing people overseas for military
contracts.
   Barcella dismissed allegations made by Durst and Paisley's
ex-wife, Mildred McGetrick of Spokane, Wash. She told The Los
Angeles Times that she had informed the FBI in mid-1981 that
Paisley took gratuities and was ``dishonest with money.''
   ``Going to disgruntled ex-employees and ex-wives, that's more
than scraping the bottom of the barrel,'' Barcella said. ``That's
tilting it over and looking underneath.'''
   He noted that both the FBI and the Senate investigated Paisley
before his confirmation in November 1981.
   The FBI confirmed it conducted a routine background check on
Paisley and furnished it to the White House. Contents of the
investigation are confidential, FBI spokeswoman Sue Schnitzer said.
   Barcella has answered calls on behalf of Paisley and his fourth
wife, Vicki, since the initial reports that FBI agents had searched
Paisley's office in their investigation into allegations that
defense contractors and consultants bribed Pentagon officials to
obtain classified material vital for winning multibillion-dollar
contracts. No one has been charged in the probe.
   The Washington Post reported in Tuesday's editions that federal
investigators found ``stacks'' of classified federal documents that
Paisley had no security clearance to possess when they searched his
home and office. The Post cited informed officials for the
information.
   An engineer by training, Paisley listed himself in government
biography as a 1953 graduate of the American Institute of
Technology, and a 1954 graduate of the Massachusetts Institute of
Technology. MIT said Paisley attended one semester.
   Paisley and Lehman socialize together and live four houses apart
in an exclusive McLean, Va., neighborhood. The two men had formed a
friendship before President Reagan's election when Boeing hired
Lehman's military consulting firm, Abington Corp., for $350,000 a
year, according to a report published in The New York Times in 1983.
   Law enforcement officials have said Lehman, now a managing
director at Paine Webber Inc., is not a target of the
investigation, but investigators have evidence suggesting Lehman
may have tipped Paisley about the inquiry. Lehman has refused to be
interviewed.
   Paisley left government in March 1987 to form a defense
consulting business with an office in the Watergate complex, near
the office of his friend, William Galvin, another defense
consultant who is under investigation.
   Sources told The Los Angeles Times last week that, as a
consultant, Paisley and his wife copied secret documents, and
Paisley then allegedly passed the information to his major client,
McDonnell Douglas Corp.
   Other sources said James Gaines, a deputy Navy secretary who
worked with Paisley at Boeing in the 1970s, is believed to be one
of the people who passed the information to Paisley. All of the
sources talked on condition their names not be used. Paisley's
other clients included BDM International Inc., a defense
contractor, and United Technologies Corp.
   Barcella said he would not comment on the allegations until he
has seen the evidence.
   This is not the first time Paisley has attracted the Justice
Department's interest. He was one of several former Boeing
officials sued for receiving improper severance payments. Paisley's
``golden handshake'' at Boeing, amounting to $183,000, is still
tied up in the courts.
   While Paisley managed the Navy's weapons-buying, his wife went
to work in 1983 for BDM, which hired Paisley as a consultant when
he resigned from the government.
   In 1986, Mrs. Paisley had several sources of income, according
to her husband's financial disclosure form. She received
unspecified amounts from BDM, Town and Country Real Estate, and
from VAMO Inc., a company in Vienna, Va. The Paisleys' friend,
William Galvin, was on VAMO's original board of directors, public
records show.
   The forms describe Mrs. Paisley as the sole owner of VAMO, with
the ownership worth between $15,000 and $50,000.
   VAMO is a ``computer-type'' business that helps companies solve
management problems, according to Robert Plotkin, another attorney
for Mrs. Paisley. Galvin's lawyer, William Nussbaum, refused to
comment on matters pertaining to his client.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
