<NOTE>For Release Friday, July 8</NOTE>
<HEAD>Today in History</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Today is Friday, July 8, the 190th day of 1988. There are 176
days left in the year.
   Today's highlight in history:
   On July 8, 1896, William Jennings Bryan captivated the
Democratic National Convention in Chicago and enhanced his chances
for nomination with a speech in which he denounced supporters of
the gold standard, saying, ``You shall not crucify mankind upon a
cross of gold.''
   On this date:
   In 1663, King Charles II of England granted a charter to Rhode
Island.
   In 1776, Col. John Nixon gave the first public reading of the
Declaration of Independence to a crowd gathered at Independence
Square in Philadelphia.
   In 1889, The Wall Street Journal was first published.
   In 1891, future President Warren G. Harding married Florence K.
DeWolfe in Marion, Ohio.
   In 1907, Florenz Ziegfeld staged his first ``Follies,'' on the
roof of the New York Theater.
   In 1919, President Woodrow Wilson received a tumultuous welcome
in New York City after his return from the Versailles Peace
Conference in France.
   In 1947, demolition work began in New York City to make way for
the new permanent headquarters of the United Nations.
   In 1950, General Douglas MacArthur was named commander-in-chief
of United Nations forces in Korea.
   In 1959, Major Dale R. Buis of Imperial Beach, Calif., and
Master Sgt. Chester M. Ovnand of Copperas Cove, Texas, were the
first American soldiers to be killed during the Vietnam War.
   In 1975, President Gerald R. Ford announced he would seek the
Republican nomination for the presidency in 1976.
   Ten years ago: Tennis star Bjorn Borg of Sweden won his third
consecutive men's singles title at Wimbledon as he defeated Jimmy
Connors, 6-2, 6-2, 6-3.
   Five years ago: Turkish assailant Mehmet Ali Agca surprised
reporters by charging that Soviet and Bulgarian agents had helped
him try to assassinate Pope John Paul II in 1981, an allegation
strongly denied by the Soviets as ``propaganda.''
   One year ago: Kitty Dukakis, wife of Massachusetts Governor and
Democratic presidential candidate Michael S. Dukakis, revealed she
had been addicted to amphetamines for 26 years, but sought help and
was drug-free.
   Today's birthdays: Former Michigan Gov. George Romney is 81.
Critic Walter Kerr is 75. Singer Billy Eckstein is 74. ABC News
President Roone Arledge is 57. Singer Steve Lawrence is 53.
Ballerina Cynthia Gregory is 42. Actress Kim Darby is 40.
   Thought for today: ``The right to be alone _ the most
comprehensive of rights, and the right most valued by civilized
men.'' _ Louis D. Brandeis, U.S. Supreme Court Justice (1856-1941).
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Friday, July 8</NOTE>
</DOC>
