<1ST_LINE>a i AM-Mexico-Presidential Adv04   06-27 0846</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Mexico-Presidential, Adv 04,0872</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv04</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Mon AMs, July 4, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Opposition Candidates Raise Issue of Fraud in Mexico</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Note election is July 6.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By CHRIS ANGELO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In the final days of a presidential race
they're expected to lose, Mexico's opposition parties are stepping
up their claims that the government and ruling party will steal
victory from them.
   Carlos Salinas de Gortari, the man virtually guaranteed victory
as candidate of the government's Institutional Revolutionary Party,
is hammering just as hard at his claim that he will win Wednesday
in a clean election.
   Opposition parties long have accused the dominant PRI, as it is
commonly called, of stuffing or stealing ballot boxes and other
forms of vote fraud.
   But the charges are being hurled with more force and frequency
than in past campaigns for the nation's top office. This year's
opposition is presenting the PRI with its biggest presidential
challenge since the 1950s at a time when its candidate is seen as
weakened by Mexico's economic crisis and general discontent.
   In a change from the past, Salinas de Gortari has acknowledged
that a fraud problem exists. Juan Enriquez, his spokesman, says the
need for a clean election is one of the top issues in his campaign.
   ``It is not only the PRI presidential candidate who rejects
obsolete practices and electoral trickery, it is the majority of
Mexicans,'' Salinas de Gortari said in a speech April 22.
   ``Let us hold clean, clear elections. ... You can be sure that
we will defend our victories, but we will equally accept our
defeats,'' he said.
   Cuauhtemoc Cardenas, a former state governor who led a dissident
movement in the PRI and broke away to become candidate of nearly
all the leftist parties, said recently he saw much evidence of
preparation of ``a fraud of enormous dimensions.''
   Manuel J. Clouthier, candidate of the conservative National
Action Party, has charged that ``electoral fraud has been prepared
throughout the country.''
   ``The problem is that the tendency of fraud and the real
interests that would be affected by a clean election could be more
powerful than a mere desire for honesty by Salinas de Gortari,''
Jorge G. Castaneda, a well-known author and political scientist,
wrote in the current issue of the magazine Nexos.
   Opposition leaders say the PRI's repertoire of means of fraud is
vast, ranging from inflating the voter registration lists to giving
workers ballots already marked for the PRI.
   ``All the cemeteries in Mexico City are on the registration
lists,'' charged Porfirio Munoz Ledo, a former head of the PRI and
ambassador to the United Nations who with Cardenas organized the
dissident movement known as the Democratic Current.
   In rural areas where opposition representatives usually are not
present at the polls, ``they fill the boxes as they want,'' he
added.
   Said Raul Trejo, of the National University's Institute for
Social Research: ``There are municipalities in the country where
the PRI has gotten 100 percent of the votes or more, ... where the
vote was greater than the registration list.''
   Opposition leaders contend that manipulation of the process is
not limited to election day and they have complained loudly that
voter registration was closed as long before the election as Dec.
31.
   Enriquez, the PRI candidate's spokesman, said the reason was to
give parties six months to check their copies of the electoral
rolls.
   While by law all parties are allotted radio and television time,
National Action, particularly, has complained that some stations
wouldn't sell it time or cancelled interviews.
   Virtually all television stations in Mexico are either
government-owned or closely aligned with the government, including
the major Televisa private network.
   The other two candidates, Rosario Ibarra de Piedra of the
Trotskyite Revolutionary Workers Party, and Gumersindo Magana of
the conservative Mexican Democratic Party, have complained of
similar problems.
   Enriquez says the opposition parties raise accusations of fraud
to excuse their losses.
   ``It is very difficult, in fact impossible, I think, to show
that there's a massive, systematic change of the voting patterns of
the population,'' he said.
   Opposition parties say their main defense will be to try to have
representatives at all the polling places this time, although it
can be difficult in the remote mountain regions of the country.
   Clouthier has urged the Mexican army to prevent fraud and called
repeatedly for civil disobedience if irregularities show up.
Cardenas says his parties will use ``popular mobilization,''
essentially the same thing.
   With its extensive grassroots system of organization among rural
people, labor and other sectors, and government benefits such as
housing and health care, the PRI in most cases can win without
resorting to what is popularly known here as ``alchemy.''
   ``It would be naive to say that there are not electoral frauds
in Mexico,'' Francisco Baez Rodriguez, an economics professor at
the National University, said in an article in Nexos.
   ``But it is equally naive to pretend that the dominance of the
PRI finds its main sustenance in fraud, at least in federal
elections.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Mon AMs, July 4</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880627-0210 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-27-88 1423EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a i AM-Niger-FamilyPlanning Adv05   06-27 0867</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Niger-Family Planning, Adv 05,0898</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv05</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Tue AMs, July 5, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Niger Tries Family Planning to Ease Strains on Resources</HEAD>
<BYLINE>BY ROBERT WELLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NIAMEY, Niger (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Unable to turn back the advancing Sahara
Desert or stop periodic droughts, Niger has turned to family
planning to control population growth and reduce pressure on its
fragile resources.
   The north-central African nation has only 6.8 million people in
an area twice the size of France, but it can't feed itself and at
its current growth rate the population will double in 23 years.
   Three and a half years ago the government strongly endorsed
family planning, an unprecedented move in this largely Moslem area
of Africa just below the Sahara, and in April it legalized
contraception.
   ``The legalization of contraception is concrete proof of the
government's support for family planning,'' said Dr. Halima
Maidouka Diallo, director of family planning in the Ministry of
Health.
   To counter African traditions in favor of large families and
avoid potential clashes with some interpretations of the Koran, the
Moslems' holy book, the government presented family planning as a
necessary move to reduce infant and maternal mortality.
   Niger's infant mortality rate of 135 deaths per 1,000 births and
maternal mortality rate of 7 deaths per 1,000 births are among the
highest in the world.
   ``For a woman to be valued here, she must have many children as
soon as possible. Children help with work and are considered life
insurance,'' Maidouka said.
   ``Women are considered wicked if they do not produce children,''
she added.
   Customarily, if a woman doesn't bear children, a husband will
look for another wife.
   Because many infants die, mothers bear many children. It is not
unusual for a mother to have 15 children with only five surviving.
   The frequent births become both a cause and effect. Women become
pregnant again as soon as possible after delivery, without time to
fully recover, and often give birth prematurely to infants who have
little chance of surviving.
   It also creates problems in schools, where many young girls
become pregnant. The average age for marriage for women is about
15{.
   Some women seek abortions clandestinely, as they are not legal
here, or go to neighboring countries.
   ``At least once a month there is a case of a baby being
strangled and tossed in a trash can,'' Maidouka said.
   She added that suicides are also a problem among women with
unwanted pregnancies.
   The family planning program seeks to offer women an alternative.
   ``A child if I want, when I want,'' says a poster displayed
throughout the country's main family planning center.
   The center, built with funding from the United Nations, has a
large poster explaining various contraception methods. The
explanations are accompanied by explicit diagrams showing, among
other things, how to use a condom.
   The diagrams are necessary in a nation where only 4.4 percent of
the women are literate and only 20 percent of children go to
primary schools.
   Dr. Voahangi Ravao of Malagasy, a staff associate of the
Columbia University Center for Population and Family Health, says
the most common reason given in a Niamey survey of women who did
not use family planning was ``nobody told me.''
   Opposition by husbands was cited by only 5 percent, she said.
   She added that she has seen women who've walked 10 miles to pick
up birth control pills.
   She said a survey taken a year ago showed 6 to 10 percent of the
women were using some form of modern contraception, which is a very
high rate for the Sahel, the region just below the Sahara.
   In the West African nation of Burkina Faso, for example, a
similar survey found 4 to 6 percent of women using modern birth
control methods.
   Maidouka said radio and television broadcasts, in the main
national languages, will be used to reach as many people as
possible.
   The U.S. Agency for International Development has approved an
$11-million, five-year grant, to support the project.
   In a report, the agency said Niger's ``rapid population growth
has accentuated the processes of deforestation and
desertification.''
   It added, ``Wood harvesting, which provides 80 percent of the
nation's energy, far exceeds the sustainable capacity of the
forests. The forested area has decreased by 30 percent over the
last 20 years due to pressure from farmers, herders, firewood
cutters and drought.''
   Only 12 percent of the country is arable, and only 3 percent can
be used for growing crops. The annual per capita income is $240.
   The U.S. agency's report concedes that even if couples were
limited immediately to two children per family the population would
continue to grow for 40 years because almost half the current
population are teen-agers. And the agency says it is likely to take
30 years to reach the goal of only two children per family.
   The family-planning project, however, doesn't even talk of
limiting families to two children.
   It focuses on how planning and spacing of pregnancies will mean
better health for mother and child.
   ``There is much to do,'' Maidouka said. ``Tradition is a
problem. Perhaps our children will have full rights. Now the man is
the boss.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Tue AMs, July 5</NOTE>
</DOC>
