<FILEID>AP-NR-06-27-88 1627EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>s a BC-APN--Chicago'68-Memorabilia Adv10   06-27 0697</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-APN--Chicago '68-Memorabilia, Adv 10,0711</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv 10</NOTE>
<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, July 10</NOTE>
<HEAD>From AP Newsfeatures</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-APN--Chicago '68
^(APN SUNDAY ILLUSTRATIONS: Mailed print subscribers get 1 b&w
photo. ColorFoto subscribers get 1 35mm slide.)</HEAD>
<TEXT>
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mitch Kuhn leafs through one of his bound
collections of political buttons, pauses at a page of peace-symbol
pins and reaches 20 years into his memory for a black-and-white
image from August 1968.
   ``I was a peace activist in Milwaukee,'' Kuhn says. ``I had
worked for (Sen. Eugene) McCarthy. And when I saw on television the
McCarthy folks being rousted out of their rooms at the Hilton and
beaten and bloodied _ that goes right to the bottom of your soul.
   ``In hindsight, looking back, I wish I'd have been here.''
   Here: Chicago, 1968, when in the last week of August, thousands
of angry young anti-war protesters upstaged the Democratic National
Convention and the nomination of Hubert Humphrey with violent,
nationally televised clashes with police in the parks and on the
streets.
   Those who were there may remember the stinging tear gas, the
crackling megaphones or the sight of an enraged Mayor Richard J.
Daley leaping to his feet on the convention floor at Connecticut
Sen. Abraham Ribicoff's denunciation of ``Gestapo tactics in the
streets of Chicago.''
   But for those who were not there, the artifacts remain. And for
reasons both economic and emotional, prices for '68 convention
collectibles have risen dramatically.
   Certain Humphrey campaign buttons are worth $150, more than 10
times their book value just 10 years ago. Copies of the Seed,
Chicago's leading underground newspaper of the day, have doubled in
price in less than five years and now sell for about $10 at
rare-book stores.
   As in any market, scarcity increases value. Clean, documented
20-year-old buttons bearing the once-ubiquitous peace symbol go for
$2. But several buttons designed by cartoonist Jules Feiffer to
help raise money to defend the Chicago Seven protest leaders,
charged with conspiracy to incite violence at the convention, go
from $5 to $12.50, depending on their condition.
   Books of the era also are in demand, says Kenan Heise, who owns
Chicago Historical Bookworks in suburban Evanston.
   Typical buyers are people in their late 30s and 40s who shared
the rebellious spirit of the times and yearn for something more
tangible than their memories, says Heise, who recently added a
shelf of out-of-print books by the Chicago Seven.
   ``Trial'' by Tom Hayden, published in 1970 at $1.95, sells for
$15. Abbie Hoffman's 1968 paperback ``Revolution for the Hell of
It,'' published at $1.95, goes for $12.50. Listed at $12 are Jerry
Rubin's ``We Are Everywhere'' (``written secretly in the Cook
County Jail and smuggled out,'' according to a cover blurb) or ``Do
It'' (``Read this book stoned!'').
   There also are memorabilia collectors who just like the way the
stuff looks.
   ``One of the best things to come out of the '60s was the
buttons,'' says Jim Norton, 51, of suburban Oak Park, who collects
anti-Vietnam War pins.
   At the spring meeting of the local chapter of the American
Political Items Collectors, a 2,000-member national organization,
Norton pointed out his favorites, circa 1968: an anti-Lyndon
Johnson button inscribed ``LSD not LBJ;'' a black-and-white pin
bearing a sketch of Uncle Sam with a pistol, and a
red-white-and-blue button showing a dove shedding a bloody tear.
   ``My daughter almost cried when she saw that,'' he said.
   The market for Chicago '68 artifacts is broad enough to include
everything from a comic-book-style copy of poet Allen Ginsberg's
testimony at the Chicago Seven trial _ $25 at Heise's store _ to a
Humphrey-Muskie poster, also $25.
   But some items are valued by their owners beyond any price.
Charles ``Sky'' King, 48, worked as a newspaper film courier during
the convention and remembers steering his motorcycle through the
tear gas in Licoln Park with a photographer standing up behind him
on the passenger foot-pegs, shooting riot scenes.
   His souvenirs include a bright-orange Secret Service pass and
his courier identification card, marking him, he said, as ``a
veteran of the Democratic War.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, July 10</NOTE>
</DOC>
