<1ST_LINE>s a BC-APN--EuthanasiaII Adv10-2Takes   06-27 0950</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-APN--Euthanasia II, Adv 10-2 Takes,0969</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv10</NOTE>
<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, July 10</NOTE>
<HEAD>From AP Newsfeatures</HEAD>
<NOTE>(APN SUNDAY ILLUSTRATIONS: Mailed print subscribers get 2 b&w
photos. ColorFoto subscribers get 1 35mm slide.)</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   
   EDITOR'S NOTE _ Most people want to live as long as possible and
most want the benefits of the healing arts. But what of those who,
stricken by terminal illness, think otherwise? And those who,
incapable of decisions themselves, linger hopelessly to the
distress of their families? Few questions raise greater
difficulties or more emotional debate. This is the second of three
articles on euthanasia.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE ESPER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Special Correspondent</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   That December night 3{ years ago in the Bahamas,
where Darlena and Bob Risley had traveled in a last, desperate
journey in search of a miracle cure for her cancer, she became so
nauseous and dehydrated that the doctor had to be called.
   At their apartment, the doctor gave her one shot for the nausea
and a second shot to kill the pain in her back and in her stomach
that had swollen larger than during her pregnancy years ago.
   A few hours later, just before midnight on Dec. 5, 1984, Darlena
reached up and put her arms out to her husband. He held her. At
that moment, Darlena Risley stopped breathing at age 41.
   Darlena's suffering haunted Risley so much that he was prepared
to help her die sooner had she asked him for a peaceful end to her
life, even though it would have been a crime. He thought about that
when he returned to California and about the many others who endure
the pain of terminal illness.
   Six months after Darlena's death, the 54-year-old Los Angeles
attorney started a campaign to revise the California Natural Death
Act to legalize active euthanasia and allow physicians to give
terminally ill patients lethal doses of drugs, upon their request
and under certain safeguards.
   Darlena's death inspired Risley to found Americans Against Human
Suffering. The group fell more than 100,000 signatures short of the
number required by the May 8 deadline to get the issue on the
California ballot for November's election. But it still managed to
gather 250,000 names.
   The organization, with another pro-euthanasia group, the Los
Angeles-based National Hemlock Society, is planning to try again in
1990, not only in California, but in Oregon, Washington state and
Florida as well.
   While support for active euthanasia is growing in some segments
of the American population, the opposition remains strong from
leading experts on medical ethics, lawmakers, religious leaders,
doctors and lawyers.
   ``As individuals and as a society, we have the positive
obligation to protect life,'' said Cardinal Joseph Bernardin,
leader of the Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Chicago, in a recent
speech. ``We have the negative obligation not to destroy or injure
human life directly, especially the life of the innocent and the
vulnerable.''
   Four prominent physicians and experts on medical ethics spoke of
``perilous times for our profession'' in a commentary printed in
the April 8 issue of the Journal of the American Medical
Association. They cited efforts in court and legislatures to
legalize killing by doctors if patients request it.
   ``Now is the time for the medical profession to rally in defense
of its fundamental moral principles, to repudiate any ... acts of
... intentional killing by physicians and their agents,'' the
commentary said. ``We call on fellow physicians to say that we will
not deliberately kill. And we must say to the broader community
that if it insists on tolerating or legalizing active euthanasia,
it will have to find non-physicians to do its killing.''
   The commentary was in response to an article published in the
journal in which a doctor, whose name was withheld, described how
he killed a 20-year-old woman named Debbie with an injection of
morphine. The woman, like Darlena, was dying of ovarian cancer.
   The commentary was signed by Willard Gaylin, president of the
Hastings Center in Briarcliff Manor, N.Y.; Leon R. Kass, professor
in the Committee on Social Thought at the University of Chicago;
Mark Siegler, director of the Center for Clinical Medical Ethics at
the University of Chicago; and Edmund D. Pellegrino, director of
the Kennedy Institute of Ethics at Georgetown University.
   In a telephone interview, Gaylin said he is not opposed to
withdrawing medication or treatment from a dying patient if that's
what he wants, or to giving him pain relievers even if it would
hasten death.
   ``But I don't think doctors should assume the responsibility for
actually killing a patient,'' he said. ``If our society wishes to
condone that, I think it would be best if that were not the
doctor's role. We do allow the patient to do it to himself. Suicide
is no longer a crime in any of the 50 states. Abetting a suicide is
in almost every state.''
   Gaylin suggested that if the public decides that some people
should have the option of euthanasia, then it should be done by a
family member as surrogate for the physician.
   This is precisely what ran through Bob Risley's mind in the
final days of his wife's life. She wanted to live so much that she
withstood surgery four times and chemotherapy as the cancer spread
through her body. She suffered the indignity of having a catheter
inserted into her stomach for eight months through which
chemotherapeutic fluids flooded her abdomen. The doctor had given
her only a year to live. She survived for two.
   A few days before she died, she and Risley had discussed what
they would do if her pain became too great. But no decision was
made except in his own mind.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>MORE</NOTE>
<TEXT>
</TEXT>
