<DOCNO> AP880627-0224 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-27-88 1918EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>s e BC-APN--TheaterWeek Adv10   06-27 1165</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-APN--Theater Week, Adv 10,1192</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv10</NOTE>
<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, July 10</NOTE>
<HEAD>From AP Newsfeatures</HEAD>
<NOTE>(APN SUNDAY ILLUSTRATIONS: Mailed print subscribers get 1 b&w
photo. ColorFoto subscribers get 1 35mm slide.)</NOTE>
<TEXT>
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL KUCHWARA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Drama Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   At dinner two years ago, a friend told David
Henry Hwang a bizarre tale that had made headlines in Europe but
received little attention in the United States.
   A French diplomat falls in love with a Chinese actress in
Beijing. They carry on an affair for 20 years. He later is arrested
in France on espionage charges. At the trial, it is revealed that
the actress is a man who was coerced into the liaison by the
Chinese government. The diplomat claims he didn't know she was a he.
   ``The story had a kind of resonance that appealed to me,'' Hwang
says of what turned into ``M. Butterfly,'' winner of the 1988 Tony
Award as best play of the season. ``So I initially thought of doing
it as a musical.''
   Hwang approached producer Stuart Ostrow who once had brought
Hwang, composer Philip Glass and designer Eiko Ishioka together for
a musical project that didn't pan out.
   Hwang thought about the story for two months and decided to
dovetail the spy drama with the plot of Puccini's ``Madama
Butterfly.'' He sent a two-page outline to Ostrow. It contained the
axis of the plot, particularly the idea of the French man thinking
of himself as Pinkerton and the actress as Butterfly.
   The outline became a play _ written in about six weeks _ rather
than a musical because Hwang didn't want to go through the lengthy
process of finding a composer and lyricist.
   ``I did no research on the story itself because the fact that
the incident existed was enough for me,'' he says. ``I wanted to
interpret it in my own way. Instead, I did a lot of research on the
period _ what type of secrets could have been passed in the early
'60s, the origins of the Vietnam War and what was going on in
China.''
   Before the end of 1986, Ostrow optioned the play for production.
John Dexter, director of ``Equus,'' came aboard in 1987, and a year
was spent casting and raising the $1.2 million needed to bring the
play to New York. When it opened in March 1988 at the Eugene
O'Neill Theater, John Lithgow was starred as the hapless diplomat
and B.D. Wong played the exotic Chinese opera singer.
   ``Broadway always was the goal,'' Hwang says. ``I thought this
was a play that had some commercial potential, but it had never
occurred to me, growing up and working in the non-profit theater,
that you could initiate a production on Broadway.''
   ``M. Butterfly'' is the first Broadway play for the 30-year-old
Hwang, even though he has had extensive credits off-Broadway. He
made his mark there in the early 1980s with plays about
Chinese-Americans such as ``FOB,'' ``The Dance and the Railroad''
and ``Family Devotions.''
   Hwang was raised as a musician, not a writer. His first theater
experiences were playing violin in the pit orchestra for amateur
musicals. But at age 12, he wrote a detailed family history,
divided into three generations.
   ``My mother's family were wealthy Chinese merchants who went to
the Philippines in the 19th century,'' Hwang says. ``My father's
family came from Shanghai where my paternal grandfather was a
businessman.''
   Hwang's parents arrived in the United States to go to school _
his father to study business at the University of Southern
California, his mother to study piano. They met at a foreign
students' dance at USC.
   Hwang was born in Los Angeles and grew up in a comfortable
California suburb. He has two younger sisters, one a cellist and
the other an elementary school teacher.
   Hwang's father wanted him to study business in college. But he
ended up at Stanford which didn't have an undergraduate business
program, so he majored in English literature.
   ``I started writing plays in college,'' Hwang says.``I liked the
idea of creating a world which then would exist in front of you.''
   In 1978, he studied writing with Sam Shepard and Maria Irene
Fornes at the fledgling Padua Hills Playwrights Festival in
Claremont, Calif.
   ``It was a real mind opener for me,'' Hwang says. ``They helped
me get in touch with my subconscious, in terms of using the
subconscious to influence your work and give your characters life.''
   Out of the festival came ``FOB,'' the story of a young Chinese
man _ ``fresh off the boat'' _ coming to United States to live with
his Chinese-American relatives. The play was first performed at his
Stanford dormitory, and during his senior year it was accepted by
the National Playwrights Conference in Connecticut. From there in
the summer of 1979, ``FOB'' was picked up by the New York
Shakespeare Festival for production in New York in 1980.
   ``After that, I kind of had a career,'' Hwang says. ``I've
always been able to make a living as a writer. It's been a
combination of the play writing, some film and television writing
and grants.''
   Now he's cautiously enjoying his fame as a Tony Award-winning
playwright.
   ``I had a vaccination against this at a younger age,'' Hwang
says. ``When I was in my early 20s, I had a certain amount of work
done. Not at this level, but I got a certain amount of attention
and dealt with these things at a smaller level. I like to think
that I'm more prepared.''
   Since the opening of ``M. Butterfly,'' Hwang has turned his
attention to a new music-theater monologue he is creating with
Glass and designer Jerome Sirlin. It's called ``1,000 Airplanes on
the Roof'' and concerns the unlikely subject of UFO abductions. The
piece, starring actor Rocco Sisto, premieres in Vienna this month
and comes to the United States in September.
   Hwang, who lives in Los Angeles with his wife, Ophelia, would
like to get back to writing his next play. One already has been
commissioned by the South Coast Repertory of Costa Mesa, Calif.,
which received a Tony this year as outstanding regional theater.
   ``When I'm working on a play, the play determines the hours,''
he says. ``I can write continuously. Consequently, I can finish my
plays fairly quickly, usually between three and six weeks.''
   Hwang feels he gradually has been able to get attention as a
playwright, not a Chinese-American playwright.
   ``I feel less like a spokesman for Asian-American playwrights
than I did the last time around,'' says Hwang, referring to the
days when ``FOB'' and ``The Dance and the Railroad'' first
attracted attention. ``Those early plays were specifically
Chinese-American.
   ``Today, I am less inclined to accept the role of spokesman for
the Asian-American community. Once, I felt duty-bound to fulfill
it. Now I feel it's not really possible for me to be any kind of
spokesman for any view other than my own.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, July 10</NOTE>
