<1ST_LINE>s i BC-SwingingCanton Adv03   06-27 0503</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Swinging Canton, Adv 03,0516</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv03</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, July 3, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Canton Swings while the Rest of China Sleeps</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-Pearl River Delta, b0681</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN BIERS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CANTON, China (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   While China sleeps, Canton swings.
   It is the nation's neon-lit nightlife capital, where people dine
and dance into the wee hours.
   Cantonese are known for ``going all out to make money and going
all out to enjoy it,'' explained 24-year-old singer Yuan Jun,
originally from the northern city of Harbin some 1,800 miles away.
   ``In the rest of China, most people are asleep by 10 p.m.,''
said Yuan, exaggerating just a bit. ``In Canton, in the middle of
the night there are still plenty of places to go,'' he added,
exaggerating not at all.
   Per capita disposable income in Canton, the steamy Pearl River
port capital of southeastern Guangdong province, was 1,416 yuan
($381) last year, or 175 percent above the national average.
   Many Canton residents use their pocket money to go dancing at
one of the city's ballrooms, which number 135 by government count.
   On a recent Saturday night, the Nanfang Dance Hall was packed
with customers paying 10 yuan ($2.69) each to swing to Cantonese
hits. Three separate seatings of 250 people each were scheduled for
the evening, with the closing set for 3:45 a.m.
   The city's electronic game rooms also were busy. Most of the 11
machines by the Yonghan Theater were in use at 30 fen (8 cents) a
game, typically bringing in 200 yuan ($54) on a busy day.
   Streets near the popular district along the Pearl River were
full of people well past midnight, with many strollers stopping to
drink tea or snack at the sidewalk restaurants that stay open as
late as 3 a.m.
   Even ``cruising'' has come to Canton, a city of about 3 million
people. Two men pulled a sedan up to a pair of young women walking
outside the Nanfang and beckoned them inside. The women hesitated,
but finally climbed in.
   Prostitution and gambling, which Communist authorities in
Beijing spent years trying to stamp out, also have returned to the
Canton region. Guangdong province recorded 5,600 cases of venereal
disease last year, up three times from 1986.
   Canton seems more in step with the capitalist British colony of
Hong Kong, about 90 miles to the southeast, than with Beijing, the
national capital where most restaurants close by 8 p.m. and people
spend their summer evenings playing chess and cards under street
lights.
   Does Canton's lust for fun and games mean communist morals are
on the decline? At least one top city official scoffs at the notion
that dancing and communism are incompatible.
   Deputy Mayor Lei Yu says Canton's people work hard during the
day and are entitled to relax at nights.
   Invoking the names of the two men primarily responsible for
bringing communism to China, Lei ends the argument: ``Mao Tse-tung
danced and so did (Red Army leader) Zhu De.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, July 3</NOTE>
</DOC>
