<DOCNO> AP880627-0228 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-27-88 1459EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>s p BC-ConventionCity Adv03   06-27 0962</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Convention City, Adv 03,0983</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv03</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, July 3 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Convention '88</HEAD>
<BYLINE>A Look At The Home Of GWTW, Hartsfield and Ted Turner
^By ROBERT BYRD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The city the Democrats have picked for the
nomination of the 41st president _ they hope _ is known to
outsiders as the home of ``Gone With The Wind,'' one very busy
airport and three historically rotten sports teams.
   To those who live here, Atlanta is a city that's easy on the
eyes and fairly low on stress, once even winning Rand McNally's
``most liveable'' designation. A city with no hurricanes and very
little snow. A city that has always taken a great deal of pride in
itself, despite the problems that plague many counterparts: crime,
poverty and the rest.
   Metro Atlanta, with no mountains or oceans to stop it, spreads
in every direction across 18 counties, where about 2.5 million
people live _ 41 percent of Georgia's population. With around
425,000 in the city itself, most ``Atlantans'' actually live in the
suburbs. The average house costs $100,000, and the average salary
is a shade over $19,000.
   Not much is left of Atlanta from the Civil War days _ indeed,
its burning at the hands of Union forces made a spectacular scene
in ``GWTW,'' as the locals are wont to abbreviate the movie.
   Yes, Hartsfield Atlanta International Airport is entrenched in
an ongoing battle with Chicago's O'Hare for the ``nation's
busiest'' title. But it is, after all, an airport, and you do not
often think about it.
   The world's most accurate perception of life in Atlanta may be
of its sporting life. The Braves, the Falcons and the Hawks really
have been, through their history, pretty rotten. In Atlanta's 23
years as a ``big league city,'' through 75 seasons _ including
eight by the Flames hockey team, which up and left _ citizens have
yet to be inconvenienced by the rigors of lining up for tickets to
a championship game.
   (A long-dead soccer team, the Atlanta Chiefs, did play for a
championship once _ and won _ but you didn't exactly have to camp
out to get in.)
   To get around, Atlantans get in the car. The city enjoys an
extensive bus system and a clean, fast train operation, but trains
serve only four lines, which end at commuter lots in the suburbs,
and the system covers only two counties.
   Two other heavily populated suburban counties, Cobb and
Gwinnett, have rejected joining MARTA, the Metropolitan Atlanta
Rapid Transit Authority. The most often stated reasons are fear of
crime and taxes, although it is widely understood that more than a
few in Atlanta's white suburbs fear the train will bring blacks
into their neighborhoods.
   That's a painful admission for a city that then-Mayor William B.
Hartsfield, during the civil rights movement of the late 1950s,
called ``the city too busy to hate.''
   But Atlanta struggles still with racism.
   The city itself is 66 percent black; the 18-county metro area is
74 percent white. While the metro area's cost-of-living ranks
eighth best among the nation's large urban areas, the city itself
is the second-poorest in the nation, with 28 percent of its people
living in poverty.
   Although metro Atlanta's school systems and public places are
integrated, most individual schools and neighborhoods are not. And
in the housing projects of the inner city, the drug trade and its
attendant crime make regular headlines.
   The city's elected leadership is predominantly black, a point of
pride for those surveying civil rights gains in the United States.
But it is not untroubled: two Fulton County commissioners are
facing jail terms for vote-selling convictions, including A.
Reginald Eaves, who was public safety commissioner under Atlanta's
first black mayor, Maynard Jackson.
   The city has sustained a major business boom for the past three
decades, the root of its ``too busy to hate'' boast.
   Ted Turner's once-homey little TV station, which once used a dog
as a co-host of the news, has grown into a global news and
communications empire known as Cable News Network. City fathers in
the mid-'60s built a major-league sports stadium before they had a
team to put in it.
   The same booster spirit was evidenced earlier this year when
Atlanta surprised even itself by winning designation as the U.S.
candidate to host the 1996 Summer Olympics.
   Atlantans like to say, with a knowing smile, that their city is
``a nice place to live, but you wouldn't want to visit here.''
However, tourist attractions can be found.
   Metro Atlanta has Stone Mountain, a mammoth granite hill with a
popular park surrounding it, and the Memorial Arts Center, home of
the High Museum of Art and the award-winning Atlanta Symphony
Orchestra.
   There is also the restored birthplace of Martin Luther King Jr.
and the nearby King Center; the Carter Presidential Center, home of
the former president's museum, library and policy forum, and an
increasing number of nightclubs, bars and first-quality restaurants.
   Atlanta also has 100 Waffle House restaurants, which ``lead the
WORLD in serving T-bone Steaks, Grits and Waffles,'' and a
mystifying number of Mexican restaurants. The Varsity, meanwhile,
bills itself as the world's largest drive-in restaurant.
   Atlanta has Piedmont Park, a tranquil lawn surrounded by the
commotion of the city in the manner of New York's Central Park. It
has Grant Park, which contains an ambitiously renovating zoo and
the Cyclorama, the world's largest painting, depicting the Civil
War's Battle of Atlanta.
   And Atlanta, after all, does have National League baseball, a
National Football League team, and a representative of the National
Basketball Association. You can cheer a Dale Murphy home run or a
Dominique Wilkins slam dunk.
   Tickets aren't that hard to get.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, July 3</NOTE>
