<NOTE>For Release Sunday, July 3, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Convention '88</HEAD>
<HEAD>Democrats Will Leave Financial Impact On Atlanta</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN A. BOLT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Local leaders figure the Democratic National
Convention will make a $60 million impact on Atlanta's economy and
the Democratic Party hopes to cash in too.
   In addition, business owners are hoping to take advantage of the
presence in town of so many political and corporate decision-makers
by doing a little lobbying on their own behalf.
   The party itself is selling rights to use the convention logo on
various souvenirs _ including a official, licensed, party-approved
donkey call.
   One study done in conjunction with Atlanta's bid for the
convention estimated that the overall economic impact will be $58.7
million. A second study placed the amount at $64.3 million. It all
depends on how many thousands of people actually show up.
   Less measurable is the amount of business that might be done as
a result of contacts during convention week.
   But Barry King, Atlanta Chamber of Commerce vice president for
communications, says that ``every high-roller in political circles
will be here.''
   ``It's an opportunity for Atlanta to be seen and Atlantans to be
seen and for anybody to make a deal,'' he said.
   By offering decision-makers a good time, businesses hope to gain
an edge when contract time comes around. Or by staging an event
where customers can rub elbows with the famous and powerful,
businesses hope to benefit from kind memories later on.
   On the more concrete side, the studies estimate convention
visitors, including about 15,000 members of the news media, will
spend:
   _Between $9.6 million and $10.5 million on hotel rooms.
   _Between $3.8 million and $4.3 million in hotel restaurants.
   _Between $4.9 million and $5.2 million in other restaurants.
   _Some $1.5 million in hospitality suites.
   _Between $1.9 million and $2.2 million on entertainment.
   _Between $3 million and $3.4 million in retail stores.
   _Between $2.3 million and $2.5 million on local transportation.
   _Between $1.1 million and $1.2 million on miscellaneous
purchases.
   All that adds up to a direct impact of $28.1 million, using a
study based on the 17,200 hotel rooms reserved for the convention,
or $30.8 million, based on 35,000 visitors.
   The Atlanta Convention and Visitors Bureau says each convention
dollar spent in the city turns over 2.09 times in the local
economy, giving a total direct and indirect impact of $58.7 million
or $64.3 million.
   Mark Weiner Sr., who is in charge of policing use of the
convention logo, said there'll be the usual assortment of buttons,
T-shirts, coffee mugs, pens, pencils and other paraphernalia
available for folks who want to remember Atlanta.
   And there's the donkey call. ``It's on a string that you wear
around your neck and emulates the sounds of a donkey,'' Weiner said.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, July 3</NOTE>
