<1ST_LINE>s p BC-Convention-Peachtree Adv03   06-27 0430</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Convention-Peachtree, Adv 03,0444</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv03</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, July 3, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Convention '88</HEAD>
<HEAD>Peachtree Street, Road, Industrial Boulevard Atlanta's Main Drag</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN A. BOLT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   There are three Main Streets in Atlanta, but none
is the main street.
   That is Peachtree Street, just plain Peachtree Street _ not
Peachtree Circle, Peachtree Court, Peachtree Drive, Peachtree Lane,
Peachtree Parkway, Peachtree Place, Peachtree Battle Avenue,
Peachtree Battle Circle, Peachtree Corners Circle, Peachtree Park
Drive, West Peachtree Street or any of the other almost 30 streets
named in some way after peach trees.
   Just plain Peachtree Street, the one without any peach trees.
   Just plain Peachtree Street, the one with ``P'tree Street'' on
the road signs because the full name won't fit.
   To be exactly honest, however, it's only just plain Peachtree
Street for 4.3 miles. Then it becomes Peachtree Road for 7.7 miles,
then it transforms into Peachtree Industrial Boulevard and fades
away into four counties, eight towns and one deer crossing miles
away in the northeast Georgia foothills.
   And to be precise, Peachtree Road and Peachtree Industrial
Boulevard run side-by-side, sort of, for 2.8 miles. Luckily, it's
not at the same place where West Peachtree Street runs parallel to
Peachtree Street for about about a mile.
   Confused? Welcome to Atlanta!
   A trip along Peachtree's length touches almost all parts of
Atlanta life.
   The street's southern tip rests underneath a rapid rail track. A
few blocks later, you're at Five Points, the foot of the downtown
business district.
   Next comes office towers rising on either side of the tree-lined
street as it curves its way to Midtown, the center of the city's
arts life.
   Out a ways, you reach Buckhead, long the city's most upscale
area, and then Lenox, a busy retail region.
   After that, the character begins to change from bustling to
bristling.
   There are apartment buildings, condominiums, car lots. Then the
road narrows from six to four to two lanes and the traffic lights
become sparser.
   Finally, 44.1 miles from its beginning, the road becomes plain
old McEven Road.
   As it winds through the city and suburbs, Peachtree crosses
other streets named for famous Georgians: Martin Luther King Jr.
Boulevard, Ralph McGill Boulevard, Jimmy Carter Boulevard.
   It also crosses Mitchell Street _ named for the man who donated
land for Atlanta's first railroad station, not Margaret Mitchell,
author of ``Gone With The Wind.'' She, by the way, was run over and
killed in 1949 by a cab while trying to cross, you guessed it,
Peachtree Street.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, July 3</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880627-0232 </DOCNO>
