<1ST_LINE>s p BC-Convention-Hotels Adv03   06-27 0554</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Convention-Hotels, Adv 03,0568</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv03</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, July 3 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Convention '88</HEAD>
<HEAD>Power, Geography And Lady Luck Determine Where Democrats Stay</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CURT ANDERSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Power, geography and the luck of the draw will
decide where Democrats stay during their national convention this
month.
   VIPS, financial gurus and party brass automatically get the best
hotels, while state delegates and journalists divvy up about 18,000
rooms in 106 other hotels dotting a four-county area.
   Even private dwellings are getting into the act under a
``Host-a-Home'' program that will open up some of Atlanta's best
addresses to Democrats from across the country.
   But as the convention draws near, some lingering questions about
lodging remain.
   Convention spokeswoman Ruth Berry said housing plans won't be
finalized for another week, a situation that gives hotel managers
the fits, but she said flatly that everybody will get a room.
   Only the Georgia delegation, which plays host to the convention,
got to choose its hotel outright. Chairman John Henry Anderson
selected the Omni International, which is connected to both The
Omni arena and the Georgia World Congress Center, twin sites of the
convention.
   Last October, the Democratic Party's other state chairmen used
an unusual lottery to decide where their delegations will stay and
where they will sit during the nominating process _ courtesy of the
Atlanta Braves baseball team.
   The chairmen, meeting in Washington last October, picked
numbered baseballs out of a bin, each signed by major league home
run king Henry Aaron. No. 1 was chosen by Louisiana, and State
Chairman James J. Brady promptly selected the Atlanta Hilton.
   The state getting first choice for lodging got the last choice
for seating on the convention floor, said Ms. Berry.
   Maryland chose the final baseball and wound up in a Holiday Inn,
but its delegates will have front-row seats when the Democrats
nominate their presidential candidate.
   Two other delegations, from Minnesota and South Dakota, were
barred from the lottery because they violated party rules by
failing to adhere to the national party's deadline for primary
season events, Ms. Berry said. They ended up at some of the more
far-flung motels, a traffic-clogged 45 minutes away from the
convention site.
   While lodging ranges from the posh Hilton to chain hotels on
neon-lined strips in the Atlanta suburbs, the Democratic Party's
powers-that-be will put their feet up in either the Ritz-Carlton or
the Westin Peachtree Plaza.
   The party apparatus itself will operate out of the Marriott
Marquis and the Hyatt Regency, both downtown high-rises. That means
Democrats and their top financiers will take up the biggest part of
four of the city's best hotels, all of which were exempt from the
state-by-state lottery.
   And under the ``Host-a-Home'' campaign, devised by Jerry
Skelton, some delegates and reporters will be staying with owners
willing to open their doors.
   Roger and Dee Whitney, who own a $350,000 home in Cobb County
just northwest of Atlanta, said they joined the program not because
of politics _ they are Republicans _ but because they wanted to be
a part of one of the biggest events in recent Atlanta history.
   ``This convention is putting Atlanta in the spotlight, and we'd
like to think we had a small part in all the excitement,'' said
Mrs. Whitney.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, July 3</NOTE>
</DOC>
