<FILEID>AP-NR-06-27-88 1250EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a a BC-EXP--SavingGermplasm Adv30   06-27 1249</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-EXP--Saving Germplasm, Adv 30,1290</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv30</NOTE>
<NOTE>For release Thursday, June 30, and thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Safeguarding The World's Food Supply: Working To Expand Gene Banks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL RAEBURN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Editor</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BELTSVILLE, Md. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When southern corn leaf blight wiped out
15 percent of the U.S. corn crop in 1970 at a cost of more than $1
billion, plant breeders scrambled and within two years found
varieties resistant to the disease.
   Ironically, it was the breeders who had helped to start the
disaster.
   Aiming for better varieties, they had unknowingly bred
susceptibility to the blight into fully 80 percent of the nation's
corn crop. Without that genetic uniformity, the blight would have
done little damage.
   The same reliance on uniform crops led to the Irish potato
famine of the 1840s and to the spread of a wheat disease in 1916
that led Herbert Hoover to call for two wheatless days each week.
   The danger is that it could happen again.
   According to Peter Day, director of the Center for Agricultural
Molecular Biology at Rutgers University, too little is being done
to prevent such epidemics.
   ``What we're concerned about is having back-up ability to deal
with future threats,'' Day said during a recent U.S. Department of
Agriculture conference on ``Biotic Diversity and Germplasm
Preservation _ Global Imperatives.''
   ``Germplasm'' is the breeder's term for the hereditary
information in plants or animals. When breeders encounter a crisis
like the southern corn leaf blight, they search for
disease-resistance genes in domesticated and wild varieties of the
threatened crop.
   The United States has no naturally occurring wild varieties of
its major food crops. Tomatoes come from Central and South America,
wheat and barley from the Middle East and soybeans from Asia.
Virtually every major food crop is native to some other part of the
world.
   ``The U.S. is a have-not nation in terms of germplasm
resources,'' said Henry Shands, director of the National Plant
Germplasm System, operated by the USDA's Agricultural Research
Service. ``We've got to have a certain amount of gene bank defense
to protect our nation's food supply in the future.''
   Without those breeding resources, Shands said, ``the agriculture
systems are going to collapse. We just don't have enough land.''
   Collecting germplasm in foreign countries is often a politically
delicate task, complicated by what is usually called the
``north-south debate.'' This refers to the unwillingness of some
tropical and semi-tropical countries rich in germplasm (the south)
to export their resources to the industrialized nations (the north).
   Many of the tropical countries complain they are forced to pay
industrial nations a hefty price for seeds produced from the
tropical countries' own resources.
   Some have done more than complain. Ethiopia has largely cut off
access to its germplasm resources, for example. And many nations
that could help each other _ such as North Korea and South Korea _
refuse to exchange germplasm with one another because of the tense
political relations between them.
   The United States maintains germplasm collections around the
country, with a central repository, the National Seed Storage
Laboratory, in Fort Collins, Colo.
   But not enough is being done to evaluate and use those genetic
resources, researchers say. And the programs cover only plants. No
organized program exists to collect and store the germplasm of
important farm animals.
   Unfortunately, financial support for germplasm collection and
evaluation is lacking, Shands said. The National Plant Germplasm
System budget increased from almost $14 million in 1986 to $26.5
million this year, but despite USDA appeals, no increases were
proposed for next year.
   Additional funds are needed to speed the incorporation of
disease resistance into food crops, which reduces the need for
pesticides, improving food safety and water quality, Shands said.
   ``Whales receive enormous attention while seeds go unnoticed,''
said Lawrence Busch of the University of Kentucky. ``Some
absolutely minute and totally unattractive grass might be as
important as that whale.''
   For example, a tall wild wheat collected in Eastern Turkey in
1948 was found to carry genes that made domestic wheat resistant to
common and dwarf bunt and made it better able to tolerate stripe
rust, snow mold and mildew, said Sherl Dietz, coordinator of the
Agricultural Research Service's Western Regional Plant Introduction
Station in Pullman, Wash.
   The transfer of disease-resistance genes from wild strawberries
to commercial varieties has helped increase strawberry yields by
300 percent since 1960, said Dietz. Similar advances have been made
in other crops.
   Part of the urgency in conserving germplasm comes from the
escalating destruction of forests and other natural habitats around
the world.
   Up to 20,000 species of plants and animals become extinct each
year because of land clearing, urban development and overgrazing,
said Waldemar Klassen, director of the Agricultural Research Center
in Beltsville.
   ``The loss of unique plants and animals will deny future
generations the use of still undiscovered genes for new foods,
fibers and medicines and industrial raw materials,'' he said.
   With its limited resources, the Agricultural Research Service
does the best it can to collect germplasm before it is lost, Shands
said. A botanist will go to Pakistan soon, for example, to retrace
ancient trade routes in search of citrus fruits and other crops
that may have been planted by the traders who followed Marco Polo
to the Orient.
   It's possible crops that have been lost in Europe and the Middle
East might survive in those isolated regions. Farmers are rapidly
clearing the land there, and the opportunity to search for unusual
crops won't last long, he said.
   Storing germplasm is a tricky business. Although it's tempting
to think of plant gene banks as libraries from which breeders can
pluck genetic information they need, gene banks differ from
libraries in one important respect: the gene banks are alive.
   Plant germplasm is stored largely in the form of seeds. They
last a long time _ nobody is quite sure how long; 50 or 100 years
might be a good guess depending on the species _ but they don't
last forever.
   At the National Small Grain Collection in Beltsville, David
Smith oversees 108,000 specimens of grains including wheat, barley,
oats, rye, rice and triticale, a wheat-rye hybrid.
   Seeds are stored in small, manila envelopes, with a maximum of
500 grams of seed (about a pound) kept on hand for each sample. The
envelopes are stored in metal boxes stacked on tall,
industrial-style steel shelves in a room where the temperature is
kept at 50 degrees Fahrenheit.
   Breeders requesting samples are sent about 5 grams, enough to
grow a row about five feet long, Smith said. When stocks run low,
seeds are planted and grown to replenish the seed supply.
   That also provides an opportunity to further identify the
genetic traits contained in the seeds, but the process has a cost.
Some genes in the original batch appear again in the new
generation; some don't. ``Every time you regenerate seeds you lose
a little diversity,'' says Shands.
   Information on U.S. germplasm is kept in a database called the
Germplasm Resources Information Network, or GRIN, which is
available to any plant breeder.
   Such resources will be essential to feed a world that will
support 6 billion people by the year 2000. The world's farmers will
have to produce more food in one generation than has been produced
in the entire 10,000-year history of agriculture, said Garrison
Wilkes of the University of Massachusetts, and maintaining genetic
diversity will be a global imperative.
   ``There will be no synthetic food,'' Wilkes said. ``You can't
look for substitute technology.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for June 30</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880627-0236 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-27-88 1300EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a a BC-EXP--TextbookWatchdogs Adv30   06-27 0639</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-EXP--Textbook Watchdogs, Adv 30,0658</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv30</NOTE>
<NOTE>For release Thursday, June 30, and thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>New Newsletter, ``Bookwatch,'' Finds Science Texts Botching Facts</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LEE MITGANG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Education Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Add inaccuracy to the multitude of sins critics
are attributing to science texts these days.
   Critics of science texts have lately accused publishers of
``dumbing down'' their books, of making them dull, and of pandering
to interest groups who oppose the teaching of evolution on
religious grounds.
   Above all, they charge, science texts with their predictable
experiments and boring vocabulary lists are at least partly to
blame for turning a fascinating subject into one students want to
avoid.
   Now it seems such texts may be guilty of botching elementary
scientific facts, according to ``Bookwatch,'' a first-of-its-kind,
no-holds-barred monthly newsletter devoted to reviewing junior high
and high school science texts.
   ``Bookwatch,'' was launched in February by William V. Mayer,
emeritus professor of biology of the University of Colorado, and
William J. Bennetta, a research associate and fellow of the
California Academy of Science.
   Each issue offers three 1,000-word reviews by practicing
scientists and science educators.
   Bennetta said he first became interested in science texts in
1985 when California education authorities drew national attention
by successfully demanding that publishers devote more space to
evolution.
   ``For the first time I looked into the kinds of textbooks being
submitted, and was severely disappinted by what I saw,'' he said.
   The newsletter, published by the National Center for Science
Education in Berkeley, Calif., claims to be to science texts what
``Consumer Reports'' is to retail products: a candid review free of
influence from publishers. It's aimed at teachers and state
officials responsible for selecting science texts.
   The reviews in the four editions published so far identified an
array of factual errors.
   The teacher's edition of ``Life Science 1987,'' a junior high
biology text published by Scott, Foresman and Co., states,
incorrectly, that the word ``biology'' derives from Latin roots
meaning the study of life. As reviewer Michael T. Ghiselin pointed
out, the word is rooted in Greek.
   Prentice-Hall's ``Biology 1987,'' inaccurately tells 10th
graders that electron microscopes were around in 1931 _ about 30
years before they were in use, according to reviewer Colin O.
Hermans, professor of biology at Sonoma State University.
   Lawrence W. Swan, a biology professor at San Francisco State
University, found that the teacher's edition of D.C. Heath and
Co.'s ``Life Science 1987'' text for middle-school students was
``loaded with errors.''
   The text shows a picture of a lemur, but wrongly calls it a
monkey. It presents a map incorrectly showing the range of the
American opossum extending to northernmost Alaska. The map ``also
shows both monotremes and marsupials in New Zealand, though New
Zealand has neither,'' according to the review.
   The authors of Scott, Foresman's text, ``Biology 1988,'' ``guess
that ...a fish has hipbones and a human-type pelvis'' and ``they
depict the hazardous dumping of chemical wastes as something `in
the past,''' write Mayer and Bennetta.
   Bennetta said he has not heard from publishers so far, but has
gotten numerous encouraging letters from education officials.
   But Kate Nyquist, vice president of science and health at Scott,
Foresman, said that while she has ``a great deal of respect'' for
the National Center for Science Education, ``Bookwatch is one of
their least productive enterprises.''
   ``I'm not saying we don't make any mistakes and we're always
grateful to have them pointed out. But to say as the newsletter did
that this book is `scientifically meaningless' is rather global,
and not correct.''
   She said her company takes the newsletter ``very seriously, but
it criticizes from a very narrow perspective. It can hurt my
business. But I don't think our customers recognize it as a
constructive evaluation tool.''
   Calls to Prentice-Hall and D.C. Heath were not returned.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for June 30</NOTE>
</DOC>
