<1ST_LINE>a a BC-SPE--School:WithTuition-CollegeBoard     06-27 0165</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-SPE--School: With Tuition-College Board,0171</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>BC-SPECIAL EDITION</HEAD>
<HEAD>SCHOOL: With Tuition-College Board</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   To help parents sort out some of the confusion of paying college
tuition, the College Board recently compiled a list of questions
consumers should ask to help them decide if college prepayment or
savings plans fill their needs.
   Among them:
   _ Does the plan require a minimum contribution to enter?
   _ Can anyone in the family contribute to the plan, or are there
exclusions?
   _ Can proceeds from the plan be transferred to other members of
the family if the named beneficiary's educational plans change?
   _ Are benefits restricted to colleges in a given state, or to a
particular class of colleges, such as privates?
   _ How does the plan guarantee its benefits?
   _ Does the plan cover all costs, or just tuition?
   _ Does the plan have residency requirements?
   _ What are the refund conditions in case a student isn't
admitted to college, or dies, or becomes disabled?
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880627-0243 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-27-88 0155EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a a BC-SPE--School:StudyAbroad(     06-27 0796</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-SPE--School: Study Abroad(,0817</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>BC-SPECIAL EDITION</HEAD>
<HEAD>SCHOOL: Study Abroad</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY702</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL ALLEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Newsfeatures</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bronwen E. Latimer, a 24-year-old New Yorker who
will be entering the Columbia University School of Journalism in
the fall, is studying French at the Sorbonne in Paris this summer.
   Elizabeth Cohen, 18, of Austin, Texas, two summers ago spent six
weeks in Salamanca, Spain, studying Spanish language and culture.
Now entering her sophomore year at Vassar College, Poughkeepsie,
N.Y., she plans to spend her junior year in Rome or Florence
studying art.
   They are among tens of thousands of American students reversing
a recent trend and going to foreign countries to study. According
to the Institute of International Education (IIE), the nation's
largest education exchange agency, 48,483 students earned academic
credit for studies outside the United States in 1985-86, up from
27,145 in 1982-83 _ nearly double the number in three years.
   The study offered no explanation for the increase. But
administrators of study-abroad programs said that at least some
students may be finding that study overseas is economical compared
with the more expensive U.S. schools where tuitions have been
soaring throughout the 1980s.
   Beaver College in Glenside, Pa., is noted for study-abroad
programs in which students from 225 U.S. colleges participate. The
school is sending more than 1,700 students from U.S. campuses to
study in the British Isles and Vienna this year, said college
President Bette Landman, compared with 750 students in 1980-81.
   Landman says she believes the increase stems from ``an
increasing sensitivity among students to foreign study, not only to
help their careers, but especially in the last year or two, to the
kinds of understandings we as world citizens must bring to our
lives.''
   At Northern Illinois University, where the number of students in
overseas programs has risen at least 10 percent in that period,
Orville Jones, assistant dean of international programs, says that
since more students have traveled during their high school years,
the thought of studying overseas is no longer as strange or
frightening.
   The IIE survey, which does not include American students earning
credits toward degrees in foreign institutions, found that 76.8
percent of U.S. students abroad were studying in Western Europe.
   The most popular country, Great Britain, attracted 29.3 percent
of all students studying abroad, followed by France with 13.7
percent, Spain with 8.8 percent, Italy 7.8 percent, and West
Germany 6.1 percent.
   Latin America attracted 7 percent, with smaller percentages
studying in Asia, the Middle East, Eastern Europe and Africa.
   ``I would hope that as the growth continues, American students
will go to developing countries in Africa and Latin American
countries,'' said Richard Kranos, IIE president.
   Nearly 90 percent of the students were in programs sponsored by
U.S. colleges and universities, the survey found. The most popular
field of study was liberal arts, with 18.2 percent, followed by
foreign language with 16.7 percent.
   Almost two-thirds, or 63.8 percent, of U.S. students abroad were
female, according to the report.
   The survey was conducted by mail last year with 2,896 accredited
U.S. colleges and universities, of which 1,898 reported students
earning academic credit for study abroad.
   The American Institute for Foreign Study says it will send about
37,000 students, 24,000 of whom are high school students, abroad
this year.
   ``They are realizing that it will improve their chances of
getting into the college of their choice and it is something
special on their resume when they go to look for their first job to
be able to say they spent some time abroad studying,'' says Henry
Kahn, president of the Greenwich, Conn.,-based institute.
   ``Every morning when you open the newspaper, the headlines are
from other parts of the world. If young people are going to be able
to understand and relate to our interdependent, global society,
they have to study in other countries. This will enable them to
learn their languages, their cultures and their unique feelings
about the United States.
   ``This study-abroad experience provides both personal growth and
educational enrichment.''
   Elizabeth Cohen echoes the thought: ``It's a great thing to be
able to say, `I studied at the University of Salamanca,' because it
is a famous university,'' she said.
   ``I would not trade that experience for anything in the world.
It was the greatest summer of my life. I met some of the greatest
people I've ever met.''
   Julia Logan, 21, a 1988 graduate of Yale University with a
degree in biology, had visited the Soviet Union twice while
studying Russian at Yale.
   ``I think it can only help for Americans to visit the Soviet
Union and for the Soviets to visit here.
   ``I remember a Russian proverb that goes something like, `It is
better to see once than to hear a hundred times,''' she said.
</TEXT>
