<DOCNO> AP880627-0246 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-27-88 0157EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a a BC-SPE--School:Reform     06-27 0875</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-SPE--School: Reform,0894</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>BC-SPECIAL EDITION</HEAD>
<HEAD>SCHOOL: Reform</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CONNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Education Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Five years after a group of sages fired a
rocket called ``A Nation At Risk'' across America's schools, some
prominent educators believe little progress has been made so far in
rolling back the tide of mediocrity.
   But another school of opinion argues that the trend indicators _
from real wage growth for teachers to burgeoning high school
enrollments in advanced placement classes _ are pointing up and
foretell brighter days ahead.
   There is no gainsaying one fact: America's schools are still
riding a wave of reform and renewed public interest unprecedented
since the Soviets' 1957 launch of Sputnik forced political and
educational leaders to do some prolonged soul-searching about U.S.
schools.
   Those who look at the school reform movement and see a glass at
best half-empty include Secretary of Education William J. Bennett
and his predecessor, T.H. Bell; Ernest L. Boyer, president of the
influential Carnegie Foundation for the Advancement of Teaching,
and the presidents of both major teacher unions, Mary Hatwood
Futrell and Albert Shanker.
   The most vigorous proponent of the argument that school reform
is already paying sizeable dividends is Bill Honig, California's
superintendent of public instruction, who has played a central role
in efforts to toughen school curriculums and create a new, national
certification board for teachers.
   ``A Nation At Risk'' was issued in April 1983 by an 18-member
National Commission on Excellence in Education, instructed to find
out why scores on exams such as the Scholastic Aptitude Test
plummeted from 1963 through 1980.
   Bell, the Reagan administration's first secretary of education
who personally appointed the commission and who left Washington at
the end of Reagan's first term, writes in his memoirs, ``The
Thirteenth Man,'' that Reagan missed a chance to spark a real,
widespread educational revival.
   Bell, now at the University of Utah, contends that school
reforms such as stricter high school graduation requirements
imposed by most states have made things better for perhaps
two-thirds of American youth.
   But Bell contends reforms ``didn't do a darn thing'' to solve
the dropout problem or close the performance gap between affluent
students and the disadvantaged, many of them minorities. ``We're
losing 30 percent to 40 percent of the rising generation,'' says
Bell.
   Boyer's Carnegie Foundation warns that the reform movement ``has
largely bypassed our most deeply troubled schools'' in the inner
cities. The Committee on Economic Development, a policy research
group of business executives and academic leaders, came to a
similar conclusion.
   NEA President Futrell says the Carnegie and CED reports support
what the NEA was saying five years ago: that tougher standards
won't work without a major infusion of resources for the schools.
   ``We feel vindicated,'' said Futrell, who recently proposed
establishing at least one experimental ``lighthouse'' district in
all 50 states where ``anything goes'' in the name of school reform.
   Albert Shanker, president of the 665,000-member American
Federation of Teachers, supports a myriad of radical school reforms
in hundreds or even thousands of districts.
   Shanker is convinced that the passive structure of public
schools _ with a teacher standing before a class spending most of
the time lecturing _ is not working for 80 percent of all students,
not just the poor, but most of the middle class as well.
   He bases his case largely on the results of the
government-sponsored National Assessment of Educational Progress _
tests given to a cross-section of students that show only 20
percent of the 17-year-olds left in school can write a coherent
letter, and only 6 percent can solve the type of algebraic problems
taught in junior high.
   Shanker believes the only way to get markedly better results is
to radically reorganize schools, allowing teachers to work in teams
under the guidance of lead teachers, who would spend their days
consulting, preparing lessons and coaching individual students, who
would themselves work in small groups and learn the rote lessons
from computers, videotapes and other high tech tools. Students
would be freed to move ahead at their own pace.
   Bennett contends that traditional schools are far more effective
for disadvantaged students than Shanker gives them credit for.
Bennett argues that it is the poor who need most a rigorous,
classic curriculum.
   In a report, ``American Education: Making It Work,'' unveiled at
the White House on the fifth anniversary of ``A Nation At Risk,''
Bennett concluded:``American education has made some undeniable
progress in the last few years. The precipitous downward slide of
previous decades has been arrested, and we have begun the long
climb back to reasonable standards. Our students have made modest
gains in achievement. They are taking more classes in basic
subjects. ... ''
   ``But we are certainly not doing well enough, and we are not
doing well enough fast enough. We are still at risk. ...''
   California's Honig voiced a sharp dissent, citing the facts that
thousands of more students in his state now are taking three years
of math and science, and 41,000 earned college credit on advanced
placement exams last year, up 73 percent from 1984.
   ``I'm not saying we're anywhere near where we have to be, but
we're on the right track,'' said Honig. Reform ``has worked for
many kids in inner cities.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
