<1ST_LINE>a a BC-SPE--School:Notes     06-27 0198</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-SPE--School: Notes,0201</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>BC-SPECIAL EDITION</HEAD>
<HEAD>SCHOOL: Notes</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By THE ASSOCIATED PRESS</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Faulty note taking, reading and review hamper a student's recall
of facts and learning material and results in poor grades and
frustration, according to the head of the Chicago-based American
Learning Corp.
   ``Recall is the ability to write, tell or think in your own
words what you have seen, experienced or read,'' explains Robert
Baseman, president of the company, a subsidiary of Encyclopaedia
Britannica, Inc.
   ``Studies have shown that most forgetting occurs during the
first few days after one has been exposed to new material or
studied it for the first time. In fact, the average student forgets
40 to 50 percent of what he's learned in only one day, and within
two days, he may forget up to 85 percent.''
   Baseman suggests students include some review every time they
read or complete a homework assignment. In so doing, he adds, they
will retain and understand more than if they wait to review a large
amount of material _ such as immediately before a test.
   The American Learning Corp. administers the Evelyn Wood Study
Dynamics program and operates more than 100 learning centers across
the nation.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
