<1ST_LINE>r f PM-GETalks     06-27 0258</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-GE Talks,0267</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Tentative Agreement Reached in GE Talks</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   General Electric Co. has reached tentative
agreement with its two largest unions on a new three-year contract,
both sides reported.
   Negotiators for the company and the unions reached the accord
Sunday evening, several hours before the old contract was to
expire, said Jerry Borstel, spokesman for the International Union
of Electronic, Electrical, Salaried Machine and Furniture Workers
(IUE), and Jack Batty, a company spokesman.
   Earlier Sunday, the IUE and the United Electrical, Radio, and
Machine Workers of America (UE) gave the company a 10-day strike
notice, Borstel said.
   Details of the agreement were not released, pending ratification
by union members, who are scheduled to vote July 6.
   The IUE and UE have a combined membership of 47,000. Ten other
unions, representing another 21,000 GE workers, coordinate their
bargaining with the IUE and the UE although their contracts are
negotiated at the local plant level.
   The IUE represents about 40,000 workers in 75 locals at about
100 GE factories in Massachusetts, Kentucky, New York, Ohio and
Indiana. The UE represents about 6,300 GE employees in
Pennsylvania, Indiana and New York.
   The unions had said they were seeking a moratorium on plant
closings, a no-layoffs guarantee, better early retirement benefits,
stronger limits on subcontracting and other job security
improvements.
   They also wanted wage increases in each year of the new
contract, improvements in the cost of living formula, increases in
pension benefits, improvements in health and hospitalization
insurance, reimbursement for dependent care and prepaid
prescription drugs.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
