<1ST_LINE>r f PM-BraniffSale     06-27 0427</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Braniff Sale,0441</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Expansion Likely for New Braniff, Analysts Say</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EVAN RAMSTAD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The new leadership of Braniff Inc. pledges to
become a competitive force in the airline industry, but at least
one observer says reaching that goal will take time.
   Louis A. Marckesano, an airline industry analyst with Janney
Montgomery Scott Inc. in Philadelphia, said Sunday Braniff's market
position, wedged between the commuter airlines and the major
carriers, will make its survival difficult.
   ``That doesn't mean that they can't succeed,'' Marckesano said,
adding he doesn't expect any rapid expansion or downsizing of the
airline. ``I don't think we'll know the answer to that for a while.
They still have to find themselves a niche that they can survive in
long term.''
   BIA Acquisitions, an investor group led by PaineWebber Group
Inc., said Saturday it agreed to acquire Dallas-based Braniff in a
deal that values the airline at $111 million.
   Although Braniff posted a net loss of $8.1 million in the first
quarter, the airline has doubled its number of flights at Kansas
City International airport since the beginning of the year.
   Outgoing Braniff chairman J. Patrick Foley said the new
management will continue the expansion.
   Braniff primarily serves the Southwest, but analysts have
speculated it may try to reduce its operations at Dallas-Fort
Worth, where there is strong competition between American Airlines
and Delta Air Lines.
   BIA agreed to buy Braniff from Dalfort Aviation Inc., which is
owned by the Pritzker family of Chicago. BIA is paying $7 a share
in cash and a pro rata share of 20 percent of the restructured
airline for each share of Braniff common stock.
   BIA appointed five top executives who resigned from Piedmont
Airlines Friday to manage Braniff. The executives, led by new
chairman William McGee, flew to Dallas Sunday and were expected to
meet the company's employees and local media today.
   ``We intend for Braniff to become a strong competitive force in
our nation's air travel and hospitality industries,'' Jeffrey R.
Chodorow, one of BIA's leading investors, said in a statement
Saturday. He could not be reached at his Philadelphia home for
comment Sunday.
   The investor group has pledged to protect the jobs of Braniff's
2,600 employees for at least three years.
   Dalfort owned 64 percent of the airline's common stock and all
of its Series A preferred stock, which gave it more than 90 percent
of the stock voting rights.
   Dalfort will continue to hold a large equity stake in Braniff.
PaineWebber also will retain an equity interest in Braniff.
</TEXT>
