<2ND_LINE>PM-Seabrook,0182</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Utility Willing to Abandon Seabrook If Price Is Right</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NASHUA, N.H. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The main owner of the Seabrook nuclear power
plant acknowledged today that it has held preliminary meetings with
the state about possibly abandoning the troubled facility.
   ``We don't have any blinders on. We are willing to consider
anything,'' Robert Harrison, president of Public Service Co. of New
Hampshire said.
   But Harrison declined to speculate about the likelihood that
Seabrook would be scrapped, and said he still believes the $5.4
billion reactor will be licensed. The plant was completed in 1986
but left idle because it has not received a federal operating
license.
   Harrison disclosed the abandonment talks when asked if his
company would consider a deal similar to one worked out between the
state of New York and Long Island Lighting Co. involving the
Shoreham nuclear plant.
   A recent agreement in principle calls for LILCO to abandon the
plant in return for multibillion-dollar tax breaks, permission to
continue operating as a private company and a schedule of rate
increases.
