<1ST_LINE>u f BC-Britain-Trade 1stLd-Writethru f0036 06-27 0453</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Britain-Trade, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0036,0464</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Trade Deficit Soars To Record Level In May</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 2nd graf pvs, The pound ..., with one graf to CORRECT
size of dollar's decline. Picks up 3rd graf pvs, The seasonaly ...</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Britain's merchandise trade deficit soared to a
record 1.705 billion pounds, or $2.9 billion, in May, with imports
running at their highest level since last summer, the government
reported Monday.
   The pound fell sharply on the news, losing about 1 cent against
the dollar to stand at $1.7043. Share prices on the London Stock
Exchange also took a beating.
   The seasonally adjusted trade deficit compared with a revised
deficit of 1.23 billion pounds, or $2.09 billion, in April and a
deficit of 1.06 billion pounds, or $1.8 billion, in May 1987, the
Department of Trade and Industry said.
   Analysts' forecasts for the merchandise trade gap had ranged
from 900 million, or $1.5 billion dollars, to 1.2 billion pounds,
or $2.04 billion.
   Meanwhile, Britain's current account shortfall in May, which
includes ``invisible trade'' such as services, overseas investment
earnings and official transfer payments, widened to a record 1.205
billion pounds, or $2.05 billion. That compared with a revised
deficit of 728 million pounds, or $1.24 billion, in April and a
deficit of 361 million pounds, or $614 million, in May 1987.
   Market forecasts for the May current account deficit rangd from
450 million pounds, or $765 million, to 800 million pounds, or
$1.36 billion.
   News of the wider-than-expected deficits pushed the pound down
against both the U.S. dollar and the West German Deutsche mark,
despite expectations that a further fall in the pound might prompt
the Bank of England to signal a rise in the British commercial
banks' base lending rate, which stands at 9 percent.
   The pound fell to $1.7043 about 15 minutes after the release of
the trade numbers, dropping from $1.7125 just prior to the
announcement. The pound fell to 3.1065 marks from 3.1230 marks.
   Stock prices also took a tumble. By midday, the Financial
Times-Stock Exchange 100-share index was off around 20 points, or
1.1 percent, at the 1,850 level.
   British exports totaled 6.48 billion pounds, or $11 billion, in
May, down from 6.79 billion pounds, or $11.5 billion, in April and
up from 6.4 billion pounds (10.9 billion dollars) a year ago.
   Imports totaled a record 8.19 billion pounds, or $13.9 billion,
up from a revised 8.02 billion pounds, or $13.6 billion, in April
and up from 7.4 billion pounds, or $12.6 billion, last year.
   The government attributed the 2 percent rise in imports in May
to a high intake of erratic items, particularly precious stones and
aircraft. Imports were at their highest level since August 1987.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880627-0270 </DOCNO>
