<1ST_LINE>u f PM-BoardofTrade Open   06-27 0315</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Board of Trade, Open,0008</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Another dry and searing forecast drove corn and
soybean futures prices up their daily limit in early trading today
on the Chicago Board of Trade.
   Crop-damaging record-high temperatures over the weekend across
much of the Midwest gave way to cooler weather, but scattered
showers brought little relief from the drought, analysts said.
   The extended forecast from the National Weather Service fueled
further buying interest in the corn and soybean pits, calling for
another warming trend this week and no foreseeable rain until
Friday.
   ``It is the weather, it is the lack of rain,'' that continue to
encourage frenzied buying, said Dale Gustafson, an analyst with
Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc.
   Corn for delivery in all months except December advanced the
10-cents-a bushel daily limit; while soybeans moved up the
30-cents-a bushel limit for all months except November.
   In early trading, wheat was 12 cent to 20 cents higher, with the
contract for delivery in July at $4.00\ a bushel; corn was 9{ cents
to 10 cents higher with the July contract at $3.52{ a bushel; oats
were 11 cents to 15 cents higher with the December contract at
3.74\ a bushel; and soybeans were 25 cents to 30 cents higher with
July at $10.59{ a bushel.
   Cattle and hog futures prices were mixed in early trading at the
Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were .25 cent lower to .43 cent higher, with the
contract for delivery in August at 62.55 cents a pound; feeder
cattle were .92 cent lower to .10 cent higher with August at 69.95
cents a pound; hogs were .08 cent to 1.50 cents higher with July at
45 cents a pound; and frozen pork bellies were .35 cent lower to
1.90 cents higher with July at 37.85 cents a pound.
   Cattle futures advanced, hogs were mixed and pork bellies
retreated in trading Friday.
</TEXT>
