<1ST_LINE>r f BC-IBM-Jobs     06-27 0231</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-IBM-Jobs,0239</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>IBM Planning New Job Moves To Lower Costs, Report Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   International Business Machines Corp. declined
to comment Monday on a published report that the leading computer
company plans another major redeployment of its work force to cut
costs.
   The Wall Street Journal, citing what it called unnamed industry
executives, said in Monday editions that the plan would require
several thousand people to change jobs and many of those to move.
It said the plan had yet to receive final approval from senior
management, but might be announced as early as this week.
   IBM, while declining to comment on the report, reaffirmed that
it remains ``fully committed'' to its practice of not laying off
employees.
   IBM just got through a massive redeployment in which 15,000
people worldwide accepted incentives to retire early and thousands
of others were moved to new jobs in 1986 and 1987. IBM eliminated
8,200 staff jobs and 16,000 manufacturing jobs while adding 11,000
jobs in its sales force and 7,700 to programming operations,
spokesman Michael Starks said.
   IBM's worldwide employment fell about 14,000 last year to
389,348 and its U.S. employment fell about 9,000 to 228,000, he
said.
   In spite of the cost-cutting efforts, IBM continues to hire
selectively in technical areas such as engineering, computer
science and programming and marketing areas such as marketing
representatives and systems engineers, Starks said.
</TEXT>
