<1ST_LINE>u f PM-Bonds     06-27 0482</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bonds,0501</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bond Prices Pull Back</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bond prices headed lower in cautious early
trading today, reflecting concern about the dollar and the
direction of interest rates here and abroad.
   The Treasury's 30-year bond was off about { point, or $5 per
$1,000 face amount, by midday. Its yield, which moves inversely to
its price, climbed to 8.92 percent from 8.85 percent late Friday.
   Trading started out on a down note following a drop in U.S. bond
prices overseas, despite the dollar's continued strength.
   Robert Brusca, chief economist for Nikko Securities Co.
International, said bond investors were worried that the dollar's
rise in recent days could be coming to an end, especially amid
reports of central-bank intervention against the U.S. currency.
   ``I think at this point everyone realizes the dollar probably
has an upside that will be limited at some point,'' he said. ``If
the dollar draws back, people don't want to be involved in bonds.''
   A strong dollar is seen as bullish for the credit markets
because it makes dollar-denominated bonds and notes more attractive
to foreigners while lessening the prospects for higher inflation.
   Brusca said bond traders also were concerned today that interest
rates may be on the rise worldwide.
   There is widespread speculation that Britain, West Germany and
Japan might move to push up rates, and that the Federal Reserve
would be forced to reciprocate to remain competitive.
   In addition, the Fed faces the prospect of higher inflation due
to stronger-than-expected growth in the U.S. economy. Inflation
erodes the value of fixed-income securities.
   By midday in the secondary market for Treasury bonds, prices of
short-term governments declined [ point, intermediate maturities
fell between [ point and { point and long-term issues were down
around { point, according to figures provided by Telerate Inc., a
business-information service.
   The movement of a point is equivalent to a change of $10 in the
price of a bond with a $1,000 face value.
   The Merrill Lynch Daily Treasury Index, which measures price
movements on all outstanding Treasury issues with maturities of a
year or longer, fell 0.30 to 109.88. The Shearson Lehman Hutton
Daily Treasury Bond Index, which makes a similar measurement, stood
at 1,150.24, down 2.95.
   In corporate trading, industrials lost \ point and utilities
were off [ point in light trading, according to the investment firm
of Salomon Brothers Inc.
   Moody's Investment Grade Corporate Bond Index, which measures
price movements on 80 corporate bonds with maturities of five years
or longer, fell 0.38 to 283.81.
   Yields on three-month Treasury bills were up 5 basis points to
6.53 percent. A basis point is one-hundredth of a percentage point.
Six-month bills rose 2 basis points to 6.77 percent and one-year
bills were up 4 basis points at 7.01 percent.
   The federal funds rate, the interest on overnight loans between
banks, traded at 7 9-16 percent, unchanged from late Friday.
