<FILEID>AP-NR-06-27-88 1332EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f PM-DiabloCanyon     06-27 0567</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Diablo Canyon,0584</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Proposed Settlement In $5.8 Billion Nuke Plant Rate Case</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About $2 billion in design and construction
costs of the Diablo Canyon nuclear power plant would be paid by
utility shareholders under a settlement proposed today by the
operating company and state officials.
   The settlement also would increase electricity rates for Pacific
Gas & Electric Co. customers 1.6 percent, effective Friday, and 1.3
percent on Jan. 1 each of the next three years.
   Rates in future years would be based on how well the plant
operates, under a system of ``performance-based pricing'' that has
never been used for a major power plant in California. Usually,
utilities are allowed to charge rates based on how much of their
construction costs were found to be reasonable.
   The settlement was announced by PG&E, the staff of the
California Public Utilities Commission and state Attorney General
John Van de Kamp. It is subject to approval by the full commission.
   The company said it would take a one-time charge of $500 million
and reduce cash dividends to help absorb the cost of Diablo Canyon.
   The plant, located near an earthquake fault on the San Luis
Obispo coast, originally was to begin operating in the mid-1970s.
But design errors, discovery of the magnitude of the earthquake
fault, and federal licensing problems delayed operation by about a
decade and multiplied the cost 13-fold.
   Last year, the utility commission's Division of Ratepayer
Advocates recommended the utility not be allowed to collect $4.4
billion of the plant's original $5.5 billion costs by raising
rates. Additions to the plant since have pushed the total cost to
$5.8 billion.
   Under today's settlement, PG&E would face no specific
disallowance.
   However, the $500 million charge is expected to virtually
eliminate the company's 1988 earnings after taxes, and the company
will have to reduce its cash dividend from $1.92 per share to a new
annualized rate of $1.40 per share.
   Under the ``performance-based'' arrangement, if Diablo Canyon
operates as well as the average large U.S. nuclear plant, about
$2.1 billion of the construction cost will be charged to
shareholders, and customers would pay the rest, Van de Kamp said.
   The more efficiently the plant operates, the more of the cost
customers would pay; on the other hand, they would pay less for
other fuels that PG&E would have to use when the plant was shut
down.
   PG&E officials said the settlement means customers will
initially pay about 25 percent less for power from Diablo Canyon
than if the company had gotten permission to fully recover the
plant's costs.
   The company said rates will increase ``only by about 5 percent''
under the proposed settlement.
   A public hearing on the settlement is scheduled for Wednesday.
The agreement is subject to approval by the Public Utilities
Commission, whose members were not part of the negotiations.
   Bill Ahern, director of the utility commission's Division of
Ratepayer Advocates, hailed the proposed settlement as ``a
tremendously good deal for PG&E's customers.
   ``It provides at least $2 billion in customer savings over the
next few years, and it shifts the financial risks of runaway
nuclear plant costs and poor plant operation from the customers to
PG&E's stockholders,'' he said.
   In a letter to shareholders, PG&E's chairman and chief executive
officer, Richard A. Clarke, said the settlement provided ``the best
alternative for shareholders, including the potential for
substantial earnings growth over time.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
