<2ND_LINE>BC-Britain-Stocks, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0033,0274</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>London Shares Close Lower</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Rewrites thruout to UPDATE with closing figures. No pickup</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices skidded lower Monday on the London
Stock Exchange following the release of a dismal trade deficit
report for May.
   The Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-share index closed 29.8
points, or 1.6 percent, lower at 1,841.5.
   Trading volume was a modest 390.7 million shares, compared with
Friday's 589.0 million shares.
   Dealers said there was severe disappointment that Britain's
merchandise trade gap soared to a record 1.705 billion pounds, or
$2.9 billion, in May, with imports running at their highest level
since last summer.
   Analysts had predicted the trade gap would range from 900
million pounds, or $1.5 billion, to 1.2 billion pounds, or $2.04
billion.
   The pound plummeted 4 cents against the dollar on the news,
ending at $1.7030.
   The government report was ``really ghastly and beyond even the
worst expectations,'' said Glenn Davies, an economist at
CL-Alexanders Laing Cruickshank Ltd.
   ``The problem for equities is that the only option at this
moment available to the government to curtail domestic demand is to
raise base (interest) rates,'' Davies said.
   A dealer said the figures were so bad that they ``beg for severe
measures and it's only a question of how quickly and by how much
the government will put up interest rates.''
   Several market watchers predicted a half percentage-point rise
to 9.5 percent in the British commercial banks' base lending rate
as soon as Tuesday, with another half-point hike sometime during
the week if the British currency does not show signs of recovery.
</TEXT>
