<1ST_LINE>u f BC-BoardofTrade Close   06-27 0214</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Board of Trade, Close,0224</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Corn and soybean futures prices surged up their
daily limits Monday at the Chicago Board of Trade in a
drought-driven rally fueled by another hot and dry forecast.
   ``They opened limit up, they traded limit up, they closed limit
up,'' said Cathy Leow, a New York-based grains analyst with Thomson
McKinnon Securities Inc.
   ``We're trading forecasts,'' she said. ``While the weekend was
dry ... basically we're looking at dryness through the rest of the
week'' across the major growing regions.
   The buying mania was further fueled by a USDA crop-rating report
to be released late Monday, which was expected to show continued
deterioration of the nation's corn and soybean crops, she said.
   Corn for delivery in all months advanced the 10-cents-a bushel
daily limit; while soybeans moved up the 30-cents-a bushel limit
for all months except November 1989.
   At the close, wheat was 12 cents to 20 cents higher with the
contract for delivery in July at $4 a bushel; corn was 10 cents
higher across the board, with the July contract at $3.52{ a bushel;
oats were 15 cents higher across the board, with September at $3.79
a bushel; and soybeans were 27 cents to 30 cents higher with July
at $10.59{ a bushel.
