<FILEID>AP-NR-06-27-88 2014EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Earns-Pillsbury     06-27 0429</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Earns-Pillsbury,0446</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Posts Rise in 4th-Qtr Profit, Decline for Year</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pillsbury Co. said Monday its fourth-quarter
profit rose 51 percent, but its earnings for all of fiscal 1988
fell 62 percent compared with a year earlier because of a huge
restructuring charge.
   Earnings for the three months ended May 31 rose to $47.8
million, or 56 cents a share, from $31.6 million, or 37 cents a
share a year earlier. Sales in the fourth quarter rose 1 percent to
$1.55 billion from $1.53 billion.
   For the full year, net earnings fell to $69.3 million, or 81
cents a share, compared with $181.9 million, or $2.10 a share, in
fiscal 1987.
   Annual sales rose slightly to $6.19 billion from $6.13 billion.
   The restructuring reduced earnings for the full year by $140.9
million, or $1.64 per share, but none of it was booked in the
fourth quarter.
   ``Periodically, every company must make the necessary changes to
re-establish itself in the marketplace,'' William H. Spoor,
Pillsbury's chairman and chief executive officer, said in a
statement. ``We have now entered fiscal 1989 with direction,
confidence and discipline.''
   The restructuring charge covered the sale of the Godfather's
Pizza, Quik Wok, Bay Street and Key West Grill restaurant chains,
and 30 Steak and Ale and Bennigan's restaurants. It also covered a
writedown of assets at Burger King, the consolidation of several
food manufacturing plants and a reduction in administrative
personnel throughout the company.
   For fiscal 1988, the company's foods division posted a 6 percent
sales gain to $3.56 billion on a 1 percent increase in unit volume.
Operating profit rose 6 percent to $280.5 million.
   Excellent performances were turned in by the refrigerated dough,
ice cream, international and industrial divisions, Spoor said. But
he said weaknesses in pizza and seafood held back profit growth.
   In the fourth quarter, food sales rose 9 percent to $904.6
million and unit sales rose 5 percent, but operating profit slipped
2 percent to $51.2 million.
   In the restaurant division, sales fell 5 percent for the year to
$2.63 billion and operating profit fell 8 percent to $217.2 million.
   Spoor attributed the decline to flat sales at individual units
and to a drop in sales at the company's restaurant supply
subsidiary.
   In the fourth quarter, Pillsbury's restaurant sales declined 8
percent to $649 million and operating profit declined 10 percent to
$65 million.
   The decline was attributed to a decline in its restauarnt supply
subsidiary and at its full-service restaurants where profit was off
sharply because of the expense of new menus, training and
additional staffing.
</TEXT>
