<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Germany-Texaco     06-27 0285</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Germany-Texaco,0298</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cartel Office Approves Sale of Texaco Subsidiary to West German
Utility</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GIRARD C. STEICHEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BONN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The West German government said Monday
it has approved the sale of Texaco Inc.'s West German subsidiary to
the utility Rheinisch-Westphaelische Elektrizitaetswerk AG.
   The Federal Cartel Office determined that RWE ``would not secure
a controlling monopoly of the market with the purchase,'' said
Hubertus Schoen, a spokesman for the office.
   RWE, West Germany's largest utility and its eighth-largest
corporation, is active in the production and supply of electricity,
coal mining and the petroleum and chemicals businesses.
   Texaco announced June 6 it had agreed to sell its West German
subsidiary Deutsche Texaco AG to RWE for $1.23 billion as part of
the U.S. company's $5 billion restructuring plan. The sale was
subject to West German government approval.
   Schoen also said the office would not stand in the way of a
proposal to allow Norway's state oil company, Stat-oil, to have a
stake in the new RWE unit.
   RWE officials say an association with Stat-oil would boost RWE's
refining sector earnings. Stat-oil could supply crude oil to the
West German market and also use its refineries to supply that
market with oil products, officials said.
   The officials said the company will include the Texaco
subsidiary into a newly-formed unit, RWE Mineral Oil and Chemical
Corp.
   Deutsche Texaco is active in all phases of the oil business,
from exploration and production to petrochemicals. It owns two
refineries, capable of producing 140,000 barrels daily, and holds a
10.2 percent share of the West German retail gasoline market, with
about 1,900 Texaco-branded retail outlets throughtout the country.
   Deutsche Texaco currently employs about 4,200 workers.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
