<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Dollar-Gold     06-27 0589</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dollar-Gold,0608</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Rises To Eight-Month High; Gold Mixed</HEAD>
<HEAD>Precede LONDON-BC</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar soared Monday to its highest point
since last October against some major currencies, but reports of
dollar-selling by the U.S. central bank knocked it off the day's
highs.
   Gold prices were mixed. Republic National Bank of New York
quoted gold at a bid of $442.60 a troy ounce as of 4 p.m. EDT, down
40 cents from late Friday.
   Traders said reports of intervention by the Federal Reserve had
limited effect because there was no firm evidence the Fed actually
had sold dollars, at least in large amounts.
   The dollar's rapid ascent _ it has climbed roughly 4 percent
against the Japanese yen and the West German mark in the past week
_ left traders wondering whether the rise could continue.
   ``I don't know what will stop it. We'd have to have a nasty
surprise,'' said Francoise Soars-Kemp, treasury vice president for
Credit Suisse in New York. But she also said, ``The market is
likely to turn tail at any moment if it gets upset. I can't say
with any confidence that the dollar is firmly on its way back up.''
   Traders said corporate buying bolstered the dollar Monday.
   ``All the multinationals who basically missed out on buying
dollars came in,'' said Peter Wild, senior trader for Bank Julius
Baer & Co. in New York.
   The dollar soared against the British pound on news of a record
British merchandise trade deficit in May. The pound fell to $1.7030
in London from $1.7430 late Friday, its lowest point against the
dollar since October. Later in New York, sterling fell to $1.7025
from $1.7270 late Friday.
   The dollar peaked at 1.8300 West German marks in Europe, but
fell back on the reports of Fed intervention to finish at 1.8185
marks, up from 1.8010 on Friday and its highest point since
October. Later in New York the dollar closed at 1.8216 marks, up
from 1.8155 Friday but off from its highs of the session.
   Against the Japanese yen, the dollar rose 2 yen to a closing
131.70 in Tokyo, its highest point since December. Later in London,
the dollar was quoted at 130.93 yen. At the end of the trading day
in New York, the dollar closed at 131.14 yen, up from 130.53 late
Friday.
   Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with late Friday's
rates, included: 1.5078 Swiss francs, up from 1.5030; 1.2063
Canadian dollars, up from 1.2033; 6.1478 French francs, up from
6.1110; and 1,351.00 Italian lire, up from 1,330.37 late Friday.
   Late dollar rates in Europe, compared with late Friday's rates,
included: 1.5050 Swiss francs, up from 1.4945; 6.1385 French
francs, up from 6.0635; 2.0460 Dutch guilders, up from 2.0305;
1,353.48 Italian lire, up from 1,330.37; and 1.2075 Canadian
dollars, up from 1.2050.
   Gold bullion fell in Hong Kong by $1.55 a troy ounce to close at
a bid of $444.14.
   Later in London, gold fell to a late bid of $441.50 a troy ounce
from Friday's $442.90. In Zurich, gold closed at a bid of $443.00,
compared with $442.90 late Friday.
   Gold bullion for current delivery closed unchanged at $443 a
troy ounce on the Commodity Exchange in New York.
   Silver bullion prices were unchanged on the London market where
the metal traded at a late bid of $6.84 a troy ounce. On New York's
Comex, silver bullion for current delivery rose to $6.936 a troy
ounce from $6.800 an ounce late Friday.
</TEXT>
