<FILEID>AP-NR-06-27-88 2319EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-PanasonicTVs     06-27 0357</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Panasonic TVs,0367</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>First Shipment of 3,000 U.S.-Built TVs Shipped to Japan</HEAD>
<HEAD>Laserphoto</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FRANKLIN PARK, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The first shipment to Japan of 5,000
Panasonic television sets built at a suburban Chicago left Monday
amid fanfare and predictions that it would be the first of many.
   ``Hopefully, this is just a small beginning to what ultimately
will lead to a more balanced trading situation between all
countries of the world _ but especially the United States and
Japan,'' said Richard Kraft, president of Matsushita Industrial
Co., a subsidiary of the Japanese consumer giant Matsushita, which
markets some of its products under the Panasonic brand name.
   The 27-inch color television sets were part of an initial order
of 5,000 sets. While U.S.-made materials account for about 70
percent of each set, Kraft noted the televisions are ``virtually
unusuable in this country'' because the settings, the power supply
and the frequencies are adapted for foreign use.
   ``Japan is a different market, and these sets today represent an
honest attempt to market and sell a product based on conditions
there ... not just send over whatever we build,'' he added.
   ``With this kind of thinking and this kind of product, we can
make genuine inroads,'' said Kraft.
   He said Matsushita decided to build the sets in Franklin Park
because of savings of about 10 percent and the availability of
American craftsmen to design and build the cabinets out of U.S.
hardwoods.
   Kraft said he could not estimate what the set would cost in
Japan, but a comparable product for the U.S. market would range
between $1,500 and $2,000.
   State Department of Commerce spokesman Wally Biermann said
exports from Illinois to Japan were up 46 percent for the first
four months of this year compared to last.
   ``These are not just gestures of goodwill, but hard-core
economic decisions,'' Paul O'Connor, another state Commerce
Department spokesman said. ``If the dollar remains weak against the
yen, you'll see more and more of this.''
   Gov. James R. Thompson joined executives and 800 workers for a
brief ceremony at the plant, which manufactures more than one
million sets for the North American market.
</TEXT>
