<1ST_LINE>u f AM-CommodityRdp 1stLd-Writethru   06-27 0734</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Commodity Rdp, 1st Ld-Writethru,0757</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Drought Sends Corn, Beans Skyrocketing; Hits Other Markets, Too</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: adds one graf after 5th graf pvs to UPDATE with crop report,
picksup 6th graf pvs: Corn for ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By LINDSEY TANNER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Corn and soybean futures prices jumped their daily limits higher
Monday at the Chicago Board of Trade following another hot, dry
forecast and fears of further crop damage from the midwestern
drought.
   The drought-related buying spree spilled onto other exchanges:
cotton futures prices soared while cattle and hog prices rallied
sharply on drought-related speculation.
   In other markets, silver surged while gold was mixed and energy
prices declined.
   ``We're trading forecasts,'' said Cathy Leow, a New York-based
grains analyst with Thomson McKinnon Securities Inc. ``While the
weekend was dry...basically we're looking at dryness through the
rest of the week'' across the major growing regions.
   BOT traders also were buying in anticipation of a late-Monday
USDA report expected to show continued deterioration of the
nation's corn and bean crops, she said.
   The USDA weekly crop condition report, issued after the close of
trading, showed deterioration in all states in the major growing
regions, ``with the corn and soybean crops in mostly fair to poor
condition,'' Ms. Leow said,
   Corn for delivery in all months advanced the 10-cents-a bushel
daily limit; and soybeans moved up the 30-cents-a bushel limit for
all months.
   Wheat settled 14{ cents to 20 cents higher with the contract for
delivery in July at $4{ a bushel; corn was 10 cents higher across
the board, with the July contract at $3.52{ a bushel; oats were 15
cents higher across the board, with September at $3.78 a bushel;
and soybeans settled 30 cents higher across the board with July at
$10.59{ a bushel.
   Cotton prices surged in trading at the New York Cotton Exchange,
with deferred months advancing the 2-cents-a-pound daily limit in
sympathy with skyrocketing grains prices, said Ed Whitten, a cotten
specialist with New York-based Balfour Maclaine Corp.
   Cotton settled .95 cent to 2.70 cents higher for the nearby July
contract, which has no daily limit. The July contract was at 68.80
cents a pound.
   Weekend rain in some parts of the cotton belt eased dry
conditions but rain still was needed in the central belt and
southeast, he said. Cotton doesn't require as much moisture as
soybeans and grains, but still was being hurt by the drought,
Whitten said.
   Cattle and hog futures prices advanced sharply in trading at the
Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Expectations of a long-term drop in supplies sparked a buying
wave that pushed prices up the 1.50 cents-a-pound daily limit in
deferred contracts for cattle and hogs, and up the 2 cents limit in
pork bellies, said Philip Stanley, an analyst in Chicago with
Thomson McKinnon Securities.
   ``There is assumption that there is liquidation going on right
now in the breeding herd'' as the drought damages feed crops,
Stanley said. That means a short-term influx of beef and pork but
an anticipated tightening of supplies down the road, he said.
   Live cattle settled 1.35 cents to 1.50 cents higher, with the
contract for delivery in August at 64.15 cents a pound; feeder
cattle were .70 cent to 1.23 cents higher with the August contract
at 71.55 cents a pound; live hogs were 1.28 cents to 1.50 cents
higher, with July at 46.20 cents a pound; and frozen pork bellies
were .85 cent to 2 cents higher with July at 39.05 cents a pound.
   Gold futures prices were mixed while silver rallied sharply in
trading at the New York Commodity Exchange.
   Bette Raptopoulos, an analyst with Prudential-Bache Securities
Inc. in New York, said silver was supported by inflationary
speculation stemming from the rally in soybeans and grains, while
gold was depressed by the recent strength of the U.S. dollar.
   Gold settled 10 cents lower to 10 cents higher with the contract
for delivery in June at $443 a troy ounce; silver was 13 cents to
13.6 cents higher with June at $6.936 a troy ounce.
   Energy futures prices retreated at the New York Mercantile
Exchange.
   Crude oil settled 11 cents to 19 cents lower with the contract
for delivery in August at $15.86 a barrel; heating oil was .18 cent
to .55 cent lower with July at 42.59 cents a gallon; unleaded
gasoline settled .38 cent lower to .14 cent higher with July at
51.05 cents a gallon.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
