<2ND_LINE>AM-Allegheny International,0292</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Management Says It Retains Board Majority In Proxy Fight</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Allegheny International Inc. claimed Monday
its management retained control of the 13-member board of directors
in a proxy contest against dissident shareholders, who apparently
won five of seven seats up for election.
   Management based its claim on preliminary results of a June 20
vote released by Manufacturers Hanover Trust Co., which judged the
election. Final results are expected July 5.
   The results claimed by management followed last week's
announcement by Speer Leeds claiming that, based on its analysis,
the dissidents had won five seats, with two others still in doubt.
   ``Now we can proceed with business as usual,'' Chairman Oliver
S. Travers said. ``Our first priority is a successful
reorganization to emerge from Chapter 11 protection as soon as
possible.''
   The dissidents, led by the New York brokerage firm Speer, Leeds
& Kellogg, attempted to win four of seven open board seats at the
shareholders meeting. In addition, Allegheny International's
failure to pay dividends gave the holders of two classes of
preferred stock the right to place their nominees in three seats.
   Two management nominees, Travers and Morris W. Offit, apparently
won election, giving management control of eight seats. The Speer,
Leads & Kellogg group gained five seats, including two elected by
common shareholders and three nominees to uncontested seats.
   ``The results of the election from the prelminary tally firm
management's commitment to continue running the compnay in the best
interests of all the company's constituencies, including all
classes of equity,'' Travers said.
   The dissidents claimed they could reorganize the troubled
consumer products company under a plan that would improve the
market value of the company's stock.
</TEXT>
