<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Macmillan-Bass     06-27 0330</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Macmillan-Bass,0343</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Macmillan Reaffirms Rejection of Bass Takeover Overtures</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Macmillan Inc. reaffirmed Monday its earlier
rejection of a $1.9 billion takeover proposal from a group led by
Texas investor Robert Bass.
   The publishing and information services giant said a special
committee of its board had also reaffirmed that the company is not
for sale.
   Macmillan and the Robert M. Bass Group are scheduled to square
off Wednesday in a Delaware Chancery Court over whether Macmillan
will be allowed to proceed with a restructuring plan that it
offered earlier this month.
   In trading on the New York Stock Exchange, Macmillan slipped 25
cents a share to $74.50.
   Macmillan's plan includes paying a special dividend of $52.35 a
share in cash and splitting the company into two parts _ publishing
and information services.
   The plan had been proposed after the Bass group said it wanted
to discuss a takoever of the entire company at $64 a share.
   It subsequently boosted its offer to $73 a share in cash or,
alternatively, a restructuring identical to what Macmillan proposed
except that it included a higher dividend of $58 a share.
   In its statement on Monday, Macmillan said its special committee
felt that the Bass group's plan does not contribute any added value
to the operation of Macmillan ``as they have no experience or
business know-how in the publishing and information fields.''
   Macmillan said its restructuring plan ``will maintain the
tradition of editorial independence and integrity which has served
the public for 145 years and will insure the continued quality of
Macmillan's teaching and information products.''
   The court hearing, which was to be held Monday in Delaware
Chancery Court before Vice Chancellor Jack B. Jacobs, has been
resceduled for 2 p.m. EDT Wednesday, a spokesman for the court said.
   Earlier this month Jacobs granted Bass's request for a temporary
injunction blocking the restructuring. At Wednesday's hearing,
Jacobs will hear arguments concerning a preliminary injunction,
which would void the proposed restructuring.
</TEXT>
