<DOCNO> AP880627-0301 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-27-88 2132EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-CropForecast     06-27 0471</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Crop Forecast,0483</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>USDA To Make Special Crop Forecast Because of Drought</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: also on general news wires.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A special crop production forecast will be
issued in two weeks to reflect the drought that is shriveling corn,
wheat and other harvest prospects in much of the nation, a senior
Agriculture Department official said Monday.
   The special forecast will be issued in USDA's regular crop
report on July 12 and will include new figures adjusted for damage
done by this year's heat and drought, said Assistant Secretary Ewen
M. Wilson, who oversees the department's economic and statistical
services.
   Under normal conditions, the July crop report would include
updated production and yield-per-acre estimates for winter wheat,
which is now being harvested across the nation's midsection.
Similar field estimates for corn, spring wheat, soybeans, cotton
and other fall-harvested crops are not scheduled until August.
   That has not changed. The August crop report will still be the
first big-scale estimate of U.S. crops, Wilson said.
   But the July 12 report will include freshly revised
``projections'' of corn and other fall crops based on the latest
drought and acreage information, he said. The projections now being
used began in May, based on past trends and other assumptions that
no longer apply.
   Wilson, in an interview, disclosed that the 1988-89 projections
based on the trendlines of past years would be wrong and that ``we
would be way off the right numbers'' for this year's harvests.
   ``We're going to move away from that trend-yield estimate and
make some adjustments based on what we know about crop
conditions,'' he said. ``We won't be doing a (field) survey because
it's too early in the season. But we'll do some analysis which will
move us off that trend-line yield in order to reflect the impact of
the drought.''
   Wilson said the special project to come up with better figures
for harvest prospects and anticipated demand through the 1988-89
marketing season was not unique and that USDA had done it before.
   Asked if USDA economists and statisticians weren't sticking
their necks out regarding drought losses, Wilson said, ``I think
we're in a year where, if they put out a trend-line projection,
they would be sticking their necks out even more, because, clearly,
no one believes the trend yield is going to the the actual yield
this year. It's reflecting reality.''
   Earlier this month, when the winter wheat harvest was updated,
the supply-and-demand analysis _ based on the trend lines described
by Wilson _ included projections showing that this fall's corn
harvest would be around 7.3 billion bushels, an increase from 7.06
billion bushels harvested in 1987.
   Soybean production, using the trend-line method, was projected
on June 9 at 1.88 billion bushels, just slightly less than the 1.9
billion bushels produced last year.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880627-0302 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-27-88 2133EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Lead-Housewares     06-27 0577</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Lead-Housewares,0595</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Americans Warned of Poisoning Danger From Imported Ceramic Ware</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: also on general news wires.</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   By JERRY ESTILL=
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Americans should be more aware of the
potential of lead poisoning from imported ceramic ware that does
not meet U.S. standards, the head of the Food and Drug
Administration told Congress on Monday.
   Although the agency has stepped up its spot checks in recent
years, FDA Commissioner Frank E. Young acknowledged that it will
never be able to check each shipment. He noted that that it lacks
authority to inspect foreign plants where the products originate.
   Even if the FDA budget was expanded to allow it to make more
spot checks of imports and if the agency was authorized to make
spot checks in foreign plants, Young pointed out that much of the
glazed pottery coming into the United States is purchased abroad by
tourists and military personnel, often from small village
operations.
   Still more, he said, comes in from Mexico ``as either small,
informal entries, as personal belongings of members of the
Mexican-American community living along the border, or as gifts or
individual pieces purchased by U.S. tourists.''
   ``The thousands of trucks and automobiles crossing the border
simply cannot be effectively inspected or their cargos tested for
lead,'' said Young.
   He added that a new program under which the FDA has contracted
with state officials in Colorado and New Mexico to sample Mexican
dinnerware from local retailers has revealed that more than 10
percent of the items sampled have leached excess levels of lead.
   The FDA ordered 20 recalls of ceramic ware in fiscal 1987,
compared with nine in the preceeding five years. Of the 27 recalls,
only one lot was manufactured in the United States.
   Rep. Ron Wyden, D-Ore., who chaired the hearing of the oversight
and investigations panel of the House Energy and Commerce
Committee, said there are ``serious deficiencies'' in the FDA's
efforts to control ceramic ware.
   Background material distributed by the committee said the FDA,
for example, has only one inspector to police the entire port of
Houston.
   However, Wyden also acknowledged that a major part of the
hearing he organized was educational.
   ``In view of the widespread lack of knowledge about the nature
and extent of the risks posed by defective ceramicware and
glassware, one of the major purposes of today's hearing is to
inform the public about such risks,'' he said. ``Without adequate
education about this problem, many individuals will continue to
purchase dangerous items for food service.''
   Young said there is ``no way to know whether ceramic ware is
defective by visually inspecting it.''
   ``Consumers thus need to be alerted to this potential hidden
danger,'' he said. ``This hearing should help.''
   Officials say the most risky ceramic dinnerware are poorly fired
pitchers, cups and other vessels. They are especially dangerous
when filled with acidic liquids, such as coffee, orange juice or
wine, which can speed the breakdown of the glazes containing lead.
   Potters have used pulverized lead for years to give a sheen and
rich color to ceramic products. Firing the glaze at high enough
temperatures binds the lead to the surface. But inadequate firing
can result in the glazes degrading over time from use and releasing
microscopic particles of lead.
   One of the main problems is that ceramic items labeled for
decorative use only do not have to pass FDA lead-leach standards,
yet sometimes are used for food preparation or serving.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
