share cash.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A sharply divided Supreme Court has ruled that
defense contractors enjoy broad protection from lawsuits when
defective equipment they sell to the government causes death and
injury.
   By a 5-4 vote, the court refused Monday to reinstate a $725,000
award to the family of a Marine helicopter co-pilot who died in a
1983 crash in the Atlantic Ocean near Virginia Beach, Va.
   The dissenting justices denounced the ruling as a
``breathtakingly'' far-reaching grant of immunity to the nation's
defense industry.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Boeing Co. warned Aloha Airlines last fall
that unless serious corrosion on its oldest aircraft was fixed
through a stepped-up repair program the planes might become unsafe,
documents show.
   Nevertheless, according to documents released Monday, Aloha in
early March canceled plans for the speedier maintenance schedule,
less than seven weeks before one of its aging Boeing 737s broke
apart during flight on April 18.
   The documents were released by the National Transportation
Safety Board, which is investigating the accident.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The crash of an Airbus A320 jetliner during a
demonstration flight in France could make potential purchasers of
the plane wary and may be damaging for its manufacturer, some
airline analysts say.
   Sunday's crash of the ultra-modern Air France jet could inflict
``psychological'' damage on the highly touted A320 and prompt
cancelled orders and lost sales. The incident also focuses
attention on the trend toward more technology and fewer pilots,
analysts said Monday.
