<DOCNO> AP880627-0306 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-27-88 2218EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-PlantClosings 1stLd-Writethru f0204 06-27 0501</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Plant Closings, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0204,0514</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Senate Stands Firm on Requiring Advance Notice of Layoffs</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS grafs 5-6 pvs, `The Senate ... the latest,' with 2 grafs
to UPDATE with Senate halting work for the night, Byrd moves to
invoke cloture later in the week; PICKS UP 7th graf pvs bgng, `The
move'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MIKE ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Senate stood firm on requiring companies
to give employees advance notice of large-scale layoffs Monday,
refusing to drop the provision from a bill calling for prior
warning of plant closings.
   ``This is a blueprint for employers who want to disobey the
plant-closing law itself,'' said Sen. Howard M. Metzenbaum, D-Ohio,
in urging the Senate to retain the layoff provision.
   ``Employers would simply lay them off, piece by piece, bit by
bit, until there was nothing left,'' he said.
   The Senate voted 63-32 to table, or kill, a proposal to drop the
layoff provision from the larger plant-closings notification bill.
   The proposal to drop the layoffs provision was the major
amendment offered thus far by critics of the bill. After lawmakers
acted on it, however, they became snarled in debate over further
limiting moves and Majority Leader Robert C. Byrd, D-W.Va., gave up
hope of a final vote Monday.
   Byrd said he still was hoping for a vote Tuesday but, before the
Senate halted work for the night, he took steps to invoke cloture,
or shut off debate, later in the week.
   The move to drop the layoff provision was made by Sen. Nancy
Kassebaum, R-Kan. It would have sharply altered the plant-closings
measure, which until recently was part of the 1,000-page omnibus
trade bill.
   President Reagan vetoed the trade bill May 24, singling out the
plant-closings provision for special criticism. He said it would
hamstring managers attempting to operate their companies at peak
efficiency.
   The plant-closings measure was deleted from the trade bill and
reconstituted as a separate piece of legislation after the Senate
sustained Reagan's veto.
   The bill would require companies with at least 100 employees to
provide advance notice of layoffs involving at least 50 workers as
well as notification of full-scale plant closings.
   Labor unions have had some form of the plant-closings
legislation on their congressional shopping list for 15 years.
   Critics said the bill was too broad and thus bound to set off
lawsuits and squabbles. They said dropping the layoff provision
represented one way to impose some limits.
   ``A layoff of 50 employees at a 10,000-employee manufacturing
plant would not be a plant closing to most people but it is under
terms of this legislation,'' said Sen. Orrin Hatch, R-Utah.
   House Speaker Jim Wright, D-Texas, told reporters Monday morning
that he would call the plant-closings measure for a vote in his
chamber on Wednesday.
   He also said he would seek a House vote Wednesday on the
reconstituted trade bill, which has been shorn not only of the
plant-closings provision but of curbs on export of Alaska oil and
refined petroleum products.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
